81\u20131995\n* Fantastic Fountains 1981\u20131992\n* [[Ferris wheel]] 1985\u20131986\n* [[Gravitron]] 1990\u20131992\n* Magic Carpet 1984\u20131985\n* Magic Show 1980\u20131986\n* [[Miniature Golf]] 1980\u20131994\n* Mississippi Showboat 1985\u20131996\n* [[Model Railway]] 1957\u20131992\n* Motor Museum 1987\u20131992\n* [[Nickelodeon: Outta Control]] 1997\u20131998\n* Nina's Science Lab 2014-2018\n* Octopus 1984\u20131991\n* Old MacDonald's Singing Barn 1995-2013\n* Old MacDonald's Tractor Ride 1995-2013\n* Park Railway ({{Track gauge|2ft|lk=on|disp=or}} [[Narrow gauge railway|narrow gauge]])<ref>{{cite web|url=http://altontowersmemories.net/page8.htm|title=Alton Towers Memories - Park Railway}}</ref> 1953\u20131996\n* Paddling Pool 1963\u20131992\n* Peter Rabbit and Friends on Ice 1994\u20132005\n* [[Planetarium]] 1972\u20131987\n* Rowing Boats 1923\u20131996\n* [[Sea Lions]] 1957\u20131990\n* Space Boat 1983\n* Spider 1986\u20131991\n* Splash Cats 1966\u20131996\n* Splash Karts 2004\u20132007\n* Sun Liner Trains 1984\u20131986\n* Swan Boats 1987\u20132003\n* Tea Cup Ride 1986-2007\n* Thunderbirds 1982\u20131990\n* Towers Express 1974\u20131983\n* Tri-Star 1989\u20131992\n* Turbo Star 1984\u20131989\n* [[Tweenies]] Playground 2003\u20132005\n* Vintage Cars 1983\u20132005\n* Wobble World 2009-2015\n* 3D Cinema 1981\u20132004\n* 1001 Nights 1985\u20131994\n{{div col end}}\n\n== Food facilities ==\n{{div col|colwidth=20em}}\n* Theme Park\n** Towers Street: [[Costa Coffee]], Towers Street Hot Dogs, Towers Street Doughnuts, Treats, \n** CBeebies Land: Little Explores Lunch Box, Big Fun Showtime Snack box \n** X-Sector: Just Chicken, Donut Factory, Rehydrator\n** Cloud Cuckoo Land: \n** The World of David Walliams: [[Costa Coffee]]\n** The Towers: Burger Kitchen, Archway, Front Lawns\n** Dark Forest: Woodcutters Bar and Grill, Eastern Express, Tormented Treats\n** Forbidden Valley: [[Rollercoaster Restaurant]], [[Costa Coffee]], Nemices Donuts, Forbidden Valley Refresh\n** Gloomy Wood: Nitrogenie, Gloomy Wood Kiosk\n** Katanga Canyon: Explorers Pizza and Pasta Buffet, Katanga Kiosk\n** Mutiny Bay: Burger Kitchen, [[Costa Coffee]], Welcome Inn, Eastern Express, Courtyard Hot Dogs/Wraps/Waffles, Mutiny Bay Doughnuts, Pirates Kiosk\n* Accommodation\n** Alton Towers Hotel: Secret Garden Restaurant, [[Costa Coffee]], Dragons Bar, Captains Bar\n** Alton Towers Conference Centre: Algenon's Bar, Sir Algenon's Grill (Only open in peak times)\n** Splash Landings Hotel: Flambos Jambo, Ma Garrita's Bar, [[Costa Coffee]], Burger Cove\n** Enchanted Village: Crooked Spoon\n** CBeebies Land Hotel: The Windmill Restaurant\n** Stargazing Pods: Stargazing Bar\n* Midway Attractions\n** Alton Towers Waterpark: The Cave, Ice Cream Shack\n** Tree Top Quest: The Crooked Teaspoon\n\n{{div col end}}\n\n=== Past food facilities ===\nAlton Towers previously had leases with High Street outlets, which have since been replaced by in-house brands such as Explorers Pizza & Pasta, Just Chicken and Burger Kitchen.\n* [[McDonald's]] (1998-2007)\n* [[Burger King]] (2008-2012)\n* [[Pizza Hut]] (1998-2008)\n* [[KFC]] (1998-2011)\n* Fried Chicken Co. (2011-2018)\n* Forest Feasts (2010-2016)\n* Towers Street Bar and Grill (1985-2016)\n\n== Alton Towers Theme Park ==\n\nThe Alton Towers Theme Park is divided into areas: Towers Street, Mutiny Bay, Katanga Canyon, Gloomy Wood, Forbidden Valley, Dark Forest, The Gardens, The Towers, The World of David Walliams, X-Sector and CBeebies Land. The SkyRide cable car system travels between Towers Street, Forbidden Valley, and the Towers and takes in views of the gardens.\n\nThe park's maximum capacity at any one time is set at 28,000 guests.<ref>{{cite web|last=Machnik |first=Stef |url=http://www.thisisstaffordshire.co.uk/Park-Pink-pop-success/story-12555854-detail/story.html |title=ALTON Towers says it has not ruled out holding more music concerts after successfully playing host to pop superstar Pink. |publisher=This is Staffordshire |date=28 June 2010 |accessdate=9 April 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.birminghampost.co.uk/news/local-news/alton-towers-turns-islam-gay-3980196|title=Alton Towers turns to Islam and gay markets|date=2 July 2006|work=Birmingham Post}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metro.co.uk/news/821589-rides-evacuated-after-alton-towers-power-cut |title=Rides evacuated after Alton Towers power cut &#124; Metro News |work=Metro|location=UK |date=13 April 2010 |accessdate=9 April 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thisisstaffordshire.co.uk/Towers-signs-JLS-24-000-ticket-gig/story-12511564-detail/story.html |title=JLS, McFly and The Saturdays to perform at Alton Towers |publisher=This is Staffordshire |date=16 February 2011 |accessdate=9 April 2013}}</ref> According to the TEA attendance report, the park was estimated to have attracted 2,000,000 people in 2017, a 1% increase on 2016's figure of 1,980,000. This makes Alton Towers Britain's 2nd most visited theme park after [[Legoland Windsor Resort|Legoland Windsor]] and the joint 12th most visited theme park in Europe. The launch of the Thirteen rollercoaster saw the theme park attract 3 million admissions in the 2010 season, a number equalled by the launch of Nemesis in 1994 and Oblivion in 1998. The park's highest attendance to date is 4,195,000, which made it the second most visited Theme Park in Europe in 1999.\n\n===Timeline of park areas===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+ Years areas opened\n|-\n! 1980\n! 1981\n! 1984\n! 1986\n! 1990\n! 1992\n! 1994\n! 1995\n! 1996\n! 1997\n! 1998\n! 1999\n! 2008\n! 2009\n! 2010\n! 2014\n! 2020\n|-\n| colspan=2 rowspan=2|Ingestre Centre\n| colspan=3 rowspan=2|Aqualand\n| colspan=12 style=background:#CCCCFF|Katanga Canyon\n|-\n| colspan=7|Merrie England\n| colspan=5 style=background:#CCCCFF|Mutiny Bay\n|-\n|colspan=2|Springfield Centre\n| colspan=8|Fantasy World\n| colspan=7 style=background:#CCCCFF|X-Sector\n|-\n| colspan=2|Talbot Centre\n| colspan=9|Festival Park\n| colspan=3|UG Land\n| colspan=3 style=background:#CCCCFF|Dark Forest\n|-\n| style=\"background:lightgrey;\"|\n| colspan=5|Talbot Street\n| colspan=3|Land of Make Believe\n| colspan=4|Cred Street\n| colspan=3|Cloud Cuckoo Land\n|colspan=2 style=background:#CCCCFF|The World of David Walliams\n|-\n| colspan=\"3\" style=\"background:lightgrey;\"|\n| colspan=14 style=background:#CCCCFF|Towers Street\n|-\n| colspan=\"3\" rowspan=\"2\" style=\"background:lightgrey;\"|\n| colspan=5 rowspan=2|Kiddies Kingdom\n| colspan=9 style=background:#CCCCFF|Adventure Land\n|-\n| colspan=7|Storybook Land\n| colspan=\"3\" rowspan=\"2\" style=background:#CCCCFF|CBeebies Land\n|-\n| colspan=\"4\" style=\"background:lightgrey;\"|\n||Britannia Farm\n| colspan=2|Safeway Farm\n| colspan=8|Old MacDonalds Farmyard\n|-\n| colspan=\"4\" style=\"background:lightgrey;\"|\n| colspan=2|Thunder Valley\n| colspan=11 style=background:#CCCCFF|Forbidden Valley\n|-\n| colspan=\"5\" style=\"background:lightgrey;\"|\n| colspan=12 style=background:#CCCCFF|Gloomy Wood\n|}\n\n{{Color box|#FFFFFF|border=darkgray}}&nbsp; Previous themed area\n\n{{Color box|#CCCCFF|border=darkgray}}&nbsp; Current themed area<gallery widths=\"150\" heights=\"115\" class=\"center\">\nFile:Alton Towers 01.jpg|Towers Street<br />View of The Towers\nFile:MutinyBay2015.JPG|Mutiny Bay\nFile:Katanga Canyon at Alton Towers.jpg|Katanga Canyon\nFile:Alton towers zombie.jpg|Gloomy Wood<br />Exterior of ''[[Duel (ride)|Duel]]''\nFile:Alton Towers Dark Forest entrance.jpg|Dark Forest\nFile:Cloud Cuckoo Land, Alton Towers - geograph.org.uk - 1464494.jpg|Cloud Cuckoo Land<br />Galloper's Carousel and Twirling Toadstool\nFile:Nemesis at Alton Towers 162 (4756073039).jpg|Forbidden Valley<br />Nemesis theming\nFile:X-Sector, Alton Towers - geograph.org.uk - 1464822.jpg|X-Sector<br />Enterprise and Oblivion\nFile:Sonic Spinball.JPG|The Towers<br />Spinball Whizzer roller-coaster\n</gallery>\n\n=== Towers Street ===\nOpened in 1986, Towers Street is the first area that visitors to the park encounter. Themed loosely as a town street, it leads to views of the gardens and the Towers across the lake in the distance. Along the pathway are the park's jumping frog fountains and a lawn where seasonal events take place. The first ''SkyRide'' station is located nearby, which is a 1048&nbsp;m long [[Aerial lift|cable car]] transport that opened in 1987, and was refurbished 2009. The [[monorail]] moves guests from the three on-site hotels and the water park to the theme park; it opened 1987 and was refurbished in 2008. In this area during the hour before the park's daily closure, departing guests are entertained by three people wearing police costumes, two of them riding [[Segway]]-like vehicles which play party music and the third standing with an old-fashioned megaphone that is unused, and a man riding a miniature ship while dressed as a sea captain.\n\n=== Katanga Canyon ===\nThemed as an African village; created in 1992 and incorporated existing rapids ride. Rides include the roller coaster [[Runaway Mine Train (Alton Towers)|Runaway Mine Train]] and [[Congo River Rapids (Alton Towers)|Congo River Rapids]]. Both are well-established rides in the park whose ride tracks share a tunnel. Congo River Rapids is a river rapids ride that opened 1986, as The Grand Canyon Rapids, and was refurbished in 1992. A 735 m long wild river rapids ride down the Congo River that lasts six minutes. Runaway Mine Train is a steel sit down powered coaster that reaches a speed of 22&nbsp;mph (36&nbsp;km/h) on a 1000&nbsp;ft long track (305 m) and height of {{convert|36|ft|m|abbr=on}}; height limit 90&nbsp;cm. It was designed by [[John Wardley]] for Tussauds and manufactured by [[Mack Rides]].\n\n=== Gloomy Wood ===\nGloomy Wood serves as the area for the dark ride ''[[Duel (ride)|Duel - The Haunted House Strikes Back!]]'', originally ''The Haunted House''. Opening in 1992, this was originally Europe's largest haunted dark ride, but was significantly altered with interactive laser guns in 2003. Each player's shooting score is recorded on a display in the ride car, as guests shoot targets around the ride.\n\nIn 2007, a themed footpath through the woods was added to the area, named ''Haunted Hollow''. The pathway follows the route formerly used by the park's old scenic railway, linking from Mutiny Bay. ''Haunted Hollow'' includes tombstones, statues and other features, some of which interact with guests using sound effects.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.altontowers.com/rides-and-attractions/fun-rides/haunted-hollow/|title=Haunted Hollow - Theme Park Experience at Alton Towers Resort|website=www.altontowers.com}}</ref> In July 2015, Nitrogenie opened and replaced the old Waffles and Ices, a shop producing ice cream using liquid [[nitrogen]]. Gloomy Wood was suggested by the 2017 park map to be home to the new ''Wicker Man'' wooden coaster, opening 2018. However, the park later stated that the ride was in Mutiny Bay.\n\n=== Forbidden Valley ===\n[[File:Alton Towers Forbidden Valley ride signs.jpg|thumb|Theming and signs in Forbidden Valley]]\nForbidden Valley is set in a '[[post-apocalyptic]]' landscape, with [[standing stones]] and rustic structures populating the 'valley'. A ''SkyRide'' station also serves this area of the park.\n\nThe area's principal attraction is ''[[Nemesis (roller coaster)|Nemesis]]'', opened in 1994. ''Nemesis'' is a steel inverted coaster that reaches a speed of 50&nbsp;mph (81&nbsp;km) with four inversions, set in a rocky quarry over waterfalls. The ride is built down into excavated ground and was designed by Tussauds, primarily [[John Wardley]]. The attraction is themed as an alien creature inhabiting the quarry where the coaster is situated. \n\n''The Blade'' is a Huss Pirate Boat modified with a pendulum blade. It opened in 1980, and was relocated to the area in 1997 from Fantasy World. The Blade currently operates as the only flat ride in Forbidden Valley since the removal of ''[[Ripsaw (Alton Towers)|Ripsaw]]''. However, in October 2019, The Blade was dismantled to be 'Resharpened by the Phalanx' and has been added back to the Alton Towers app hinting it\u2019s return.\n\n[[Galactica (roller coaster)|Galactica]] is a B&M flying coaster, originally opening as ''Air'' in 2002. Air was loosely themed as a peaceful landscape, distanced from the 'apocalyptic' look of Nemesis. Air was redesigned as Galactica in 2016, adopting [[virtual reality]] headsets and a space travel theme. The VR headsets have since been removed due to feedback from customers.<ref name=\"Twitter170320191501\">{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/altontowers/status/1107295909078097923|date=17 March 2019|accessdate=18 March 2019|title=Reply to user @Ev_Jay|quote=Galactica no longer features VR due to guest feedback regarding their experience on the ride.|publisher=Alton Towers official Twitter account}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2016, the '[[Rollercoaster Restaurant]]' opened, offering a dining experience where guests have their food delivered by looping rails. The restaurant is open daily from 10am - 9:30pm; available to guests without theme park admission after the park has closed, except during Scarefest and Fireworks events.\n\n=== Adventure Land ===\nAdventure Land is a small family area featuring ''[[Spinball Whizzer (roller coaster)|Spinball Whizzer]]'';<ref>{{cite web|title=Theme Park|url=https://www.altontowers.com/theme-park/|website=Alton Towers|accessdate=21 April 2017}}</ref> based on a pinball machine in which the car is the ball whizzing around the machine. The ride originally had this name, until 2010 when it was known as ''Sonic Spinball'' until the name change back in 2016 when a contract ended with SEGA after six years. The ride is a Maurer S\u00f6hne spinning roller coaster, in which riders sit in cars that can spin on their base whilst travelling at speed around the track. For the park map, Spinball Whizzer is listed as being in The Towers area.\n\nAdventure Land is named after the adventure play ground which previously sat on the site. The former play area was one of the attractions of a larger area called Kiddies Kingdom. In 1996, Kiddies Kingdom was split into Adventure Land and Storybook Land.<ref>{{cite web |title=Adventure Land |url=https://towersstreet.com/theme-park/area/adventure-land/#areahistory |website=towersstreet.com |accessdate=17 June 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== X-Sector ===\n[[File:Oblivion2015.JPG|thumb|View of Oblivion]]\nX-Sector is themed as a secretive industrial complex, suggested to be subjecting park guests to experimental testing.\n\nThe area currently contains three thrill rides. The steel dive coaster ''[[Oblivion (roller coaster)|Oblivion]]'' which opened in 1998 as \"the world's first vertical drop rollercoaster\", designed by Tussauds and manufactured by [[Bolliger & Mabillard]]. The cars are held over the edge of the drop for three seconds, before diving into a deep tunnel. ''[[The Smiler]]'' is a [[Gerstlauer]] [[Infinity Coaster]] which opened in May 2013 and currently holds the world record for most inversions on a roller coaster at 14.<ref name=\"Uttoxeter Advertiser\"/>  ''Enterprise'' is a standard HUSS [[Enterprise (ride)|Enterprise]] model which opened in 1984, spinning riders 360 degrees and giving the illusion of defying gravity. The area layout was partially altered in 2013 season to accommodate the opening of The Smiler.\n\nPrevious rides in X-Sector include The [[Black Hole (roller coaster)|Black Hole]], which was a Jet Star 2 coaster enclosed in a tent, where The Smiler is located today. [[Boneshaker (Alton Towers)|Energizer]] (later renamed Boneshaker) was a swinging gondola flat ride. It was replaced by [[Submission (Alton Towers)|Submission]] in 2001, a \"Chance Double Inverter\" flat ride, which was itself removed in 2014.\n\n=== Mutiny Bay ===\n[[File:Alton Towers 05.jpg|thumb|Mutiny Bay's pirates]]\nMutiny Bay is a pirate-themed family area, which opened in 2008.<ref name=\"Attractions2009\">{{cite web |url=http://www.iaapa.org/ |title=International Association of Amusement Parks and Attractions |date=January 2009 |publisher=IAAPA |accessdate=28 May 2013}}</ref> the area was a retheme for Merrie England.\n\nAttractions in Mutiny Bay include: ''[[Battle Galleons]]'', an interactive \"Splash Battle\" boat ride, where guests sit in tracked boats while soaking other riders with water cannons. Also in the area is the rocking boat ride, ''Heave Ho''. The park's original teacups ride was re-themed to become ''[[Marauder's Mayhem (Alton Towers)|Marauders Mayhem]]'', with the tea cup cars being redesigned as gunpowder barrels. '' The Flume'' was a [[Mack Rides|Mack]] log flume ride that opened in 1981 and was rethemed in 2004 with a sponsorship from Imperial Leather alongside the bubbleworks at Chessington world of adventure. Upon opening, it was the longest flume ride in the world at {{Convert|886|m}}.<ref name=\"Attractions2009\" /> Late in the 2015 season, the ride and the neighboring tavern closed and were removed in 2016 to make way for the [[Wicker Man (roller coaster)|Wicker Man]] roller coaster and the \"Welcome Inn\" bar which shares the coaster's theme.\n\nIn 2009, a [[Sea Life Centres|Sea Life Centre]] named ''Sharkbait Reef'' opened in the location previously home to the 3-D Cinema.{{Citation needed|reason=Source needed for 3-D Cinema replacement|date=March 2020}} This includes \"touch pools\" for interacting with underwater species and a {{convert|10|m|ft|adj=on}} underwater tunnel.<ref name=\"Sharkbait Reef Info\">{{cite web |title=Sharkbait Reef by SEA LIFE |url=https://www.towerstimes.co.uk/theme-park/mutiny-bay/sharkbait-reef-by-sea-life/ |website=TowersTimes |accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== The World of David Walliams ===\n[[File:Alton Towers - Circuit voitures pour enfants.jpg|thumb|Driving School attraction in Cloud Cuckoo Land]]\nThe World of David Walliams is aimed at younger children aged 7-11, featuring bright colours and fantasy decor. Attractions include ''Raj's Bouncy Bottom Burp'' (the former Frog Hopper) and ''Royal Carousel'' (previously Galloper's Carousel). ''[[Driving School (Alton Towers)|Cuckoo Cars Driving School]]'' allows children to drive miniature electric cars around a themed road layout, featuring visual jokes along the way.<ref>{{cite news | title=Coming soon \u2026 the first 'drive of your life' | publisher=easier.com | date=10 July 2006 | url=http://www.easier.com/view/News/Motoring/Peugeot/article-59601.html | accessdate=13 July 2006}}</ref> A SkyRide station is located nearby Fountain Square, giving access to other areas of the park.\nThe area was previously known as \"Cred Street\" and \"The Land of Make Believe\", with a cartoon-inspired look, mainly featuring ''[[Toyland Tours]]''. Prior to this, it was first built as \"Talbot Street\" in 1981, becoming the park's first themed area, home to the ''[[Around the World in 80 Days (Alton Towers)|Around The World in 80 Days]]'' and ''[[Doom & Sons]]'' dark rides.\n\nOn 21 July 2009, a fire broke out in the Sky Ride station for this area, caused by a faulty vending machine. The station was completely destroyed and didn't reopen until the 2010 season.\n<ref name=\"towerstimes.co.uk\">https://www.towerstimes.co.uk/theme-park/transportation/skyride/</ref>\n\nIn October 2019, it was announced that Cloud Cuckoo Land will be replaced by \"The World of [[David Walliams]]\" for the 2020 season, which will feature attractions based around Walliams' series of [[children's books]].<ref>https://www.birminghammail.co.uk/whats-on/family-kids-news/alton-towers-open-new-world-17094301</ref>\n\n=== Dark Forest ===\nThe Dark Forest is themed as a supernatural woodland area; to coincide with the opening of ''[[Thirteen (roller coaster)|TH13TEEN]]'', a steel family coaster themed as a haunted [[crypt]], that opened on 20 March 2010. Th13teen, features the \"world's first freefall drop on a roller coaster\" - an indoor, vertically dropping track element. The ride replaced the ''[[Corkscrew (Alton Towers)|Corkscrew]]''; the park's first roller coaster, which opened in 1980. ''[[Rita (roller coaster)|Rita]]'' is a hydraulically launched steel sit-down coaster that reaches a top speed of 62&nbsp;mph (100&nbsp;km) that is now themed around an abandoned [[Drag racing|drag racer]] that is used to escape the Dark Forest.\n\nThe area was previously a cartoon prehistoric area named Ug Land, which opened in 1999, but was half-demolished to make way for Rita's construction in 2005. Rita used to be themed around drag racing but was changed with the opening of Th13teen and the Dark Forest. With the opening of ''Th13teen'', the area was renamed as Dark Forest and further altered with a new colour scheme and entrance feature. ''Rita'' was also given a repainted control cabin and trains, shortening its name from \"Rita - Queen of Speed\".<ref name=\"thirteen\">{{cite web|title=SW6 Revealed: TH13TEEN|url=http://towersnerd.com/news/item.php?id=193|accessdate=1 December 2009|publisher=Towers Nerd|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100605233654/http://towersnerd.com/news/item.php?id=193|archive-date=5 June 2010|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n=== CBeebies Land ===\n{{Main|CBeebies#CBeebies Land|l1=CBeebies: CBeebies Land}}\n\nCBeebies Land is based on the [[BBC]] children's TV channel: [[CBeebies]]. It is the newest area of the Theme Park and opened on 24 May 2014. The area includes rides, shows and interactive experiences based on programmes from CBeebies, including [[In the Night Garden...]] and [[Postman Pat]].<ref name=\"Attractions2009-DM\">{{cite web |url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/travel/article-2537200/Alton-Towers-targets-lucrative-toddler-market-CBeebies-Land.html |title=Alton Towers targets the lucrative toddler market with first ever CBeebies Land|date=January 2014 |work=Daily Mail |accessdate=15 March 2014}}</ref> Attractions in the area are: ''In the Night Garden Magical Boat Ride'', ''Postman Pat's Parcel Post'', ''Get Set Go Treetop Adventure'', ''Something Special Sensory Garden'', ''Numtums Number Go-Around'', ''Charlie & Lola's Moonsquirters and Greendrops'', ''Justin's House: Pie-O-Matic Factory'', ''Mr Bloom's Allotment'' and ''Tree Fu Tom Training Camp''. Shows at the Big Fun Show Time stage include: Mike the Knight, The ZingZillas and Nina and the Neurons. In 2015, ''Octonauts Roller Coaster Adventure'' opened, it is an underwater themed children's roller coaster; built on the vacant site The Beastie roller coaster. CBeebies Land was further expanded in 2017 with the opening of the ''Go Jetters Vroomster Zoom Ride'' and ''The Furchester Hotel Live'', and again in 2019 with the addition of ''Peter Rabbit Hippity Hop'' and ''Teletubbies Big Band Live Show''.\n\n=== The Towers ===\n[[File:Alton Towers - geograph.org.uk - 1464460.jpg|thumb|Main historic house]]\nThe Towers are the ruins of Alton Towers stately home and are the source of the park's name. They belonged to the Talbot family as a stately home until 1924 and largely designed by [[Augustus Pugin]], also noted for his work on the [[Palace of Westminster]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Augustus Welby Northmore Pugin|website=Explore Parliament}}</ref> The Towers are now in a state of disrepair following decades of neglect. The ruins are open to the public during most of the open season. However, some areas are closed off as part of a \u00a31.1 million project in place to restore the oldest parts of the Towers. Key areas of The Towers include the banqueting hall, the chapel, conservatories, and Her Ladyship's Gardens.\n\n''[[Hex \u2013 The Legend of the Towers]]'', a walk-through dark ride based within the ruins themselves, opened in 2000. The finale to the ride is a Vekoma [[Madhouse (ride)|Madhouse]] located away from the real Towers but themed as a secret vault. The storyline is based on a local legend about the [[chained oak]] tree, located in a nearby forest, and makes use of the history of the Towers. It draws its theme from the legend of the 15th Earl of Shrewsbury who was said to be cursed by a beggar woman to suffer death every time a branch falls from an old oak tree.\n\nDuring the park's Halloween 'Scarefest' event multiple scare mazes operate within the Towers themselves. For 2018's Scarefest event these were; Sub Species: the End Games, and Altonville Mine Tours.\n\n=== The Gardens ===\n[[File:Alton Towers gardens - geograph.org.uk - 1464404.jpg|thumb|Gardens created by the eccentric 15th [[Earl of Shrewsbury]]]]\n\nNear the garden entrance is a [[cenotaph]] to the 15th Earl, a marble bust with an inscription reading \"He made the desert smile\". Landmarks include a Chinese Pagoda Fountain, The Swiss Cottage, Miniature 'Stonehenge', a Greek Choragic Monument, and orangeries.\n\n== Alton Towers Waterpark ==\n{{Main|Alton Towers Waterpark}}\n[[File:Alton Towers Waterpark1.JPG|thumbnail|left|Alton Towers Waterpark]]\nThe Alton Towers Waterpark, formerly known as Cariba Creek, opened alongside the Splash Landings Hotel in 2003.<ref>{{cite web\n |title       = Making a splash with a 'waterpark hotel'\n |work        = Daily Mail\n |url         = http://www.altontowers.com/waterpark/openingpricing.asp\n |access-date = 14 January 2014\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20070325013647/http://www.altontowers.com/waterpark/openingpricing.asp\n |archivedate = 25 March 2007\n |url-status     = dead\n |df          = dmy-all\n}}</ref> It is a large (with 7 pools and 10 water slides), part-indoor and part outdoor waterpark themed as a tropical Caribbean lagoon. The waterpark features several fast slides, a [[lazy river]], a giant tipping bucket and many other water features. Also located there are two food and drink venues: Adventures Cave and Ice Cream Shack. Unlike [[Chessington Zoo]] at the also [[Merlin Entertainments|Merlin]] operated [[Chessington World of Adventures Resort]], a separate ticket is needed for waterpark access as it is not included with the theme park entrance price.\n\nAttractions include ''Lagoona Bay'', which is the main tropical pool, with water cannons, geysers and waterfalls. ''The Little Leak'' is a paddling pool for young children with two small slides and interactive pipes to play with, while ''Wacky Waterworks Treehouse'' is a wooden 'treehouse' with water cannons, and other interactive features to squirt passing people with.\n\nThe largest ride in the Waterpark is the [[Water Coaster (Mack Rides)|water coaster]] ''The Master Blaster'', with uphill sections similar to the ''Master Blaster'' at [[Sandcastle Water Park (Blackpool)|Sandcastle Waterpark]], ''Blackpool'' and ''Nucleus'' at [[Water World, Stoke-on-Trent]]. ''The Master Blaster'' is a high speed water flume that contains sharp turns, drops and dark sections, and has views of the entire indoor area of the waterpark.\n\nOther rides include ''Rush & Rampage'', twin racing slides where riders experience wide turns. This attraction requires rubber rings. ''Lazy River (Calypso Creek)'' is a slow-moving water circuit, taking riders underneath spraying water jets and tipping buckets of water. Rubber rings are available. ''The Tipping Bucket'' is a container filled with 1000 litres of water which regularly tips its contents over people standing below. ''Flash Floods'' are tiered outdoor pools with two slides leading to the middle pool and three leading to the bottom. Other swimming pools include ''Volcanic Springs'', and indoor heated hot pool, and ''Bubbly Wubbly Pool'', an outdoor heated pool and whirlpool.\n\nThe indoor section of the water park operates 12 months a year excluding Christmas Day and Boxing Day, although it closes for winter maintenance for around 2 weeks each January.\n\n== Resort accommodation ==\n[[File:Alton Towers Hotel, Staffordshire - geograph.org.uk - 6099.jpg|thumb|The fountain at the entrance to Alton Towers Hotel]]\n\n=== Alton Towers Hotel ===\nThe Alton Towers Hotel opened on 10 April 1996 and is themed to the eccentric fictional character Sir Algenon Alton and his travels. The rooms are decorated in a quirky English style with pictures of Sir Algenon's inventions. The hotel is four star and has 180 rooms. The hotel was the first phase in a plan to turn the theme park into a multi-day resort.\n\nThe Alton Towers Hotel is currently undergoing a long term phased refurbishment to theme each floor to a different setting. So far, the plan has produced the Moon Voyage Bedrooms and Arctic Explorer Bedrooms.\n\n=== Splash Landings Hotel ===\nThe Splash Landings Hotel opened in 2003. The hotel has a relaxed Caribbean theme and is attached to the [[Alton Towers Waterpark]]. It is also four star and it has 216 rooms with a choice of six-room types, Family of 4 'Beachcomber' room, Family of 6 'Beachcomber' room, The Ice Age Suites, The Pirate Suites, Interconnected Family of 4 'Beachcomber' room and, Interconnected Family of 3 'Beachcomber' Room. The interconnected rooms are all on the ground floor and the family of 3 rooms are also disabled accessible. The rooms are numbered in the ranges of 1101 to 1159, 1201 to 1259, 1301 to 1359 and, 1401 to 1459, there are a few room numbers that are not used due to the shape of the hotel, these are 27, 29, 31, 33 and 35 on each floor.\n\n=== Enchanted Village ===\nThe Enchanted Village is made up of 120 lodges and 5 secluded treehouses set in the fictional ''Enchanted Forest'' woodland. Situated next to the Alton Towers hotel, it features new recreational activities, such as various playgrounds for children and an archery range, which is available to use at no extra cost. The site is also home to \"The Crooked Spoon\" restaurant, and also an additional shop which sells alcohol and outdoor activity toys.\n\nThe Enchanted Village opened to the public on 18 April 2015.\n\nAlton Towers have submitted planning application to expand the Enchanted Village in several phases. The application has been approved and if the plans go ahead, construction on the first phase will commence in 2018 with a scheduled opening of March 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.towerstimes.co.uk/enchanted-village/ |title=Enchanted Village |publisher=TowersTimes |accessdate=4 September 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== CBeebies Land Hotel ===\nThe CBeebies Land Hotel opened on 8 July 2017, the hotel has a total of 76 themed rooms: 42 standard rooms (themed to the CBeebies Bugbies) and 34 premium rooms themed to different CBeebies shows, such as ''Something Special'' and ''Swashbuckle''. Room amenities include child-friendly features, such as steps up to the sink and children's toilet seats. The hotel features CBeebies-themed shows and entertainment, which run every day of the year, as well as the \"Windmill Restaurant\".<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.altontowers.com/2017/ |title=Archived copy |access-date=28 July 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160827103207/https://www.altontowers.com/2017/ |archive-date=27 August 2016 |url-status=dead  }}</ref>\n\n=== Stargazing Pods ===\n{{refimprove|section|date=March 2020}}\nAlthough Alton Towers had previously gained the necessary permits to expand the Enchanted Village, these plans were eventually scrapped and reduced into a \"pod\"-style accommodation option. 102 individual pods were constructed, each sleeping up to four people.\n\nThe proposals have faced some critical views from the public, with many criticisms being raised over the capacity of bathroom facilities as well as how the resort will cope with the increased demand in food and beverages, as the Stargazing Pods will not have its own restaurant or bar facilities. The council even initially rejected the application citing lack of imagination and \"magic\", although the plans were granted permission the second time without making any notable improvements.\n\nThe Stargazing Pods opened on 12 April 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.altontowers.com/short-breaks/stargazing-pods/|title=Stargazing Pods|website=www.altontowers.com|language=en|access-date=12 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Recreation ==\n\n=== Alton Towers Spa ===\nAlton Towers Spa is part of the Alton Towers Hotel and opened in 2004. It includes relaxation and treatment rooms and an adults only swimming pool. Despite being inside the Alton Towers Hotel, non-hotel guests are able to use the Spa.\n\n=== Extraordinary Golf ===\nOpened in 2007, the Extraordinary Golf mini-golf attraction is themed to different rides and attractions at the park, some of which, are from the park's history. Extraordinary Golf is located to the west of the Splash Landings Hotel. Extraordinary Golf was refreshed for 2016 including the addition of a Galactica themed hole.\n\n=== Tree Top Quest ===\nOpened May 2015, the Enchanted Forest Tree Top Quest is a high ropes course near the Enchanted Village. The attraction opened shortly after, and accompanies, the Enchanted Village development. There is also a low ropes course. Tree Top Quest did not open for the 2018 season or the start of the 2019 season due to budget cuts by parent company, Merlin Entertainments. It is expected to reopen on 13 July 2019.<ref>https://www.altontowers.com/activities/tree-top-quest/</ref>\n\n== Future developments ==\nAlton Towers is working with children's author [[David Walliams]] to develop a new themed area, 'World of David Walliams', replacing Cloud Cuckoo Land in Spring 2020, the new area will feature a dark ride themed to the author's [[Gangsta Granny]] children's book.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Chamberlain |first1=Zoe |title=Alton Towers to open new 'World of David Walliams' attraction |url=https://www.birminghammail.co.uk/whats-on/family-kids-news/alton-towers-open-new-world-17094301 |website=Birmingham Mail |accessdate=11 November 2019 |date=17 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nAlton Towers is located in a [[Conservation Area (United Kingdom)|Conservation Area]], which puts restrictions on its permissible development, notably that no structures in the park should be built above tree line and if so should be disguised from external views of the park; this can be seen on the ride [[Rita (roller coaster)|Rita]], where the highest sections of track are camouflaged green.\n\nNoise pollution is also a problem for the park due to the close proximity to the villages of Alton and Farley and the town of [[Cheadle, Staffordshire|Cheadle]]. There have been several cases where Alton Towers have been taken to court over the noise levels emitted from the park and have been served noise abatement orders in 2004, 2005 and 2006.\n\n== Secret Weapon roller coasters ==\nAlton Towers has a tradition of codenaming its new roller coaster developments as \"Secret Weapon\", or \"SW\", followed by a number. The name is associated with the park's inclination to promote its rides as holding \"world first\" or in some way \"innovative\" features and records. However the naming tradition actually began for unrelated reasons, since \"Secret Weapon\" was the working title of a roller coaster that was ultimately never commissioned.\n\nSW1 was a [[pipeline roller coaster]], planned to open in around 1992, on what later became the Nemesis site. It was provisionally titled the \"Secret Weapon\", with the intention of theming the ride as an ambiguous weapon testing facility.<ref name=\"The Secret Wepons\">{{cite web|title=The Secret Weapons - Developing the Magic|url=http://old.towerstimes.co.uk/history/articles/secretweapons.htm|website=towerstimes.co.uk|accessdate=31 May 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20131104102401/http://old.towerstimes.co.uk/history/articles/secretweapons.htm|archivedate=4 November 2013}}</ref> [[John Wardley]] rode the [[Arrow Dynamics]] prototype of their pipeline coaster, but stated \"it was very slow and rather boring\",<ref name=\"The creation of Nemesis\">{{cite web|last1=Wardley|first1=John|title=The creation of Nemesis|url=http://www.towersalmanac.com/features/multimedia.php?id=19|website=Alton Towers Almanac|accessdate=31 May 2015}}</ref> as well as the requirement for such a high lift hill being unsuitable for the park's planning restrictions. After a second layout revision, labelled \"SW2\", the ride was scrapped and development on SW3 ([[Nemesis (roller coaster)|Nemesis]]) began.<ref name=\"The Secret Wepons\"/><ref name=\"The creation of Nemesis\"/> The code name subsequently became the standard preliminary name for major roller coaster projects at the park.\n\nThe naming convention was briefly dropped while the Tussauds Group changed ownership under [[Dubai International Capital]], before being continued by Merlin Entertainments.\n\n== Events ==\n{{Overly detailed|date=January 2019}}\nPrior to the main open season, Alton Towers held the February Half-Term event which saw a selected ride offering opened for the week before the start of the main season in March, however the event was cancelled for 2016; with the exception of Sharkbait Reef which was open for Pirate and Princess Week held at the Resort hotels.\n\n=== Concerts ===\nAlton Towers has a history of hosting concerts since the 1960s. Concerts in recent years have included the Alton Towers Live event in 2011 and 2013. In 2010, there was an 80s concert for the 30th Anniversary featuring [[Rick Astley]] and [[Bananarama]] and also that year hosted a [[P!nk]] concert. In the past these concerts were often held in the car park at an additional fee, however more recently concerts have been held within the theme park. Artists that have performed there include [[Tina Turner]] and [[The Black Eyed Peas]].\n\n=== Oktoberfest ===\nThe \"Alton Towers Oktoberfest\" is a new event scheduled to take place in weekends during late September and early October 2020. It is based on the German festival of [[Oktoberfest]] held traditionally in Munich, Germany. The event will involve themed food and drink, entertainment and extended evening hours with selected rides open.<ref>{{cite web |title=What is Oktoberfest? |url=https://support.altontowers.com/hc/en-us/articles/360006001078-What-is-Oktoberfest- |website=Alton Towers Resort |accessdate=24 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Scarefest ===\n''Scarefest'' is the resort's largest annual event. It celebrates [[Halloween]] with a number of temporary scare maze attractions, scare zones, costumed characters and extended opening hours. Rides and areas are lit with coloured lighting at night, with most rides and attractions continuing to operate until 9pm. The Scarefest event has been running since 2007, although the park started celebrating Halloween with decoration several years before and has operated the ''Terror of the Towers'' scaremaze since 2002.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.birminghammail.co.uk/whats-on/whats-on-news/alton-towers-scarefest-2016-you-10099966|title=Alton Towers reveals plans for Scarefest 2017 with a new addition|first=Steve|last=Wollaston|date=31 October 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/trips-and-breaks/review-alton-towers-scarefest-2017-12034148|title=Travel review: Alton Towers Scarefest 2016|first=Justin|last=Connolly|date=15 October 2016}}</ref> The scare mazes are [[upcharge attraction]]s.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center\"\n|+ Timeline of Halloween scare mazes\n! Season(s)<br>active !! 2002 !! 2003 !! 2004 !! 2005 !! 2006 !! 2007 !! 2008 !! 2009 !! 2010 !! 2011 !! 2012 !! 2013 !! 2014 !! 2015 !! 2016 !! 2017 !! 2018 !! 2019\n|-\n| 1 ||| ''Terror in the Towers'' ||colspan=\"17\" style=\"background:lightgrey;\" |\n|-\n| 3 || style=\"background:lightgrey;\"| ||  colspan=\"6\"| ''Terror of the Towers: Bloodfest Banquet *'' || colspan=\"14\" style=\"background:lightgrey;\" |\n|-\n| 2 || colspan=\"4\" style=\"background:lightgrey;\" | ||  colspan=\"2\"| ''Room13'' || colspan=\"12\" style=\"background:lightgrey;\" |\n|-\n| 3 || colspan=\"5\" style=\"background:lightgrey;\" |  || colspan=\"3\"| ''The Field of 1000 Screams'' || colspan=\"13\" style=\"background:lightgrey;\" |\n|-\n| 4 || colspan=\"6\" style=\"background:lightgrey;\" |  || colspan=\"4\"| ''The Boilerhouse'' || colspan=\"11\" style=\"background:lightgrey;\" |\n|-\n| 9 || colspan=\"7\" style=\"background:lightgrey\" |  || colspan=\"9\"| ''Terror of the Towers: What lies Within'' || colspan=\"10\" style=\"background:lightgrey;\"|\n|-\n| 4 || colspan=\"8\" style=\"background:lightgrey;\" |  || colspan=\"4\"| ''Carnival of Screams'' || colspan=\"11\" style=\"background:lightgrey;\" |\n|-\n| 3 || colspan=\"10\" style=\"background:lightgrey;\" |  || colspan=\"3\"| ''The Sanctuary'' || colspan=\"12\" style=\"background:lightgrey;\" |\n|-\n| 1 || colspan=\"13\" style=\"background:lightgrey;\" |  || ''The Haunting of Molly Crowe'' || colspan=\"5\" style=\"background:lightgrey;\" |\n|-\n| 5 || colspan=\"13\" style=\"background:lightgrey;\" |  || colspan=\"5\" style=\"background:#3F6;\" | ''Sub Species: The End Games''\n|-\n| 4 || colspan=\"14\" style=\"background:lightgrey;\" |  || colspan=\"4\" style=\"background:#3F6;\" | ''Altonville Mine Tours: Uncover the Legend of The Skin Snatchers''\n|-\n| 3 || colspan=\"14\" style=\"background:lightgrey;\" |  || colspan=\"3\" | ''House of Monsters'' || colspan=\"1\" style=\"background:lightgrey;\" |\n|-\n| 2 || colspan=\"15\" style=\"background:lightgrey;\" |  || colspan=\"2\" | ''The Welcoming: Be Chosen'' || colspan=\"1\" style=\"background:lightgrey;\" |\n|-\n| 2 || colspan=\"16\" style=\"background:lightgrey;\" |  || colspan=\"2\" style=\"background:#3f6;\"| ''Project 42''\n|-\n| 1 || colspan=\"17\" style=\"background:lightgrey;\" |  || style=\"background:#3f6;\" | ''The Attic: Terror of the Towers''\n|-\n| 1 || colspan=\"17\" style=\"background:lightgrey;\" |  || style=\"background:#3f6;\" | ''Darkest Depths''\n|}\n\n{{Color box|#FFFFFF|border=darkgray}}&nbsp; Previous Scarefest maze\n{{Color box|#3F6|border=darkgray}}&nbsp; Current Scarefest maze\n\n''*Terror of the Towers took in break in 2004, 2005 and 2006.''\n\n==== Seasonal Scarefest attractions as of 2019 ====\n* ''Altonville Mine Tours: Uncover the Legend of the Skin Snatchers'', live action horror maze, set in the baron town of Altonville. A family of inbred hillbillies are outcast due to their hideous disfigurement and warped way of life. Through desperation they begin capturing townsfolk, before removing their skin and stitching it into their own in a hope that this may finally give them the beauty they so desire.\n\n* ''Sub Species: The End Games'', a live action horror maze returning in 2018, which will push the boundaries of Scarefest's mazes with multiple routes. A post-apocalyptic, sewer dwelling community have been infested by a species from another world. In order to survive, they appease the creature's hunger by sacrificing innocent people from the surface. However, over time, insanity has twisted the feeding ritual into a sick contest. Your demise is now their entertainment. Let the death race begin!<ref name=\"AltonTowers\">{{cite web|title=Scarefest 2016|url=https://www.altontowers.com/activities/events/scarefest/}}</ref>\n\n* ''Project 42'' - The Phalanx base has been compromised and the team is in demise. The base had been used for civilian tests on a unique virus but something's gone wrong; the test subjects, now infected by the virus, have broken out. The Phalanx requires volunteers to enter the compound, find the vaccination and rescue the technician. Can you get out before contracting the infection?\n\n* ''Darkest Depths'' - {{em|New for 2019}}. Board the infamous ghost ship 'The Mutiny' and journey into the darkest depths to earn your piece of eight. The treacherous Sirens will try to lure you into the ocean as you dodge the swords of the mutinous ghost pirates and come face to face with the sea's meanest legend of all ... the Kraken!\n\n* ''The Attic: Terror of the Towers'' - {{em|New for 2019}}. Return of the iconic maze with new storyline and route. Dare you venture up to The Attic in this live action maze where you'll discover the ghost of 'The Governess'! According to local legend, she tries to avenge the death of her charges by taking the spirits of the living as penance - will you be her next victim?\n\n==== Past seasonal Scarefest attractions ====\n* ''Terror of the Towers''. The first incarnation of this long-running annual scare maze was introduced in 2002, and was located in the Towers ruins themselves. Many scenes from the original maze are still used. Visitors walked through the long, winding corridors of the Towers, through themed scenes while being pursued by live actors. The finale featured a winding pathway around actors behind fences, who lunged towards visitors, accompanied with heavy strobe effects. For 2003 it was restructured and given the tagline and theme \"Bloodfest Banquet\".\n\n* \"TH13TEEN: After Dark\" has an enhanced queue line for Alton Towers' newest roller coaster, using fog and lighting effects as well as live actors. This attraction did not return for 2012.\n\n* ''Terror of the Towers&nbsp;\u2013 Bloodfest Banquet'' was a new version of the Terror of the Towers scare maze, running from 2003 to 2008.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.scareattractions.co.uk/terror-of-the-towers-bloodfest-banquet-alton-towers/ |title=Scare Attractions UK \u2013 promoting and supporting the UK scare entertainment industry since 2006 |publisher=Scareattractions.co.uk |accessdate=24 July 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131226194338/http://www.scareattractions.co.uk/terror-of-the-towers-bloodfest-banquet-alton-towers/ |archive-date=26 December 2013 |url-status=dead  }}</ref> It retained much of the original version, but featured new scenes that included scripted dialogue from the several characters, and a new storyline was added. The strobe maze finale was moved to another point in the maze and replaced by a new ending, in which visitors become trapped in a small room with cages on every side, as actors reach for them through the metal bars for almost a minute. Every year, Terror of the Towers kept changing slightly with revised scenes and new scares.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.scareattractions.co.uk/terror-of-the-towers-2008-readers-review-2008/ |title=Scare Attractions UK \u2013 promoting and supporting the UK scare entertainment industry since 2006 |publisher=Scareattractions.co.uk |accessdate=24 July 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131226194427/http://www.scareattractions.co.uk/terror-of-the-towers-2008-readers-review-2008/ |archive-date=26 December 2013 |url-status=dead  }}</ref> However, for the 2009 Scarefest event, Terror of the Towers was once again completely rethought, with the tagline \"What Lies Within\". The new incarnation drops the scripted scenes and characters; meaning it is similar to the original Terror of Towers of 2002. The whole layout for the maze was also reversed, with what was previously the entrance becoming the exit.\n\n* ''Room 13'' was first introduced in 2006 and was located in the conference room of the Alton Towers Hotel.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.scareattractions.co.uk/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=61:alton-towers-hotel-room-13&catid=75&Itemid=126 |title=Scare Attractions UK \u2013 promoting and supporting the UK scare entertainment industry since 2006 |publisher=Scareattractions.co.uk |accessdate=24 July 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120325224813/http://www.scareattractions.co.uk/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=61%3Aalton-towers-hotel-room-13&catid=75&Itemid=126 |archivedate=25 March 2012 }}</ref> It was only available to guests of the hotel, who were led around the maze as many live actors appeared to scare them. Room 13 had positive reviews and returned in 2007, but was replaced by The Boiler House in 2008.\n\n* ''Field of 1000 Screams'' was first introduced in the 2007 Scarefest event and was the first maze at Alton Towers not situated inside a pre-existing building.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.scareattractions.co.uk/alton-towers-scarefest-maze-reviews-2007/ |title=Scare Attractions UK \u2013 promoting and supporting the UK scare entertainment industry since 2006 |publisher=Scareattractions.co.uk |accessdate=24 July 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131226194613/http://www.scareattractions.co.uk/alton-towers-scarefest-maze-reviews-2007/ |archive-date=26 December 2013 |url-status=dead  }}</ref> The Field was located entirely outdoors in a moderately sized field of [[maize]], which had to be planted especially for the event several months earlier. It purported to be a fictional village called Altonville that had become overrun by zombies. Visitors walked down a long pathway cut through the corn, and encountered characters and scares along the way, before the finale took place. The Field of 1000 Screams did not return for the 2010 event.\n\n* ''Haunted Hollow Live'' was first seen in 2007 and consisted of several sinister, costumed actors performing along the Haunted Hollow walkway in Gloomy Wood. The attraction was similar to Duel Live, which was introduced the year later. Haunted Hollow Live returned for the 2008 Scarefest event, but was cancelled for 2009.\n\n* ''Duel Live'' was first introduced in the 2008 Scarefest event. Throughout this period, the park's haunted house dark ride, [[Duel (ride)|Duel]], became host to this attraction, which included live actors situated around the ride circuit. Duel was available to ride normally until 12&nbsp;pm, when the laser guns and LED targets were switched and the actors took their positions. This was changed in 2009, when Duel Live took place throughout the whole day and many more actors than the previous year were present. Duel Live was aimed at the family audience, and included such features as new music playing throughout the ride (instead of the usual Duel theme music), as well as a butler or maid who would welcome you inside the house. The attraction was changed slightly for the 2010 season and featured the park's Scarefest mascots.\n\n* ''Skelvin's Haunted Adventure'' was a newer version of [[Duel (ride)#Duel: Live!|Duel Live]], introduced in 2010, and took over [[Duel (ride)|Duel \u2013 The Haunted House Strikes Back!]] throughout Scarefest. As in previous years, the attraction included live actors situated at different points around the ride. The laser guns and LED targets were switched off during this time. The ride featured the Scarefest mascots, notably the character of \"Skelvin\".\n\n* ''The Boiler House'' was a scare maze first introduced in 2008, and was situated next to the Alton Towers Hotel. Originally, the scare maze was set in an abandoned industrial facility and featured live actors in make up. This was changed in 2009, when a new storyline was added. The scare maze later featured the fictional \"Hamble Twins\" serial killers hiding in the industrial building, and visitors have to escape them as they are chased through the scenes. Visitors queued outside, past a van labelled \"Alton News 24\", from which television screens play news reports on the activity of the serial killers. Guests then walk through a covered walkway, which hides the marquee that the maze is contained in from view. Once inside, a man appears and warns guests about the dangers of coming inside. The murderers then appear and kill him, before chasing visitors away. Each of the Twins are played by two different actors wearing the same grotesque, latex mask. They appear at different points in the maze, creating the illusion that one character is in several places at once. Dim lighting and scent effects are heavily used. For the 2011 Scarefest, The Boiler House moved along with the Carnival of Screams to the X Sector, where they both shared the old Black Hole tent. After three years it did not return for the 2012 season.\n\n* ''Carnival of Screams'' was a scare maze that debuted for the 2010 Scarefest event. During its debut it shared the same temporary building as the Boiler House. John Wardley contributed to the development of ''Carnival of Screams'', which was entered through a large clown face with horrific features. For 2011 it and the Boiler House were relocated to the X-Sector area. The maze is a mixture of humor and serious scares, and the music used is the former ''Toy Land Tours'' attraction theme music warped for dramatic effect. From 2012 onwards, the attraction was situated opposite the hospitality suite, with the exit inside the Goal Striker unit. In 2013 and its final incarnation, the maze gained a theatrical ending involving a knife thrower.\n\n* ''The Sanctuary'' was new for the 2012 Scarefest event and returned in 2013 and 2014. The attraction was set in a research facility operated by \"The Ministry of Joy\". Alton Towers released the following description at the time: \"Lost your Smile? Then check yourself in for a refreshing check up at The Sanctuary. After being closed for new patients for almost 50 years The Sanctuary, The Ministry of Joy\u2019s earliest establishment, is now holding important trials searching for 'Advocates' for its 2013 project.\" It was revealed to be part of marketing for ''[[The Smiler (roller coaster)|The Smiler]]'' roller coaster, which opened in 2013.<ref name=\"The Sanctuary\">{{cite web|title=The Sanctuary new for 2012|url=http://www.towerstimes.co.uk/scarefest/attractions/the-sanctuary/|accessdate=27 September 2012|publisher=TowersTimes}}</ref>\n\n* ''Scary Tales Scare Zone'' was a walk through scare zone that ran for the 2014 event. The attraction setting revolved around fairy tale stories that were rewritten in a nightmarish manner.\n\n* ''The Haunting of Molly Crowe'', a multi-sensory maze set in the Towers ruins. The maze was based on the old and abandoned house of Molly Crowe, who was last seen engulfed in flames in the cellar of her house, emitting a scream of non-human origin. This ran for the 2015 event.\n\n* ''Nox:Infernus Scare Zone'', a scare zone which ran for the 2015 event, set in the Dark Forest. The underworld rises again - Will you join the Cult or face the end of the world as we know it?\n\n* ''Dark Apocalypse Scare Zone'', a scare zone which was first introduced for the 2015 event and returning in 2016. A deadly virus has spread across Forbidden Valley. The infected show signs of highly aggressive behavior and rapid physical decomposition. Phalanx control has quarantined the area however, a recent security breach has questioned their ability to contain the virus and keep society safe.\n\n* ''Terror of the Towers&nbsp;\u2013 What Lies Within'', the signature maze situated inside the Towers themselves, first introduced in 2002. A new format was introduced in the 2009 Scarefest event, along with the new tagline \"What Lies Within\" replacing \"Bloodfest Banquet\". Visitors queue outside in Her Ladyship's Gardens, and the attraction itself starts in the derelict Conservatories. Batches of guests watch a short video showing two men exploring the Towers for ghosts. The video then cuts short, and guests enter the Towers to find the men. At certain points in the maze, the bodies of the two men are each seen hanging from a noose. Visitors become lost in the lengthy corridors and themed scenes in the Towers, with live actors pursuing them in every room. The finale to the attraction is a maze-like walkway that winds around actors in cages, with strobe effects.\n\n=== Fireworks ===\nFor the last days of the season, Alton Towers host [[Fireworks|firework]] Shows, these have been running annually since the 1990s on the Great Lawns. The displays were considered disruptive by some local residents, which led to formal complaints. Two local residents decided to take the theme park to court regarding this issue. The court issued Alton Towers with a noise abatement order in October 2005 which restricted the theme park to three shows a year, previously five, with noise readings not exceeding 40 decibels outside the park.<ref>{{cite news\n| title=Fireworks go-ahead for theme park\n| work=BBC News\n| date=14 October 2005\n| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/staffordshire/4342978.stm\n| accessdate=13 July 2006}}</ref> In 2006, the display was rebranded as Electric Towers, but then discontinued. However, the fireworks and laser show was reinstated in 2010 to celebrate the 30th anniversary of the theme park and has returned to being an annual event.\n\n=== Other events ===\nDuring the closed season months Alton Towers holds regular ''Pirate & Princess Weekends''. The event entails decorations, and themed activities for children in the Hotels and the waterpark. The theme park's Sharkbait Reef aquarium also opens for the event.\n\nDuring December, the ''Santa's Sleepover'' event takes place. Both resort hotels are decorated for the event and a pantomime takes place. The Alton Towers Theme Park also opens for Christmas with a small number of rides open as well as a Santa's Grotto. The event is largely aimed at children. In 2015, the theme park permitted entry to non-hotel guests for the first time however the event reverted to hotel guests only in 2016. Festive Breaks continue from 27 December 2018 to 6 January 2019 with a similar lineup to the Santa's Sleepovers.\n\nSince 2015 Alton Towers have opened the park for a ''Services Day''; a day where a limited quantity of discounted tickets (fewer than on a usual season day) are sold to those who work in public services<ref name=\"ServicesDay\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bluelightcard.co.uk/newsletters/4thjanuary2017/4thjanuary2017-fjknkwjneuwuwn.php?mid=466017&nid=250|title=Blue Light Card Newsletter|publisher=Blue Light Card|date=4 January 2017|accessdate=28 February 2018}}</ref> such as the [[Law enforcement in the United Kingdom|Police]], [[NHS]], [[Fire brigade]], [[Her Majesty's Prison Service|Prison service]], [[British Army|Army]], [[RAF]], [[Royal Navy]] and other similar services. Services Day is usually held approximately two weeks prior to the start of the new season, which usually begins mid-March. Due to the success of the 2015, '16 and '17 Services Days, a two-day weekend of Services Days was planned for 3 and 4 March 2018, however this was postponed to 11 March [[2018 Great Britain and Ireland cold wave|due to weather conditions]]. Another two-day event took place on 16\u201317 March 2019. Services Days are open to holders of a Blue Light Card or a Defence Discount Service Card.<ref name=\"ServicesDay\" />\n\n== Incidents ==\n{{main|Incidents at European amusement parks#Alton Towers}}\n\n=== The Smiler ===\n{{For|additional information and incidents|The Smiler#Incidents}}\nIn June 2015, sixteen people were injured on The Smiler ride, with two individuals requiring leg amputations. Merlin Entertainments originally released a press release blaming the crash on \"human error\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-34911943|title=Alton Towers crash due to 'human error'|date=24 November 2015|via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref> However, the Health & Safety Executive (HSE) concluded the crash was foreseeable, stating that \"Merlin failed to put in place systems that allowed their engineers to work safely on the ride while it was running\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-stoke-staffordshire-37481825|title=Alton Towers operator fined \u00a35m|date=27 September 2016|via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref> During the subsequent court case, Merlin retracted their statement and pleaded guilty to a breach of health and safety law. The company was fined \u00a35Million, with the court citing a \"catalogue of errors\" with Merlin's operating procedure and training.<ref name=\"bbc.co.uk\">[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-stoke-staffordshire-37481825 Smiler crash: Alton Towers operator Merlin fined \u00a35m] [[BBC]] 27 September 2016</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cityam.com/250176/alton-towers-owner-merlin-just-got-slapped-5m-fine-smiler|title=Alton Towers owner Merlin just got slapped with a \u00a35m fine|first=Billy|last=Bambrough|date=27 September 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2017, Alton Towers estate owner [[Nick Leslau]] repeated the discredited claim that the crash was due to \"a human error\", but added that \"Merlin has paid a massive price, but the performance of the business has been exemplary and the share price is now at an all-time high.\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.cityam.com/266421/alton-towers-owner-and-multi-millionaire-nick-leslau |title=Archived copy |access-date=29 October 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171025061019/http://www.cityam.com/266421/alton-towers-owner-and-multi-millionaire-nick-leslau |archive-date=25 October 2017 |url-status=dead  }}</ref>\n\n=== Sky Ride ===\nOn 30 June 2004, due to a strong gust of wind, the Sky Ride cables became caught, jamming the ride. About 80 people were on the ride, and nine people had to be rescued by being [[Abseiling|abseiled]] down {{convert|200|foot|m}} cables.<ref>{{cite news\n|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/staffordshire/3851957.stm\n|title=Park investigates ride failure\n|publisher=BBC\n|date=30 June 2004\n|accessdate=23 September 2009}}</ref>\n\nDuring the 2007 [[Alton Towers#Scarefest|Scarefest]] season, a fire broke out in the [[Alton Towers#Forbidden Valley|Forbidden Valley]] section of the park due to a halogen lamp that damaged the roof and mechanics of the ride. The damage was reparable and had to be closed for six months before reopening midway through the 2008 season. Nobody was harmed.<ref name=\"towerstimes.co.uk\"/>\n\nAnother fire happened to the ride this time in the [[Alton Towers#Cloud Cuckoo Land|Cloud Cuckoo Land]] station in the 2009 season, due to a faulty vending machine, on 21 July 2009. The fire completely destroyed the whole station. Over the following season, the station was rebuilt, ready for the 2010 season.\n\n=== Runaway Mine Train ===\n{{Main|Runaway Mine Train (Alton Towers)}}\nOn 20 July 2006, when the train was entering the tunnel section of its course, two carriages uncoupled, with the front half of the train continuing up the slope while the rear half remained stuck in the tunnel. The front half failed to make it over the hill, rolled back and crashed into the rear half which had remained stuck in the tunnel. Six people were taken to hospital and 23 others were treated for cuts and bruises. Following the incident the [[Runaway Mine Train (Alton Towers)|Runaway Mine Train]] was closed for the rest of the season. The train was only returned to full length operation in June the following year.<ref name=\"Train\">{{cite news\n |url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/staffordshire/5198728.stm\n |title = Dozens hurt on Alton Towers ride\n |work = BBC News\n |date = 20 July 2006\n |accessdate = 11 August 2009\n}}</ref>\n\n== Court cases ==\nOn 3 May 2012 a couple from the local village of Farley won the rights to a full High Court trial on the amount of noise generated by the park. The couple have been in a legal battle with the park for nearly a decade, and during this period succeeded in a noise abatement order on the theme park which led to the audio from the top of the [[Oblivion (roller coaster)|Oblivion]] drop being removed, and Alton Towers having to limit the amount of annual fireworks displays to only three a year.\n\nStephen and Suzanne Roper, who live only 100 yards from the park, say that their lives have been made a misery by the noise of the screams as well as fireworks displays and music. They launched their legal fight in 2002, but after years of wrangling, their claim for an injunction and damages was thrown out in January 2011. Judge [[Gary Hickinbottom|Mr Justice Hickinbottom]] later overturned that decision, bringing the claim back. This now paves the way for a full court hearing. The Ropers will seek an injunction forcing the park owners to close or relocate some rides and an order forcing them to pay damages for noise suffered from 1998 to the present.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thisisstaffordshire.co.uk/Theme-park-noise-battle-reignited/story-15990916-detail/story.html |title=Theme park noise battle is reignited |publisher=This is Staffordshire |date=3 May 2012 |accessdate=24 July 2012}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Incidents at European amusement parks]]\n* [[List of theme parks in the United Kingdom]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n<!--\n**************************************************************** \nPlease DO NOT add fansites here. Wikipedia is not a web\ndirectory, any sites added will be removed.\nSee [[Wikipedia:External Links]]\n**************************************************************** \n-->\n{{Commons category|Alton Towers|Alton Towers Resort}}\n{{Wikivoyage}}\n* {{official website|http://www.altontowers.com}}\n* [http://www.lostheritage.org.uk/houses/lh_staffordshire_altontowers.html Lost Heritage: full architectural history of the house]\n* {{cite web|url=http://www.twilightblue.eu/en/articles/alton-towers/alton-tower-theme-areas.aspx|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091001182657/http://www.twilightblue.eu/en/articles/alton-towers/alton-tower-theme-areas.aspx|archivedate=1 October 2009|title=Description of Theme Areas}}\n* [http://www.britishpathe.com/record.php?id=8341 1930 film of Alton Towers]\n* [http://www.heraldry-online.org.uk/alton-towers/alton-towers1.htm Heraldry at Alton Towers]\n* [http://www.joylandbooks.com/themagiceye/articles/inland-parks-before-they-were-famous.htm Alton Towers: Before it was Famous (on themagiceye at Joyland)]\n\n{{Alton Towers}}\n{{Merlin attractions}}\n{{John Wardley}}\n{{British theme parks}}\n{{15 inch gauge railways}}\n\n[[Category:Merlin Entertainments Group]]\n[[Category:Gardens in Staffordshire]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions of the Peak District]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Staffordshire]]\n[[Category:Gothic Revival architecture in Staffordshire]]\n[[Category:1860 establishments in England]]\n[[Category:Amusement parks in England]]\n[[Category:Country houses in Staffordshire]]\n[[Category:British country houses destroyed in the 20th century]]\n[[Category:Alton Towers]]\n[[Category:Augustus Pugin buildings]]\n", "name_user": "Detachio", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eThe Smiler:Clarification", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alton_Towers"}
{"title_page": "Glossary of tennis terms", "text_new": "{{short description|Wikipedia glossary}}\nThis page is a [[glossary]] of [[tennis]] terminology.\n{{compact ToC | refs=yes|extlinks=yes}}\n\n==A==\n* {{Anchor|Ace|ace}} '''[[Ace (tennis)|Ace]]''': Serve where the tennis ball lands inside the ''[[#service box|service box]]'' and is not touched by the receiver; thus, a shot that is both a serve and a winner is an ace. Aces are usually powerful and generally land on or near one of the corners at the back of the service box. Initially, the term was used to indicate the scoring of a point.{{sfnp|Grasso|2011|p=19|ps=}}{{sfnp|Shine|2003|p=3|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Action|action}} '''Action''': Synonym of ''[[#spin|spin]]''\n* {{Anchor|Ad court|ad court}} '''Ad court''': Left side of the court''' '''of each player, so called because the ''ad'' (''advantage'') point immediately following a deuce is always served to this side of the court.{{sfnp|Shine|2003|p=3|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Ad|ad}} '''Ad''': Used by the chair umpire to announce the score when a player has the ''[[#advantage|advantage]]'', meaning they won the point immediately after a ''[[#deuce|deuce]]''. See [[scoring in tennis]]\n* {{Anchor|Advantage set|advantage set|Advantage format|advantage format}} '''Advantage set''': Set won by a player or team having won at least six games with a two-game advantage over the opponent (as opposed to a [[#Tiebreakbreak|tiebreak format]]). Final sets in the singles draws of the [[French Open]] remains the only major tennis event to use all advantage sets. In the past, they were used at [[Tennis at the Summer Olympics|Olympic tennis events]] (until 2012), [[Davis Cup]] (until 2015), [[Fed Cup]] (until 2015), [[Australian Open]] (until 2018) and [[The Championships, Wimbledon|Wimbledon]] (until 2018) when they all switched to tie breaks.\n* {{Anchor|Advantage|advantage|}} '''Advantage''': When one player wins the first point from a ''[[#deuce|deuce]]'' and needs one more point to win the game; not applicable when using deciding points.{{sfnp|Grasso|2011|p=19|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|All-Comers|all-comers}} '''All-Comers''': Tournament in which all players took part except the reigning champion. The winner of the All-Comers event would play the title holder in the ''[[#Challenge Round|Challenge Round]]''.{{sfnp|Hedges|1978|p=251|ps=}}{{sfnp|Grasso|2011|p=22|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|All-court|all-court|all court}} '''All-court''' (or '''All-court game'''): Style of play that is a composite of all the different playing styles, which includes baseline, transition, and serve and volley styles.{{sfnp|Shannon|1981|p=539|ps=}}{{sfnp|Shine|2003|pp=5\u20136|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|All|all}} '''All''': Used by the chair umpire to announce scores when both players have the same number of points or the same number of games. When both players are at 40, the preferred term is ''[[#deuce|deuce]]''.{{sfnp|Grasso|2011|p=22|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Alley|Tramlines|alley|tramlines}} '''Alley''': Area of the court between the singles and the doubles sidelines, which together are known as ''[[#tramline|tramlines]]''.{{sfnp|Grasso|2011|p=23|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Alternate|alternate}} '''Alternate''': Player or team that gains acceptance into the main draw of a tournament when a main draw player or team withdraws. Such a player may be a ''[[#lucky loser|lucky loser]]''.\n* {{Anchor|Approach shot|approach shot}} '''Approach shot''': A ''[[#groundstroke|groundstroke]]'' shot used as a setup as the player approaches the net, often using underspin or topspin.{{sfnp|Shine|2003|p=8|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|ATP Champions Race|ATP champions race|atp Champions Race|atp champions race}} '''ATP Champions' Race''' (or '''ATP Rankings Race To London'''): ATP point ranking system that starts at the beginning of the year and by the end of the year mirrors the ATP entry system ranking. The top eight players at the end of the year qualify for the [[ATP Finals]].<ref name=atprankingsfaq/>\n* {{Anchor|ATP World Tour Finals|ATP WTF}} '''ATP Finals''': Formerly known as the ''Tennis Masters Cup'' (see [[#T|T]] below), it is the annual season-ending tournament featuring eight of the top-ranked men in the world (plus two alternates).<ref>{{cite web|title=Tournaments \u2013 ATP World Tour Finals|url=http://www.atpworldtour.com/Tennis/Tournaments/London-Finals.aspx|website=www.atpworldtour.com|publisher=[[Association of Tennis Professionals]] (ATP)}}</ref>\n* {{Anchor|ATP|atp|Association of Tennis Professionals|Association of tennis professionals|association of tennis professionals}} '''ATP''': Abbreviation for [[Association of Tennis Professionals]], the main organizing body of men's professional tennis; governs the ATP World Tour with the largest tournaments for men.\n* {{Anchor|Australian formation|australian formation}} '''Australian formation''': In doubles, a formation where the server and partner stand on the same side of the court before starting the point.<ref>{{cite web|author1=Kathleen Krajco|title=Australian Doubles Strategy|url=http://www.tennisserver.com/wildcards/wildcards_02_06.html|publisher=The Tennis Server}}</ref>{{sfnp|Shine|2003|p=9|ps=}}\n\n==B==\n\n[[File:Ball kid - 2010 Australian Open.jpg|thumb|180px|A ''[[#ball boy|Ball boy]]'' in action]]\n* {{Anchor|Backcourt|backcourt}} '''Backcourt''': The area of the tennis court between the ''[[#baseline|baseline]]'' and the ''e line]]''.{{sfnp|Shine|2003|p=10|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Backhand|backhand}} '''[[Backhand]]''': Stroke in which the ball is hit with the back of the racket hand facing the ball at the moment of contact. A backhand is often hit by a right-handed player when the ball is on the left side of the court, and vice versa.{{sfnp|Hedges|1978|p=251|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Backhand smash|backhand smash}} '''Backhand smash''': A type of ''[[#smash|smash]]'' played over the backhand side.{{sfnp|Shine|2003|p=10|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Backspin|backspin}} '''[[Backspin]]''': Shot that rotates the ball backwards after it is hit; also known as ''[[#slice|slice]]'' or ''underspin''. The trajectory of the shot is affected by an upward force that lifts the ball. See [[Magnus effect]].{{sfnp|Shine|2003|p=10|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Backswing|backswing}} '''Backswing''': Portion of a swing where the racket is swung backwards in preparation for the forward motion to hit the ball.{{sfnp|Hedges|1978|p=251|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Bagel|bagel}} '''[[Bagel (tennis)|Bagel]]''': Colloquial term for winning or losing a set 6\u20130 (the shape of the zero being reminiscent of the round shape of a [[bagel]]). See also ''[[#breadstick|breadstick]]''.<ref>{{cite web|title=BuzzWord \u2013 Bagel|url=http://www.macmillandictionary.com/buzzword/entries/bagel.html|website=www.macmillandictionary.com|publisher=Macmillan}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author1=Peter Bodo|title=Bagel, Anyone?|url=http://www.tennis.com/pro-game/2011/07/bagel-anyone/41515/#.VOs5h3zF8rs|publisher=Tennis.com|date=26 July 2011}}</ref>{{sfnp|Shine|2003|p=11|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Bagnall\u2013Wild|bagnall\u2013wildl}} '''Bagnall\u2013Wild''': A method of draw which places all byes in the first round. Introduced in the 1880s.<ref>{{cite book|title=Wright & Ditson's Lawn Tennis Guide for 1893|location=Boston|publisher=Wright & Ditson|pages=[https://archive.org/details/wrightditsonoff20unkngoog/page/n145 124], 125|url=https://archive.org/details/wrightditsonoff20unkngoog|editor=Joseph T. Whittelsey|oclc=32300203|year=1893}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Gillmeister|first=Heiner|title=Tennis : A Cultural History|url=https://archive.org/details/tennisculturalhi0000gill|url-access=registration|year=1998|publisher=Leicester University Press|location=London|isbn=978-0718501952|page=[https://archive.org/details/tennisculturalhi0000gill/page/355 355]|edition=Repr.}}</ref>\n* {{Anchor|Ball Boy|Ball boy|ball boy}} '''[[Ball boy]]''' (also '''ball girl''' or '''ballkid'''): a person, commonly a child tasked with retrieving tennis balls from the court that have gone out of play and supplying the balls to the players before their service. Ball boys in ''net'' positions normally kneel near the net and run across the court to collect the ball, while ball boys in the ''back'' positions stand in the back along the perimeter of the arena. Ball boys in the back are responsible for giving the balls to the player serving.{{sfnp|Shine|2003|p=13|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Ball toss|ball toss}} '''Ball toss''': The action of throwing up the ball prior to the ''[[#serve|serve]]''.{{sfnp|Shine|2003|p=13|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Baseline|baseline}} '''[[Wiktionary:Baseline|Baseline]]''': Line at the farthest ends of the court indicating the boundary of the area of play. If the ball goes over the baseline it will be the other player's point.{{sfnp|Hedges|1978|p=252|ps=}}{{sfnp|Shine|2003|p=14|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Baseliner|baseliner}} '''baseliner''': Player who plays around the baseline during play and relies on the quality of his or her ground strokes.{{sfnp|Shine|2003|p=14|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Big serve|big serve}} '''Big serve''': Forceful serve, usually giving an advantage in the point for the server.\n* {{Anchor|Bisque|bisque}} '''Bisque''': One stroke (point), which may be claimed by the receiver at any part of the set. Part of the handicapping odds and used during the early era of the sport. Abolished by the LTA in 1890.<ref>{{cite news|title=Lawn Tennis Association|url=http://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0000206/18900130/001/0003|work=Manchester Courier and Lancashire General Advertiser|publisher=[[British Newspaper Archive]]|date=30 January 1890|url-access=subscription }}</ref>\n* {{Anchor|Block|block}} '''Block''' (or '''blocked return'''): Defensive shot with relatively little backswing and shortened action instead of a full swing, usually while returning a serve.{{sfnp|Shine|2003|p=17|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Bounce|bounce}} '''Bounce''': The upward movement of the ball after it has hit the ground. The trajectory of the bounce can be affected by the surface and weather, the amount and type of spin and the power of the shot.{{sfnp|Hedges|1978|p=252|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Breadstick|breadstick}} '''Breadstick''': Colloquial term for winning or losing a set 6\u20131, with the straight shape of the one supposedly being reminiscent of the straight shape of a breadstick. See also ''[[#bagel|bagel]]''.<ref>{{cite web|author1=Carl Bialik|title=Radwanska's Bakery of Odd Results|url=https://blogs.wsj.com/dailyfix/2013/07/03/radwanskas-bakery-of-odd-results/|publisher=The Wall Street Journal|date=3 July 2013}}</ref>\n* {{Anchor|Break back|break back}} '''Break back''': To win a game as the receiving player or team immediately after losing the previous game as the serving player or team.\n* {{Anchor|Break point|break point}} '''Break point''': Point which, if won by the receiver, would result in a break of service; arises when the score is 30\u201340 or 40\u2013ad. A double break point or two break points arises at 15\u201340; a triple break point or three break points arises at 0\u201340.{{sfnp|Shine|2003|p=18|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Break|break}} '''[[Wiktionary:break|Break]]''': To win a game as the receiving player or team, thereby breaking serve. At high level of play the server is more likely to win a game, so breaks are often key moments of a match. Noun: ''break (service break)'' (e.g. \"to be a break down\" means \"to have, in a set, one break fewer than the opponent\", \"to be a double break up\" means \"to have, in a set, two breaks more than the opponent\").{{sfnp|Shine|2003|pp=17\u201318|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Breaker|breaker}} '''Breaker''': Colloquial term for ''[[#tiebreak|tiebreak]]''.{{sfnp|Shine|2003|p=18|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Buggy whip|buggy whip}} '''Buggy whip''': Forehand hit with a follow-through that does not go across the body and finish on the opposite side, but rather goes from low to high, crosses the opposite shoulder (optionally) and finishes on the same side (similar to the driver of a horse-drawn carriage whipping a horse). Used, for example, by [[Rafael Nadal]] (racket head crosses the opposite shoulder) and [[Maria Sharapova]] (racket head stays on the same shoulder).<ref>{{cite book|last1=Hoskins|first1=Tina|title=The Tennis Drill Book|date=2003|publisher=Human Kinetics|location=Champaign, Ill. ;Leeds|isbn=978-0736049122|page=[https://archive.org/details/tennisdrillbook0000hosk/page/23 23]|url=https://archive.org/details/tennisdrillbook0000hosk|url-access=registration}}</ref>\n* {{Anchor|Bumper guard|bumper guard}} '''Bumper guard''': A piece of plastic that protects the outside of the upper-half of the racket head.{{sfnp|Shine|2003|p=18|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Bye|bye}} '''[[Bye (sports)|Bye]]''': Automatic advancement of a player to the next round of a tournament without facing an opponent. Byes are often awarded in the first round to the top-seeded players in a tournament.{{sfnp|Hedges|1978|p=252|ps=}}\n*'''Bunt''': To use the power of the opponents shot and hit it back with a short swing.\n\n==C==\n[[File:Tennis court imperial.svg|thumb|180px|A tennis ''[[#court|court]]'' with its dimensions and components]]\n\n* {{Anchor|Call|call}} '''Call''': Verbal utterance by a line judge or chair umpire declaring that a ball landed outside the valid area of play.{{sfnp|Shine|2003|p=19|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Can Opener|Can opener|can opener}} '''Can opener''': Serve hit by a right-handed player with slice, landing on or near the intersection of the singles tramline and service line in the deuce court (or in the ad court for a left-handed server).\n* {{Anchor|Cannonball|cannonball}} '''Cannonball''': Somewhat archaic term for a very fast, flat serve.{{sfnp|Shine|2003|p=19|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Career Golden Slam}} '''Career Golden Slam''': In addition to having won all four major titles in their career, a player that has also won an Olympic gold medal is said to have achieved a career Golden Slam. Only four players have ever achieved this in singles: [[Steffi Graf]] (1988), [[Andre Agassi]] (1996), [[Rafael Nadal]] (2010) and [[Serena Williams]] (2012). The term is rarely used in doubles, although the feat has been more common in that discipline. It has been achieved individually by nine wheelchair tennis players and three able-bodied players ([[Pam Shriver]], [[Gigi Fern\u00e1ndez]], [[Daniel Nestor]]), and by three teams ([[The Woodies]], the [[Williams sisters]], and the [[Bryan brothers]]). [[Tennis at the Summer Olympics|Tennis at the Olympics]] was not played 1928\u20131984.\n* {{Anchor|Career Grand Slam|career grand slam}} '''Career Grand Slam''' (or '''career slam'''): Players who have won all four Major championships over the course of their career (but not within the same calendar year) are said to have won a career Grand Slam.<ref name=\"oup\"/>\n* {{Anchor|Carpet|carpet|carpet court}} '''Carpet''': A surface for tennis courts consisting of textile or polymer materials supplied in rolls. Previously common for indoor professional events, the surface was dropped from major pro tournaments in 2009. See [[carpet court]].\n* {{Anchor|Carve|carve}} '''Carve''': To hit a groundstroke shot with a combination of sidespin and underspin.\n* {{Anchor|Centre Mark|Centre mark|centre mark}} '''Centre mark''': Small mark located at the centre of the baseline. When serving the player must stand on the correct side of the mark corresponding with the score.{{sfnp|Shannon|1981|p=540|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Challenge Round|Challenge round|challenge round}} '''Challenge Round''': Final round of a tournament, in which the winner of a [[Single-elimination tournament|single-elimination]] phase faces the previous year's champion, who plays only that one match. The challenge round was used in the early history of [[The Championships, Wimbledon|Wimbledon]] (from 1877 through 1921) and the [[US Open (tennis)|US Open]] (from 1884 through 1911), and, until 1972, in the [[Davis Cup]].{{sfnp|Hedges|1978|p=251|ps=}}{{sfnp|Shine|2003|p=21\u201332|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Challenge|challenge}} '''Challenge''': When a player requests an official review of the spot where the ball landed, using electronic ball tracking technology. See [[Hawk-Eye]]. Challenges are only available in some large tournaments.\n* {{Anchor|Challenger|challenger}} '''Challenger''': A tour of tournaments one level below the top-tier [[ATP World Tour]]. Currently, Challenger tournaments compose the [[ATP Challenger Tour]]. Players, generally ranked around world no. 80 to world no. 300, compete on the Challenger tour in an effort to gain ranking points which allow them to gain entry to tournaments on the ATP World Tour.\n* {{Anchor|Change-over|change-over}} '''Change-over''' (or '''change of ends'''): 90 second rest time after every odd-numbered game when the players change ends.{{sfnp|Shine|2003|p=22|ps=}}<ref name=\"oup\">{{cite web |title=Tennis words amongst those to be added to the Oxford English Dictionary |url=https://global.oup.com/academic/news/June272017?cc=de&lang=en& |website=[[Oxford University Press]] |date=27 June 2017}}</ref>\n* {{Anchor|Chip and charge|chip and charge}} '''Chip and charge''': Type of approach shot which involves hitting a slice shot while rapidly moving forward and following the shot into the net. Aimed at putting the opponent under pressure.{{sfnp|Shine|2003|p=23|ps=}}<ref name=\"oup\"/>\n* {{Anchor|Chip|chip}} '''Chip''': Blocking a shot with underspin, creating a low trajectory.{{sfnp|Shine|2003|p=23|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Chop|chop}} '''Chop''': Shot hit with extreme underspin, opposite of topspin.{{sfnp|Hedges|1978|p=252|ps=}}{{sfnp|Robertson|1974|p=217|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Clay|clay}} '''Clay''': a natural surface made of crushed [[shale]], [[stone]], [[brick]] or [[clay]] on which tennis is played, most notably at the [[French Open]]. See: [[clay court]].\n* {{Anchor|Closed stance|closed stance}} '''Closed stance''': Classic technique in which the ball is hit while the hitter's body is facing at an angle between parallel to the baseline and with his back turned to the opponent.{{sfnp|Shine|2003|pp=25\u201326|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Code Violation|Code violation|code violation}} '''Code violation''': a rule violation on the men's and women's professional tour match called by the chair umpire which results in a player receiving an official warning or a penalty. The first violation results in a warning; the second, a point penalty; the third and more, a game penalty each. A code violation may also be judged severe enough to result in the player having to forfeit the match immediately (without having to go through the three or more automatic penalty stages). There often follows additional monetary fine for each code violation.\n* {{Anchor|Consolidate|consolidate}} '''Consolidate''' (a break): To hold serve in the game immediately following a break of serve.\n* {{Anchor|Continental grip|continental grip}} '''Continental grip''': way of holding the racket in which the bottom knuckle of the index finger is in contact with the top of the handle and the heel of the hand with the bevel directly clockwise from it.<ref name=\"oup\"/>\n* {{Anchor|Counterpuncher|counterpuncher}} '''Counterpuncher''': Defensive ''[[#baseliner|baseliner]]''. See [[tennis strategy]].\n* {{Anchor|Court|court}} '''[[Tennis court|Court]]''': Area designated for playing a game of tennis.<ref name=itfcourt>{{cite web|title=Court Rules|url=http://www.itftennis.com/technical/publications/rules/courts/overview.aspx|website=www.itftennis.com|publisher=[[International Tennis Federation]] (ITF)}}</ref>{{sfnp|Hedges|1978|pp=252\u2013253|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Cross-over|cross-over}} '''Cross-over''': Player crossing the net into the opponent's court. It can be done either in a friendly fashion, or maliciously, thereby invoking a code violation. The latter sometimes happens when it is uncertain whether the ball on a decisive point landed inside or outside the court when playing on clay, thus leaving a mark.\n* {{Anchor|Crosscourt shot|crosscourt shot}} '''Crosscourt shot''': Hitting the ball diagonally into the opponent's court.{{sfnp|Hedges|1978|p=254|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Cyclops|cyclops}} '''[[Cyclops (computer system)|Cyclops]]''': Device formerly used at [[Wimbledon Championships|Wimbledon]] and other tournaments to detect a serve that landed long, past the service line. The device emitted an audible noise when the serve was long. Succeeded by ''[[#Hawk-Eye|Hawk-Eye]]''.{{sfnp|Shine|2003|p=31\u201332|ps=}}\n\n==D==\n[[File:EVD-tenis-090.jpg|thumb|180px|An example of a ''[[#dead net|dead net cord]]'']]\n\n* {{Anchor|Dampener|dampener}} '''Dampener''' A small rubber device affixed to the strings of the racket to absorb some of the vibration caused by hitting the ball.{{sfnp|Shine|2003|p=32|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Davis Cup|Davis cup|davis cup}} '''[[Davis Cup]]''': International, annual men's tennis competition in which teams from participating countries compete in a single-elimination format, with matches occurring at several stages during the year.{{sfnp|Robertson|1974|pp=225\u2013231|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Dead net|Dead net cord|dead net|dead net cord}} '''Dead net''' (or '''dead net cord'''): Situation in which a player scores by inadvertently hitting the ball in such a way that it touches the upper cord of the net and rolls over to the other side; the player is said to have \"gotten (caught) a dead net (dead net cord)\" and considered to be lucky.\n* {{Anchor|Dead Rubber|Dead rubber|dead rubber}} '''[[Dead rubber]]''': Davis/Fed Cup match which is played after the victor of the tie has already been decided. Dead rubbers may or may not be played, depending on the coaches' agreement to do so, and are usually best of three, instead of five, sets. Typically, players who play the dead rubber are lower-ranked members of the team looking to gain Davis/Fed Cup match experience.<ref name=nytrubber/>\n* {{Anchor|Deciding point|deciding point}} '''Deciding point''': In doubles, the point played when the game score reaches deuce and there is no ad play; the game is decided in favor of whichever team wins the deuce point.\n* {{Anchor|Deep shot|deep shot}} '''Deep shot''': Shot that lands near the baseline, as opposed to near the net or mid-court.\n* {{Anchor|Default|default}} '''Default''': Disqualification of a player in a match by the chair umpire after the player has received four [[Tennis terminology#Code violation|code violation]] warnings, generally for his/her conduct on court. A '''double default''' occurs when both players are disqualified. Defaults also occur when a player misses a match with no valid excuse. Defaults are considered losses.\n* {{Anchor|Deuce court|deuce court}} '''deuce court''': Right side of the court of each player, so called because it is the area into which the ball is served when the score is deuce.\n* {{Anchor|Deuce|deuce}} '''Deuce''': Score of 40\u201340 in a game. A player must win two consecutive points from a deuce to win the game, unless the tournament employs ''deciding points'', as in the 2010 ATP World Tour Finals. A player who has won one point after deuce is said to have the [[#advantage|''advantage'']].\n* {{Anchor|Dink|dink}} '''Dink''': [[Onomatopoetic]] term for a shot with little ''pace'', usually hit close to the net.{{sfnp|Shine|2003|p=35|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Dirtballer|dirtballer}} '''Dirtballer''': Colloquial term for a [[clay court specialist]].{{sfnp|Shine|2003|p=35|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Disadvantage|Disadvantage}} '''Disadvantage''': Player or team which is 40-advantage down.\n* {{Anchor|Double Bagel|Double bagel|double bagel}} '''Double bagel''': Two sets won to love; see ''[[#bagel|bagel]]''.{{sfnp|Shine|2003|p=36|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Double Fault|Double fault|double fault}} '''Double fault''': Two serving faults in a row in one point, causing the player serving to lose the point.{{sfnp|Shine|2003|p=36|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Doubles|doubles|Men's Doubles|Men's doubles|women's doubles|Women's Doubles|Women's doubles|women's doubles}} '''Doubles''': Match played by four players, two per side of the court. A doubles court is 9&nbsp;ft (2.97m) wider than a singles court.{{sfnp|Robertson|1974|p=234|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Down the line|down the line}} '''Down the line''': Ball hit straight along the sideline to the opponent's side of the court.{{sfnp|Hedges|1978|p=254|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Draw|draw|Qualifying Draw|Qualifying draw|qualifying draw|Main Draw|Main draw|main draw}} '''Draw''': The schedule of matches in a tennis tournament. The starting fixtures are determined by a combined process of player ''seeding'' and random selection, and may or may not involve a public ''draw ceremony''. A ''qualifying draw'' is set up to arrange the starting lineup of the qualifying competition (''qualies''), from where ''unseeded'' players qualify for a place in the starting lineup or the ''main draw'' of the tournament.{{sfnp|Hedges|1978|p=254|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Drive Volley|Drive volley|drive volley|Swing Volley|Swing volley|swing volley}} '''[[Drive volley]]''' (or '''swing volley'''): a tennis volley executed with full swing or topspin drive, thus with pace and conventionally at shoulder height; in the manner of a forehand or backhand swing.{{sfnp|Shannon|1981|p=542|ps=}}<ref>[https://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/drive-volley Drive Volley ''Merriam Webster'']</ref>\n* {{Anchor|Drop Shot|Drop shot|drop shot}} '''[[Drop shot]]''': Play in which the player hits the ball lightly enough to just go over the net, usually with ''backspin''; designed to catch a player who is away from the net off guard.{{sfnp|Hedges|1978|p=254|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Drop Volley|Drop volley|drop volley}} '''Drop volley''': ''Drop shot'' executed from a ''volley'' position.\n\n==E==\n* {{Anchor|Elbow|elbow}} '''Elbow''': Corner of the baseline and the doubles alley.\n* {{Anchor|Entry System|Entry system|entry system}} '''Entry system''': Ranking system used by the ATP and WTA tours, so named because it determines whether a player has a sufficiently high ranking to gain direct acceptance (not as a qualifier or wild card) into the main draw of a tournament. A player's Entry System ranking is different from his or her Race ranking, which is reset to zero at the beginning of each year. A player carries points and the associated Entry ranking continuously unless those points are lost at a tournament at which the player had previously earned them.\n* {{Anchor|Error|error}} '''Error''':  A shot that does not land (correctly) in the opponent's court, resulting in the loss of a point.{{sfnp|Shannon|1981|p=542|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Exhibition|exhibition}} '''Exhibition''': Tournament in which players compete for the purpose of entertaining the crowd or raising money, but not ranking points on the ATP or WTA tours.\n\n==F==\n[[File:2014 US Open (Tennis) - Tournament - Bernard Tomic (14954485718).jpg|thumb|180px|Example of a ''[[#follow though|follow through]]'' action after the ball is hit]]\n\n* {{Anchor|Fault|fault}} '''Fault''': Serve that fails to land the ball in the opponent's service box, therefore not starting the point. See also ''double fault'' and ''foot fault''.{{sfnp|Hedges|1978|pp=254\u2013255|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Fed Cup|Fed cup|fed cup}} '''[[Fed Cup]]''' (or '''Federation Cup'''): International, annual women's tennis competition in which teams from participating countries compete in a single-elimination format tournament with matches occurring at several stages during the year.{{sfnp|Robertson|1974|pp=241\u2013243|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|First Service|First service|first service}} '''First serve''': The first of the two attempts to serve that a player is allowed at the beginning of a point. A let serve that lands inbounds does not count as a serve.\n* {{Anchor|Five|five}} '''Five''': Number of games completed (e.g. \"7\u20135\" is spoken as \"seven\u2013five\"), or a spoken abbreviation of \"15\" in points (e.g. a score of 40\u201315 is sometimes spoken as \"forty\u2013five\").\n* {{Anchor|Flat|flat}} '''[[Flat (tennis)|Flat]]''' (or '''flat shot'''): Shot with relatively little spin and usually hard-hit.{{sfnp|Shannon|1981|p=542|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Flatliner|flatliner}} '''Flatliner''': Player who hits the ball ''flat'' with a very low trajectory with exceptional depth and accuracy. Examples include [[Andre Agassi]] and [[Lindsay Davenport]].\n* {{Anchor|Follow through|follow through}} '''Follow through''': Portion of a swing after the ball is hit.{{sfnp|Robertson|1974|p=243|ps=}}{{sfnp|Shannon|1981|p=542|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Foot Fault|Foot fault|foot fault}} '''Foot fault''': Type of service fault in which a player, during the serve, steps on or over the baseline into the court before striking the ball. A foot fault may also occur if the player steps on or across the center hash mark and its imaginary perpendicular extension from the baseline to the net. The definition of a foot fault has changed several times since the introduction of (lawn) tennis.{{sfnp|Hedges|1978|p=255|ps=}} \n* {{Anchor|Forced error|forced error}} '''Forced error''': Error caused by an opponent's good play; contrasted with an ''[[#unforced error|unforced error]]''. Counting forced errors as well as unforced errors is partly subjective.{{sfnp|Shannon|1981|p=542|ps=}}<ref name=\"oup\"/>\n* {{Anchor|Forehand|forehand}} '''[[Forehand]]''': Stroke in which the player hits the ball with the front of the racket hand facing the ball; contrasted with ''backhand''.{{sfnp|Hedges|1978|p=255|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Frame shot|frame shot}} '''Frame shot''': A mishit on the frame of the racket rather than the strings. \n* {{Anchor|Fry|fry}} '''Fry''': See ''[[#breadstick|breadstick]]''.\n* {{Anchor|Futures|futures}} '''Futures''': Series of men's tour tennis tournaments which compose the [[ITF Men's Circuit]], a tour two levels below the ATP World Tour and one level below the ATP Challenger Tour. Players compete in Futures events (generally when ranked below world no. 300 or so) to garner enough ranking points to gain entry into Challenger events.\n\n==G==\n* {{Anchor|Game point|game point}} '''[[Tennis score|Game point]]''': Situation in which the server is leading and needs one more point to win the game. See also ''[[#break point|break point]]''.{{sfnp|Shannon|1981|p=543|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Game|game}} '''Game''': A game consists of a sequence of ''[[#point|points]]'' played with the same player serving and is a segment of a ''set''. Each ''set'' consists of at least six games.{{sfnp|Shannon|1981|p=543|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Get|get}} '''Get''': Reaching and returning a ball that is difficult to retrieve.\n* {{Anchor|Ghost in to the net|Ghost into the Net}} '''Ghost in to the net''': To approach the net from the baseline while the opposing player is focused on retrieving a ball and therefore unaware that the player is approaching the net.\n* {{Anchor|GOAT}} '''GOAT''': Colloquial acronym for ''Greatest Of All Time''.\n* {{Anchor|Golden Bagel Award|Golden Bagel award|golden bagel award}} '''[[Golden Bagel Award]]''': Award for male players winning the most ''bagels'' (sets won 6\u20130), from January 1 until the year-end tournament. Davis Cup matches and incomplete sets are not counted.\n* {{Anchor|Golden Set|Golden set|Golden set}} '''[[Golden set (tennis)|Golden set]]''': A set that is won without dropping a single point.\n* {{Anchor|Golden Slam|Golden slam|golden slam}} '''[[Golden Slam]]''': Winning the Grand Slam and the [[Tennis at the Summer Olympics|tennis Olympic]] gold medal in a calendar year. This has only ever been achieved once, by [[Steffi Graf]] in 1988. See also ''career Golden Slam''\n* {{Anchor|Grand Slam|Grand Slams|Grand slam|grand slam}} '''[[Grand Slam (tennis)|Grand Slam]]''': Winning all four of the prestigious major tournaments in a calendar year. \"Grand Slam\" is also commonly used to refer to any one of the four tournaments: the [[Australian Open]], the [[French Open]] (Roland Garros), [[Wimbledon Championships|Wimbledon]], and the [[U.S. Open (tennis)|U.S. Open]].  See also [[#Career Grand Slam|Career Grand Slam]].{{sfnp|Hedges|1978|p=255|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|grass}} '''Grass''': A natural [[Lawn#Uses|turf]] surface tennis is played on, most notably at [[The Championships, Wimbledon|Wimbledon]].  See: [[grass court]].\n* {{Anchor|Grinding|grinding}} '''Grinding''': Playing out points with a series of shots from the baseline. See also [[Wear|attrition]].\n* {{Anchor|Grip|grip}} '''Grip''': A way of holding the racket in order to hit shots during a match. The three most commonly used conventional grips are the Continental, the Eastern and the Western. Most players change grips during a match depending on which shot they are hitting. For further information on grips, including all the types, see [[grip (tennis)]].{{sfnp|Robertson|1974|pp=257\u2013258|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Grommet strip|grommet strip}} '''Grommet strip''': A strip of plastic containing small tubes that are placed in the frame's string holes to prevent the strings from rubbing against the abrasive frame.{{sfnp|Shine|2003|p=56|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Groundies|groundies}} '''Groundie''': Colloquial word for a ''[[#groundstroke|groundstroke]]''.\n* {{Anchor|Groundstroke|groundstroke}} '''[[Groundstroke]]''': Forehand or backhand shot that is executed after the ball bounces once on the court.{{sfnp|Shannon|1981|p=543|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Grunting|grunting}} '''[[grunting (tennis)|Grunting]]''': Noises made by players while either serving or hitting the ball.{{sfnp|Hedges|1978|p=256|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Natural Gut|Natural gut|natural gut}} '''[[Strings (tennis)#Natural Gut|Gut]]''': Type of racket string. Can be made from [[catgut]] or synthetic gut.{{sfnp|Shannon|1981|p=543|ps=}}\n\n==H==\n* {{Anchor|Hacker|hacker}} '''Hacker''': Player whose clumsy strokes seem more accidental than intentional.{{sfnp|Shannon|1981|p=543|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Hail Mary|Hail mary|hail Mary|hail mary}} '''Hail Mary''': Extremely high lob, for defensive purposes.\n* {{Anchor|Half court|half court}} '''Half court''': The area of the court in the vicinity of the service line.\n* {{Anchor|Half volley|half volley}} '''[[Half volley]]''': A groundstroke shot made immediately after a bounce or simultaneous to the bounce and played with the racket close to the ground.{{sfnp|Hedges|1978|p=256|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Handicapping|handicapping}} '''Handicapping''' A system in which competitors are given advantages or compensations to equalize the chances of winning.{{sfnp|Hedges|1978|p=256|ps=}}{{sfnp|Robertson|1974|pp=258\u2013259|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Hardcourt|hardcourt}} '''Hardcourt''' (or '''hard court'''): A type of court which is made of asphalt or concrete with a synthetic/acrylic layer on top. They can vary in color and tend to play medium-fast to fast.\n* {{Anchor|Hawk-Eye|Hawk-eye|hawk-eye|Hawkeye|hawkeye}} '''[[Hawk-Eye]]''': Computer system connected to cameras to track the path of the ball for replay purposes; used with the player challenge system to contest and review designated [[#line call|line call]]s.\n* {{Anchor|Head|head}} '''Head''' (or '''racket head'''): Portion of the racket that contains the strings.{{sfnp|Shine|2003|p=97|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Heavy|heavy}} '''Heavy''' (ball): Ball hit with so much topspin that it feels \"heavy\" when the opposing player strikes it.\n* {{Anchor|Hit and giggle|hit and giggle}} '''Hit and giggle''': non-competitive social tennis.\n* {{Anchor|Hitting Partner|Hitting partner|hitting partner}} '''Hitting partner''' (or '''sparring partner'''): specialist employed by a tennis player to practice strokes during training\n* {{Anchor|Hold|hold}} '''Hold''' (or '''hold serve'''): To win the game when serving. Compare ''break''.\n\n==I==\n* {{Anchor|I-formation|i-formation}} '''[[I-formation (tennis)|I-formation]]''': Formation used in doubles where the net player on the serving team crouches roughly at the centre service line; used mainly to counter teams that prefer a crosscourt return.{{sfnp|Grasso|2011|p=143|ps=}}<ref>{{cite web|author1=David Cox|title=The I Formation: when, why and how to use it|url=http://www.tennis.com.au/news/2014/07/30/the-i-formation-when-why-and-how-to-use-it|publisher=Tennis Australia|date=30 July 2014}}</ref>\n* {{Anchor|Inside-in|inside-in|}} '''Inside-in''': Running around the backhand side to hit a forehand ''down the line.'' Vice versa for inside in backhand.\n* {{Anchor|Inside-out|inside-out}} '''Inside-out''': Running around the backhand side and hitting a ''crosscourt'' forehand. Vice versa for inside out backhand.\n* {{Anchor|Insurance Break|Insurance break|insurance break|}} '''Insurance break''': Break that achieves an overall advantage of two breaks of serve.\n* {{Anchor|ITF|ipin}} '''IPIN''': Abbreviation for International Player Identification Number, a registration number required for all professional tennis players and administered by the governing body ITF.\n* {{Anchor|ITF|ITF entry}} '''ITF entry''': High-ranking ITF players can be awarded a spot into ATP Challenger and ITF women's tournaments main draws based on their ITF ranking.\n* {{Anchor|ITF|itf}} '''ITF''': Abbreviation for [[International Tennis Federation]], the governing body of world tennis. Founded in 1913 as the International Lawn Tennis Federation (ILTF).{{sfnp|Robertson|1974|p=265|ps=}}\n\n==J==\n* {{Anchor|Jamming|jamming}} '''Jamming''': Serving or returning straight into the opponent's body.\n* {{Anchor|Junior exempt|Junior exempt}} '''Junior exempt''' (\"'''JE'''\"): High-ranking junior players can be awarded a spot in the draw of a tournament through the ITF's junior exempt project.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.itftennis.com/juniors/players/junior-exempt.aspx|title=Junior Exempt|publisher=[[International Tennis Federation]]|accessdate=2 February 2016}}</ref>\n* {{Anchor|Junk ball|junk ball}} '''Junk ball''': A shot or return stroke in which the ball tends to be slow and possibly also without spin; often introduced unpredictably to upset the flow of the game and the rhythm of the opposition.\n\n==K==\n\n* {{Anchor|Kick serve|kick serve}} '''[[Twist serve|Kick serve]]''': Type of spin serve that bounces high. Introduced in the United States in the late 1880s and called the ''American twist''.{{sfnp|Hedges|1978|pp=251, 259\u2013260|ps=}}<ref>{{cite web|author1=Rod Croft|title=How to hit a fierce kick serve|url=http://www.tennis.com.au/news/2013/06/06/how-to-hit-a-fierce-kick-serve|website=www.tennis.com.au|publisher=Tennis Australia|date=6 June 2013}}</ref>\n* {{Anchor|Knock-up|knock-up}} '''Knock-up''': Practice or warm-up session without scoring which usually precedes the start of competitive play.{{sfnp|Shannon|1981|p=543|ps=}}<ref>{{cite web|author1=Jonathan Overend|title=Pre-match knock-ups should be scrapped|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/blogs/legacy/jonathanoverend/2011/12/tennis_knock-up.html|website=www.bbc.co.uk|publisher=BBC|date=21 December 2011}}</ref>\n\n==L==\n[[File:Line Judges Centre Court.JPG|thumb|180px|''[[#line judge|Line judges]]'' at [[The Championships, Wimbledon|Wimbledon]]]]\n* {{Anchor|Lawn tennis|Lawn tennis}} '''Lawn tennis''': \"Regular\" tennis, as opposed to [[real tennis]], the game from which tennis is derived. Reflects the fact that the game was first played on grass.{{sfnp|Shine|2003|p=70|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Let-check|let-check}} '''Let-check''': Electronic sensor on the net that assists chair umpires in calling lets by detecting vibration. Typically, it is used only on show courts in professional matches, like electronic review. Players and commentators occasionally complain that such devices are too sensitive, that is, indicate too many [[false positive]]s.\n* {{Anchor|Let|let|Do-over|do-over}} '''Let''': A call that requires the point to be replayed. The umpire indicates this type of let by announcing \"Let. First serve,\" or \"Let. Second serve.\" Lets typically occur when an otherwise-valid serve makes contact with the net before hitting the ground. Theoretically, a player could serve an infinite number of otherwise-valid let serves, but a serve that touches the net and then lands out of bounds counts as one of the two allowed serves. A let can also be called during play when there is some distraction to either player not caused by the players themselves, such as a ball boy moving behind a receiver, debris flying across the court in windy conditions, or a ball accidentally falling out of a player's pocket or entering from a neighboring court. The call is made by the chair umpire when one is assigned to the match, as in professional matches, or one of the players when there is no chair umpire. When a receiver is legitimately unprepared for a serve, a let is technically the result, even if the word goes unspoken.<ref>{{cite book|title=Rules of Tennis|year=2012|publisher=ITF|url=http://www.itftennis.com/media/117960/117960.pdf|page=9}}</ref>{{sfnp|Shine|2003|pp=70\u201371|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Line call|line call}} '''[[Line call]]''' (or '''call'''): Call made by the ''[[#line judge|line judge]]''. A call of 'out' will be made in combination with an outstretched arm pointing sideways if a ball lands outside the court and if the ball is 'in', i.e. lands on or within the outer lines, this is indicated by holding both hands flattened and the arms stretched downwards.{{sfnp|Shine|2003|p=71|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Line judge|line judge}} '''Line judge''' (or '''linesman''', '''lineswoman''' or '''line umpire'''): Person designated to observe the passage of tennis balls over the boundary lines of the court. A line judge can declare that a play was inside or outside the play area and cannot be overruled by the players. Line judges must defer to an umpire's decision, even when it contradicts their own observations.{{sfnp|Hedges|1978|p=256|ps=}}{{sfnp|Grasso|2011|p=175|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Lingering Death tiebreak|Lingering death tiebreak|lingering death tiebreak|Lingering Death|Lingering death|lingering death}} '''Lingering death tiebreak''': Version of the tiebreak played as the best of twelve points, with a two-point advantage needed to clinch the set.{{sfnp|Shine|2003|p=72|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Lob Volley|Lob volley|lob volley}} '''Lob volley''': Type of ''[[#volley|volley]]'' shot aimed at lobbing the ball over the opponent and normally played when the opponent is in the vicinity of the net.{{sfnp|Shannon|1981|p=544|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Lob|lob}} '''[[Lob (tennis)|Lob]]''': Stroke in which the ball is hit high above the net. If the opposing player or players are up at the net, the intention may be an offensive lob in order to win the point outright. In a defensive lob, the intent is to give the player time to recover and get in position, or, if the opponents are at the net, to force them to chase down the lob. See also ''[[#moonball|moonball]]''.{{sfnp|Hedges|1978|p=256|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Love game|love game}} '''Love game''': Shutout game, won without the opponent scoring a single point.{{sfnp|Shine|2003|p=75|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Love|love}} '''Love''': A [[#Scoring|score]] of zero (e.g. \"15-0\" is spoken \"fifteen-love\"; \"to hold to love\" means \"to win the game when serving with the opponent scoring zero points\"; \"to break to love\" means \"to win the game when receiving with the opponent scoring zero points\"). Thought to be derived from the French term, ''l'oeuf'', literally ''the egg'', meaning nothing; less popular alternative theory claiming it to be from the Dutch word ''lof doen'', meaning honour.<ref>Palmatier, Robert.  [https://books.google.com/books?id=kSr4fO2zYrIC&pg=PA245&dq=love+l%27oeuf+tennis&hl=en&ei=Flr8S8ukFYOB8gb_4ND6BQ&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=2&ved=0CC0Q6AEwAQ#v=onepage&q=love%20l%27oeuf%20tennis&f=false Speaking of animals: a dictionary of animal metaphors], page 245 (1995).</ref><ref>Horn, Geoffrey.  [https://books.google.com/books?id=tQoY647Kk-wC&pg=PA13&dq=love+l%27oeuf+tennis&hl=en&ei=Flr8S8ukFYOB8gb_4ND6BQ&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=3&ved=0CDIQ6AEwAg#v=onepage&q=love%20l%27oeuf%20tennis&f=false Rafael Nadal], page 13 (2006).</ref>{{sfnp|Shine|2003|pp=74\u201375|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Lucky Loser|Lucky loser|lucky loser}} '''[[Lucky loser]]''' (\"'''LL'''\"): Highest-ranked player to lose in the final round of qualifying for a tournament, but still ends up qualifying because of a sudden withdrawal by one of the players already in the main draw. In Grand Slam events, one of the four highest-ranked losers in the final qualifying round is randomly picked as the lucky loser.\n\n==M==\n* {{Anchor|Mac-Cam|Mac-cam|mac-cam|MACCam}} '''[[Mac-Cam]]''': High-speed video camera used for televised instant replays of close shots landing on/near the baseline. Name derived from [[John McEnroe]].\n* {{Anchor|Masters Cup|Masters cup|masters cup}} '''[[Masters Cup]]''': Former name of the year-end ATP championship, in which the eight highest-ranked players compete in a [[Round-robin tournament|round-robin]] format.\n* {{Anchor|Match|match}} '''Match''': A contest between two players (singles match)  or two teams of players (doubles match), normally played as the best of three or five sets.{{sfnp|Hedges|1978|p=256|ps=}}{{sfnp|Shannon|1981|p=544|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Match point|match point}} '''Match point''': Situation in which the player who is leading needs one more point to win the match. Variations of the term are possible; e.g. ''championship point'' is the match point in the final match of a championship or a ''gold medal point'' is the match point in the final match of the Olympics.{{sfnp|Shannon|1981|p=544|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Mercedes Super 9|Super 9|super 9|Super Nine|Super nine|super nine}} '''Mercedes Super 9''': Former name for the nine ATP Tour Masters 1000 tournaments.\n* {{Anchor|Mini-break|mini-break}} '''Mini-break''': Point won from the opponent's serve. The term is usually used in a tiebreak, but it can be used during normal service games as well. To be \"up a mini-break\" means that the player has one more mini-break than his/her opponent.\n* {{Anchor|Mini-hold|mini-hold}} '''Mini-hold''': Point won by the server, usually in a tiebreak.\n* {{Anchor|MIPTC|miptc}} '''MIPTC''': Abbreviation for [[Men's International Professional Tennis Council]], administrative body of the tournaments that composed the [[Grand Prix tennis circuit]]. Existed from 1974 until the creation of the [[ATP Tour]] in 1989.\n* {{Anchor|Mis-hit|mis-hit}} '''Mis-hit''': Stroke in which the racket fails to make contact with the ball in the \"sweetspot\" area of the strings.\n* {{Anchor|Mixed Doubles|Mixed doubles|mixed doubles}} '''mixed doubles''': Match played by four players, two male, two female, one of each sex per side of the court.{{sfnp|Shannon|1981|p=544|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Moonball|moonball}} '''Moonball''': A type of groundstroke that is hit with a lot of topspin, usually with the forehand, to create a high, slow, floating shot that lands close to the opponent's baseline. See also ''[[#lob|lob]]''.<ref>{{cite news|author1=Ben Rothenberg|title=Wozniacki Survives Battle of Moonballs|url=http://straightsets.blogs.nytimes.com/2013/03/16/wozniacki-survives-battle-of-moonballs/?_r=0|work=The New York Times|date=16 March 2013|access-date=7 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150207210531/http://straightsets.blogs.nytimes.com/2013/03/16/wozniacki-survives-battle-of-moonballs/?_r=0|archive-date=7 February 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author1=Ron Waite|title=A Tennis Stroke That Is \"Out Of This World\"|url=http://www.tennisserver.com/turbo/turbo_09_02.html|publisher=The Tennis Server}}</ref>\n* {{Anchor|MOP|mop}} '''MOP''': Point at 0\u201330; stands for major opportunity point.\n* '''Main draw''': See ''[[#draw|draw]]''.\n\n==N==\n* {{Anchor|Net cord|net cord|netcord}} '''Net cord''': see ''dead net cord''\n* {{Anchor|Net point|net point}} '''Net point''': Point won or lost on approaching the net, as opposed to a point won or lost by a stroke from the baseline.\n* {{Anchor|Net posts|net posts}} '''Net posts''': Posts on each side of the court which hold up the net. The net posts are placed 3 feet (0.914 m) outside the doubles court on each side, unless a singles net is used, in which case the posts are placed 3 feet (0.914 m) outside the singles court.<ref name=itfcourt/>\n* {{Anchor|Net sticks|net stick}} '''Net sticks''' (or '''[[#singles sticks|singles sticks]]'''): Pair of poles placed on the singles line to support the net during a singles match.{{sfnp|Shannon|1981|p=544|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Net|net}} '''Net''': Interlaced fabric, cord, and tape stretched across the entire width of the court; it is held up by the posts.{{sfnp|Robertson|1974|p=287|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|New balls|new balls}} '''New balls''': New set of balls replacing the old ones during the game from time to time due to the fact that strokes make the ball heat up and alter its bounce characteristics; the player first to serve one of the new balls shows it to the opponent.\n* {{Anchor|No-Man's Land|No man's land|No-man's land|no-man's land|no man's land}} '''No-man's land''': Area between the service line and the baseline, where a player is most vulnerable.{{sfnp|Shannon|1981|p=544|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Non-endemic products|non-endemic products}} '''Non-endemic products''': Products for tennis sponsorship that are not intrinsic to the sport such as watches, cars, jewelry.\n* {{Anchor|Not up|Not Up|not up|not Up}} '''Not up''': Call given by the umpire when a player plays a ball that has already bounced twice, i.e. the ball was out of play when the player played it.\n* {{Anchor|NTRP Rating|NTRP rating|NTRP}} '''NTRP rating''': National Tennis Rating Program rating; system used in the United States to rank players on a scale from 1 to 7, with 1 being an absolute beginner and 7 a touring pro.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.usta.com/USTA/Global/Active/Custom%20Pages/Leagues/1237_NTRP.aspx |title=USTA National Tennis Ranking Program (NTRP) |publisher=[[USTA]] |accessdate=2009-08-21 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090820090732/http://www.usta.com/USTA/Global/Active/Custom%20Pages/Leagues/1237_NTRP.aspx |archive-date=2009-08-20 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==O==\n* {{Anchor|Official|official}} '''[[Official (tennis)|Official]]''': Member of the officiating team: tournament referee, chair umpire, or linesman.\n* {{Anchor|On one's racket|on one's racket}} '''on one's racket''': A situation in which a player can win the match, set, or tiebreak by holding serve.  This occurs when a player breaks the opponent's serve or achieves a mini break in a tiebreak.<ref><!-- \"And Zverev had the match on his racket, with match point at 5-4. But Zverev had a sitter that he hit into the net.\" -->{{Cite news|url=http://www.bnpparibasopen.com/en/media-and-news/news/2016/03/16/nadal-reacts-to-zverev-win|title=Nadal Reacts To Zverev Win {{!}} BNP Paribas Open|work=BNP Paribas Open|access-date=2017-07-15|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.atpworldtour.com/en/news/federer-stuttgart-2016-sf-reaction|title=Federer Stuttgart 2016 SF Reaction {{!}} ATP World Tour {{!}} Tennis|work=ATP World Tour|access-date=2017-07-15|language=en}}<!-- \"After Thiem saved a match point serving at 5/6, Federer had the match on his racquet at 7/6.\" --></ref><ref><!-- \"The next eight points went on serve; Ferrer had the set on his racquet when he took the balls with two serves to come at 5-4.\" -->{{Cite news|url=http://www.tennis.com/pro-game/2012/07/inadequately-heartbreaking/38079/|title=Inadequately Heartbreaking|work=Tennis.com|access-date=2017-07-15}}</ref><ref><!-- \"Once he had broken for 4-2, he had the set on his racquet at 5-3.\" -->{{Cite news|url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-sports/fantastic-federer-shows-his-class-on-grass/article3611733.ece|title=Fantastic Federer shows his class on grass|work=The Hindu|access-date=2017-07-15|language=en}}</ref>\n* {{Anchor|On serve|on serve}} '''On serve''': Situation where both players or teams have the same number of breaks in a set. While on serve, neither player or team can win the set without a break of serve. An advantage set requires at least one break to win.\n* {{Anchor|Open Era|open era}} '''Open Era''': Period in tennis which began in 1968 when tournaments became open to both amateurs and professional players.{{sfnp|Shine|2003|p=85|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Open stance|open stance}} '''Open stance''': Modern technique in which the hitter's body facing is at an angle between parallel to the baseline and facing the opponent. See also ''[[#closed stance|closed stance]]''.\n* {{Anchor|OP|op}} '''OP''': Stands for opportunity point; 15\u201330, an opportunity to potentially break serve.\n* {{Anchor|Out|out}} '''Out''': An error in which the ball lands outside the playing area.{{sfnp|Shine|2003|p=86|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Overgrip|overgrip|Overwrap|overwrap}} '''Overgrip''' (or '''overwrap'''): padded tape spirally wrapped over the handle or grip of the racket to absorb moisture or add gripping assistance.{{sfnp|Shine|2003|p=86|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Overhead|overhead}} '''Overhead''': Stroke in which the player hits the ball over his/her head; if the shot is hit relatively strongly, it is referred to as a [[Smash (tennis)|smash]]; smashes are often referred to as simply ''overheads'', although not every overhead shot is a smash.{{sfnp|Shine|2003|p=87|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Overrule|overrule}} '''Overrule''': To reverse a call made by a ''[[#line judge|line judge]]'', done by the ''[[#umpire|umpire]]''.{{sfnp|Shine|2003|p=87|ps=}}\n\n==P==\n* {{Anchor|Paint the lines|paint the lines}} '''Paint the lines''': To hit shots that land as close to the lines of the court as possible.\n* {{Anchor|Passing shot|passing shot}} '''Pass''' (or '''passing shot'''): Type of shot, usually played in the vicinity of the baseline, that passes by (not over) the opponent at the net. See also ''[[#lob|lob]]''.{{sfnp|Shannon|1981|p=545|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Percentage tennis|percentage tennis}} '''Percentage tennis''': Style of play consisting of safe shots with large margins of error. Aimed at keeping the ball in play in anticipation of an opponent's error.<ref name=\"oup\"/>\n* {{Anchor|Poaching|poaching}} '''Poaching''' (noun: '''poach'''): In doubles, an aggressive move where the player at the net moves to volley a shot intended for his/her partner.{{sfnp|Hedges|1978|p=257|ps=}}{{sfnp|Shannon|1981|p=545|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Point|point}} '''[[Point (tennis)|Point]]''': Period of play between the first successful service of a ball and the point at which that ball goes out of play. It is the smallest unit of ''[[#scoring|scoring]]'' in tennis.{{sfnp|Shine|2003|p=90|ps=}}\n*{{Anchor|Pre-qualifying|pre-qualifying}} '''Pre-qualifying''': Tournament in which the winner earns a wild card into a tournament's qualifying draw.\n* {{Anchor|Pressureless Ball|Pressureless ball|pressureless ball}} '''Pressureless ball''': Special type of tennis ball that does not have a core of pressurized air as standard balls do, but rather has a core made of solid rubber, or a core filled tightly with micro-particles.  Quality pressureless balls are approved for top-pro play generally, but pressureless balls are typically used mostly at high altitudes, where standard balls would be greatly affected by the difference between the high pressure in the ball and the thin air.\n* {{Anchor|Protected Ranking|Protected ranking|protected ranking}} '''Protected ranking''' (\"'''PR'''\"): Players injured for a minimum of six months can ask for a protected ranking, which is based on his or her average ranking during the first three months of his or her injury. The player can use his or her protected ranking to enter tournaments' main draws or qualifying competitions when coming back from injury.<ref name=atprankingsfaq>{{cite web|title=Rankings FAQ|url=http://www.atpworldtour.com/Rankings/Rankings-FAQ.aspx|website=www.atpworldtour.com|publisher=[[Association of Tennis Professionals]] (ATP)}}</ref> It is also used in the [[Women's Tennis Association|WTA]] for players returning from [[pregnancy]] leave.<ref>https://uk.reuters.com/article/uk-tennis-women-wta/wta-increases-rankings-protection-for-returning-mothers-idUKKBN1OG28M</ref>\n* {{Anchor|Pulp|pulp}} '''Pulp''': 30\u201330, not quite ''deuce'' (punning on the [[homophone]] \"juice\").\n* {{Anchor|Pusher|pusher}} '''[[Pusher (tennis)|Pusher]]''': Player who does not try to hit winners, but only to return the ball safely; often used in a derogative manner.\n* {{Anchor|Putaway|putaway}} '''Putaway''': Offensive shot to try to end the point with no hope of a return.{{sfnp|Shannon|1981|p=546|ps=}}\n*'''Ping it''': To hit an offensive shot and place the ball deep to the corners of the court.\n\n==Q==\n* {{Anchor|Qualies|qualies}} '''Qualies''': Short for ''qualification rounds'' or similar.{{sfnp|Grasso|2011|p=229|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Qualification round|qualification round}} '''Qualification round''': Final round of play in a pre-tournament qualification competition, also known as ''qualies''.{{sfnp|Grasso|2011|p=229|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Qualifier|qualifier}} '''Qualifier''' (\"'''Q'''\"): Player who reaches the tournament's main draw by competing in a pre-tournament qualifying competition, rather than automatically by virtue of his/her world ranking, by being awarded a wild card, or other exemption.{{sfnp|Grasso|2011|p=229|ps=}}\n* '''Qualifying draw''': See ''[[#draw|draw]]''.\n\n==R==\n[[File:Babolat pure drive plus.jpg|thumb|180px|A modern ''[[#racket|tennis racket]]'']]\n\n* {{Anchor|Racquet abuse|racquet abuse|Racket abuse|racket abuse}} '''Racket abuse''' ('''racquet abuse'''): When a player slams their racket into the ground or net in frustration. Can result in a warning from the umpire or docking of points.\n* {{Anchor|Racquet|racquet|Racket|racket}} '''[[tennis racket|Racket]]''' (or '''racquet'''): Bat with a long handle and a large looped frame with a string mesh tautly stretched across it, the frame made of wood, metal, graphite, composite, or some other synthetic material, used by a tennis player to hit the tennis ball during a game of tennis.{{sfnp|Hedges|1978|pp=257\u2013258|ps=}}{{sfnp|Grasso|2011|p=231|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Rally|rally}} '''[[Rally (tennis)|Rally]]''': Following the service of a tennis ball, a series of return hits of the ball that ends when one or other player fails to return the ball within the court boundary or fails to return a ball that falls within the play area.{{sfnp|Hedges|1978|p=258|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Rankings|rankings}} '''Rankings''': A hierarchical listing of players based on their recent achievements. Used to determine qualification for entry and seeding in tournaments.{{sfnp|Hedges|1978|p=257|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Rating|rating}} '''Rating''': A system used by national tennis organizations to group players of comparable skills. The rating of players is dependent on their match record.{{sfnp|Shine|2003|p=100|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Real tennis|real tennis}} '''[[Real tennis]]''' (also '''royal tennis''' or '''court tennis'''):  An indoor racket sport which was the predecessor of the modern game of (lawn) tennis. The term ''real'' is used as a [[retronym]] to distinguish the ancient game from the modern game of lawn tennis. Known also as ''court tennis'' in the United States or ''royal tennis'' in Australia.{{sfnp|Shine|2003|pp=101\u2013102|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Receiver|receiver}} '''Receiver''': Player who is receiving the ''[[#serve|service]]'' of the opponent.{{sfnp|Hedges|1978|p=258|ps=}}<ref>{{cite web|title=The rankings riddle|url=http://www.tennis.com.au/news/2014/06/20/the-rankings-riddle|website=www.tennis.com.au|publisher=Tennis Australia|date=20 June 2014}}</ref>\n* {{Anchor|Referee|referee}} '''[[Official (Tennis)#Referee|Referee]]''': Person in charge of enforcing the rules in a tournament, as opposed to a tennis match. See also ''[[#umpire|umpire]]''.{{sfnp|Robertson|1974|p=304|ps=}}{{sfnp|Shannon|1981|p=546|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Reflex Volley|Reflex volley|reflex volley}} '''Reflex volley''': Volley in which the player has no time to plan the shot, and instead reacts instinctively to get the racket in position to return the ball. This occurs frequently in doubles and in advanced singles.\n* {{Anchor|Registered player|registered player}} '''Registered player''': A designation used during the beginning of the Open Era to identify a category of amateur tennis players who were allowed to compete for prize money but stayed under the control of their national associations. \n* {{Anchor|Retirement|retirement}} '''Retirement''' (\"'''ret.'''\"): Player's withdrawal during a match, causing the player to forfeit the tournament. Usually this happens due to injury. For a pre-match withdrawal, see ''[[#walkover|walkover]]''.\n* {{Anchor|Retriever|retriever}} '''Retriever''': Defensive baseliner who relies on returning the ball rather than scoring direct winners. See [[tennis strategy]].{{sfnp|Shannon|1981|p=546|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Return Ace|Return ace|return ace}} '''Return ace''': Shot in which the opponent serves, the receiver returns the serve, and the opponent does not hit the ball.\n* {{Anchor|Return|return}} '''Return''': Stroke made by the receiver of a service.{{sfnp|Robertson|1974|p=305|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Rising Shot|Rising shot|rising shot}} '''Rising shot''': Shot in which the ball is hit before it reaches its apex; also ''hitting on the rise''.\n* {{Anchor|Round of 16|Round of sixteen}} '''Round of 16''': Round of a tournament prior to the quarterfinals in which there are 16 players remaining, corresponds to the fourth round of 128-draw tournament, the third round of a 64-draw, and second round of a 32-draw tournament.\n* {{Anchor|Round Robin|Round robin|round robin}} '''Round robin''' (\"'''RR'''\"): Tournament format in which players are organised into groups of three or four players and compete against all other members of the group. Players are then ranked according to number of matches, sets, and games won and head-to-head records. The top one, two, or four players then qualify for the next stage of the tournament.{{sfnp|Hedges|1978|p=258|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Rubber|rubber}} '''Rubber''': Individual match, singles or doubles, within a Davis Cup or Fed Cup ''[[#tie|tie]]''.<ref name=nytrubber>{{cite news|author1=Stuart Miller|title=Quirks of the Game: Davis Cup\u2019s Strange Lingo|url=http://straightsets.blogs.nytimes.com/2012/11/15/quirks-of-the-game-davis-cups-strange-lingo/|work=The New York Times|date=15 November 2012|access-date=7 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150922041224/http://straightsets.blogs.nytimes.com/2012/11/15/quirks-of-the-game-davis-cups-strange-lingo/|archive-date=22 September 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref>{{sfnp|Hedges|1978|p=259|ps=}}\n\n==S==\n[[File:Azarenka Roland Garros 2009 2.jpg|thumb|180px|Preparing to ''[[#serve|serve]]'' to start a ''[[#point|point]]'']]\n\n[[File:Joao Souza (14706260226).jpg|thumb|180px|Player preparing to hit a backhand ''[[#slice|slice shot]]'']]\n\n<!-- 'serving wide':  See Talk page, the section entitled 'serving wide'.  --> \n* {{Anchor|SABR|SABR}} '''SABR''' (Sneak Attack By Roger): a ploy where a returner rushes forward during a serve to catch an opponent off guard with a quick return. Popularized by [[Roger Federer]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Federer defends 'SABR' attack as US Open final tension builds|url=https://sports.yahoo.com/news/ageless-federer-braced-straight-shootout-djokovic-031717637--ten.html|accessdate=13 September 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/tennis/rogerfederer/11859167/US-Open-2015-Roger-Federers-aggressive-new-SABR-shot-is-not-disrespectful-but-it-is-brilliant.html | title=The Telegraph: Roger Federer's aggressive new SABR shot | accessdate=8 December 2015| date=2015-09-11 | last1=Cary | first1=Tom }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://ftw.usatoday.com/2015/09/what-is-roger-federers-new-sabr-move | title=USA Today: What is Roger Federer's new SABR move? | accessdate=8 December 2015| date=2015-09-10 }}</ref>\n* {{Anchor|Satellite|scratch}} '''Satellite''': Intermediate junior level of play, equivalent of Level 6\n* {{Anchor|scoring|scoring}} '''Scoring''': Method of tracking progress of a match. A match consists of ''points'', ''game'' and ''sets''.{{sfnp|Grasso|2011|p=255\u2013256|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Scratch|scratch}} '''Scratch''': Withdrawal from a match due to an injury.\n* {{Anchor|Second Service|Second service|second service|Second Serve|Second serve|second serve}} '''Second serve''': Second and final of the two serve attempts a player is allowed at the beginning of a point, not counting net cord let serves that would otherwise be good.\n* {{Anchor|Second Snap|Second snap|second snap}} '''Second snap''': a tennis ball struck for top spin against lubricated or co-poly strings will get extra rotation on the ball from the mains popping back in position before the ball leaves contact with the racket.\n* {{Anchor|Seed|seed}} '''Seed''' (or '''seeding'''): Player whose position in a tournament has been arranged based on his/her ranking so as not to meet other ranking players in the early rounds of play. Named for the similarity to scattering seeds widely over the ground to plant them. For a given tournament there is a specified number of seeds, depending on the size of the draw. For ATP tournaments, typically one out of four players are seeds. For example, a 32-draw International Series tournament would have eight seeds. The seeds are chosen and ranked by the tournament organizers and are selected because they are the players with the highest ranking who also, in the estimation of the organizers, have the best chance of winning the tournament. Seed ranking is sometimes controversial, because it does not always match the players' current ATP ranking.{{sfnp|Hedges|1978|p=259|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Serve and volley|serve and volley}} '''[[Serve and volley]]''':  Method of play to serve and immediately move forward to the net to make a volley with the intent to hit a winner and end the point.{{sfnp|Grasso|2011|p=261|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Serve|serve}} '''[[Serve (tennis)|Serve]]''' (verb and noun. Also '''service''', noun): The starting stroke of each point. The ball must be hit into the opponent's ''service box'', specifically the box's half that is diagonally opposite the server.{{sfnp|Grasso|2011|pp=260\u2013261|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Service box|service box}} '''Service box''': Rectangular area of the court, marked by the sidelines and the service lines, that a serve is supposed to land in.{{sfnp|Shine|2003|p=113|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Service game|service game}} '''Service game''': With regard to a player, the game in which the player is serving (e.g. \"Player A won a love service game\" means that Player A has won a game where (s)he was serving without the opponent scoring).\n* {{Anchor|Service line|service line}} '''Service line''': A line that runs parallel to the net at a distance of 21&nbsp;ft (6.4m) and forms part of the demarcation of the ''service box''.{{sfnp|Hedges|1978|p=260|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Set point|set point}} '''Set point''': Situation in which the player who is leading needs one more point to win a set. If the player is serving in such a situation, (s)he is said to be \"serving for the set\".{{sfnp|Grasso|2011|p=261|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Set|set}} '''Set''': A unit of scoring. A set consists of games and the first player to win six games with a two-game advantage wins the set. In most tournaments a ''[[#tiebreak|tiebreak]]'' is used at six games all to decide the outcome of a set.{{sfnp|Grasso|2011|p=261|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Shamateurism|shamateurism}} '''Shamateurism''': Amalgamation of 'sham' and 'amateurism', derogatory term for a custom that widely existed before the open era where an amateur player would receive financial remuneration to participate in a tournament in violation of amateur laws.{{sfnp|Robertson|1974|p=316|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Shank|shank}} '''Shank''': Significantly misdirected shot, the result of hitting the ball in an unintentional manner, typically with the frame of the racket. Such shots typically land outside the court, however, it is possible to hit a shank that lands validly in the court.\n* {{Anchor|Shot clock|shot clock}} '''Shot clock''': A publicly displayed clock which is used in between points to ensure that a player serves within 25 seconds. First used in grand slams at the Australian Open in 2018.\n* {{Anchor|Singles Sticks|Singles sticks|singles sticks}} '''Singles sticks''' (or '''[[#net sticks|net sticks]]'''): Pair of poles which are placed underneath the net near the singles sideline for the purpose of raising it for singles play.\n* {{Anchor|Singles|singles}} '''[[Singles (tennis)|Singles]]''': Match played by two players, one on each side of the court. A singles court is narrower than a doubles court and is bounded by the inner sidelines and the baseline.{{sfnp|Hedges|1978|p=260|ps=}}{{sfnp|Grasso|2011|p=263|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Sitter|sitter}} '''Sitter''': Shot which is hit with very little pace and no spin, which bounces high after landing, thus being an easy shot to ''put away''.{{sfnp|Shine|2003|p=119|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Sledgehammer|Sledgehammer}} '''Sledgehammer''': Two-handed backhand winner down the line.\n* {{Anchor|Slice|slice}} '''Slice''': Shot with underspin (backspin), or a serve with sidespin. Groundstrokes hit with slice tend to have a flat trajectory and a low bounce.{{sfnp|Hedges|1978|p=260|ps=}}{{sfnp|Grasso|2011|p=263|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Smash|smash}} '''[[Smash (tennis)|Smash]]''': Strongly hit ''[[#overhead|overhead]]'', typically executed when the player who hits the shot is very close to the net and can therefore hit the ball nearly vertically, often so that it bounces into the stands, making it unreturnable.{{sfnp|Hedges|1978|p=260|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Spank|spank}} '''Spank''': To hit a groundstroke flat with a lot of pace.\n* {{Anchor|Sparring Partner|Sparring partner|sparring partner}} '''Sparring partner''': see ''[[#hitting partner|hitting partner]]''\n* {{Anchor|Special Exempt|Special exempt|special exempt}} '''Special exempt''' (\"'''SE'''\"): Players who are unable to appear in a tournament's qualifying draw because they are still competing in the final rounds of a previous tournament can be awarded a spot in the main draw by special exempt.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.atpworldtour.com/-/media/files/rulebook/2017/2017-atp-rulebook_chapter-vii.pdf|title=ATP Rule Book|publisher=atpworldtour.com|accessdate=3 May 2018}}</ref>\n* '''Special ranking''' (\"'''SR'''\"): See ''[[#protected ranking|protected ranking]]''.\n* {{Anchor|Spin|spin}} '''Spin''': Rotation of the ball as it moves through the air, affecting its trajectory and bounce. See ''[[#backspin|backspin]]'', ''[[#topspin|topspin]]'', and ''[[#underspin|underspin]]''.{{sfnp|Hedges|1978|p=260|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Split step|split step}} '''Split step''': a footwork technique in which a player does a small bounce on both feet, just as the opponent hits the ball. This lets the player go more quickly in either direction.{{sfnp|Shine|2003|pp=122\u2013123|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Spot Serving|Spot serving|spot serving|Spot Server|Spot server|spot server}} '''Spot serving'''/'''spot server''': Serving with precision, resulting in the ball landing either on or near the intersection of the center service line and service line or singles tramline and service line.\n* {{Anchor|Squash Shot|Squash shot|squash shot|}} '''Squash shot''': Forehand or backhand shot typically hit on the run from a defensive position, either with slice, or from behind the player's stance.\n* {{Anchor|Stance|Stance}} '''Stance''': The way a player stands when hitting the ball\n* {{Anchor|Stick the Volley|Stick the volley|stick the volley}} '''Stick volley''': Volley hit crisply, resulting in shot with a sharp downward trajectory.\n* {{Anchor|Stiffness|stiffness}} '''Stiffness''' (or '''racket stiffness'''): The resistance of the racket to bending upon impact with the ball.{{sfnp|Shine|2003|pp=123\u2013124|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Stop volley|stop volley}} '''Stop volley''': A softly-hit volley which absorbs almost all the power of the shot resulting in the ball dropping just over the net.{{sfnp|Shannon|1981|p=547|ps=}}{{sfnp|Shine|2003|p=124|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Stopper|stopper}} '''Stopper''': Player who will not win or go deep in a tournament but is good enough to stop a top seed from advancing.\n* {{Anchor|Straight sets|straight sets}} '''Straight sets''': Situation in which the winner of a match does not lose a set. A straight set may also mean a set which is won by a score of 6-something; i.e. is won at the first opportunity and does not reach five games all.{{sfnp|Shannon|1981|p=547|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|String Saver|String saver|string saver}} '''String saver''': Tiny piece of plastic that is sometimes inserted where the strings cross, to prevent the strings from abrading each other and prematurely breaking.{{sfnp|Shine|2003|p=125|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Strings|strings}} '''[[Strings (tennis)|Strings]]''': Material woven through the face of the racket. The strings are where contact with the ball is supposed to be made.{{sfnp|Shine|2003|pp=124\u2013125|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Stroke|stroke}} '''Stroke''': Striking of the ball.{{sfnp|Hedges|1978|p=260|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Sudden Death tiebreak|Sudden death tiebreak|sudden death tiebreak|Sudden Death|sudden death}} '''Sudden death tiebreak''': Version of the tiebreak played as the best of nine points, with the last being a deciding point to clinch the set. Introduced in 1965 by Jimmy Van Alen as a component of the ''[[#VASSS|VASSS]]''.<ref name=tiebreak/>{{sfnp|Shine|2003|pp=134\u2013135|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Super-Tiebreak|super tiebreak}} '''Super tiebreak''': A ''tiebreak'' variation played to ten points instead of seven; usually used in double to decide a match instead of playing a third set.{{sfnp|Shine|2003|p=127|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Supercoach}} '''Supercoach''': A tennis coach who has had a successful professional career.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.atpworldtour.com/en/news/raonic-krajicek-june-2017|title=Raonic, Krajicek Mutually Part Ways {{!}} ATP World Tour {{!}} Tennis|work=ATP World Tour|access-date=2017-12-10|language=en}}</ref>\n* {{Anchor|Sweetspot|sweetspot}} '''Sweetspot''': Central area of the racket head which is the best location, in terms of control and power, for making contact with the ball.{{sfnp|Shine|2003|p=128|ps=}}\n* '''Swing volley''': See ''[[#drive volley|drive volley]]''.\n\n==T==\n[[File:Tennis ball 01.jpg|thumb|180px|A standard optic yellow ''[[#tennis ball|tennis ball]]'']]\n\n* {{Anchor|Tanking|tanking}} '''Tanking''' (noun: '''tank'''): Colloquial term for losing a match on purpose; or to purposely lose a non-vital set, so as to focus energy and attention on a match-deciding set which could result in a temporary ban such as that encountered by [[Nick Kyrgios]].{{sfnp|Shine|2003|pp=130\u2013131|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Taping it|taping it}} '''Tape it''': To play a shot that hits the tape at the top of the net.\n* {{Anchor|Tennis Ball|Tennis ball|tennis ball|Ball|ball}} '''[[Tennis ball]]''': Soft, hollow, air-filled rubber ball coated in a synthetic fur, used in the game of tennis. The ITF specifies that a tennis ball must have a diameter of 6.54\u20136.86&nbsp;cm (2.57\u20132.70&nbsp;in) and a weight of 56.0\u201359.4g. Yellow and white are the only approved colors at tournament level.{{sfnp|Hedges|1978|p=251|ps=}}{{sfnp|Robertson|1974|p=202|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Tennis Bubble|Tennis bubble|tennis bubble}} '''Tennis bubble''': Indoor tennis facility consisting of a domed structure which is supported by air pressure generated by blowers inside the structure.\n* {{Anchor|Tennis Dad|Tennis dad|tennis dad}} '''Tennis dad''': Father of a tennis player, often used in reference to a parent actively participating in the player's tennis development and/or career.\n* {{Anchor|Tennis Elbow|Tennis elbow|tennis elbow}} '''[[Tennis elbow]]''': Common injury in beginner to intermediate tennis players, possibly due to improper technique or a racket which transmits excessive vibration to the arm.{{sfnp|Robertson|1974|p=329|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Tennis Hall of Fame|tennis Hall of Fame|Hall of Fame|HoF|HOF|hof}} '''Tennis Hall of Fame''': The [[International Tennis Hall of Fame]] located in [[Newport, Rhode Island]], United States. It was established in 1954 and hosts an annual tournament around the induction ceremony.{{sfnp|Grasso|2011|p=144\u2013145|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|The Vineyard of Tennis|The vineyard of tennis|the vineyard of tennis}} '''The vineyard of tennis''': Southern California as characterized by [[Bud Collins]].\n* {{Anchor|Tiebreak|Tie-break|Tie break|Tie-breaker|Tiebreaker}} '''[[Tennis score#Scoring a tiebreak game|Tiebreak]]''': Special game played when the score is 6\u20136 in a set to decide the winner of the set; the winner is the first to reach at least seven points with a difference of two points over the opponent.{{sfnp|Hedges|1978|p=260|ps=}}<ref name=tiebreak>{{cite web|author1=Steve Tignor|title=1970: The Tiebreaker Is Introduced|url=http://www.tennis.com/pro-game/2015/02/1970-tiebreaker-introduced/54116/#.VOoChXzF8rs|publisher=Tennis.com|date=18 February 2015}}</ref>\n* {{Anchor|Tie|tie}} '''Tie''': Synonymous with ''[[#match|match]]'', but used for team competitions such as the [[Davis Cup]] and [[Fed Cup]].\n* {{Anchor|Topspin|topspin}} '''[[Topspin]]''': Spin of a ball where the top of the ball rotates toward the direction of travel; the spin goes forward over the top of the ball, causing the ball to dip and bounce at a higher angle to the court.{{sfnp|Shine|2003|pp=135\u2013136|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Toss|Toss}} '''Toss''': At the beginning of a match, the winner of a coin toss chooses who serves first. In amateur tennis the toss is often performed by spinning the racket.{{sfnp|Hedges|1978|pp=260\u2013261|ps=}}{{sfnp|Robertson|1974|p=330|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Touch|touch}} '''Touch''': Occurs when a player touches any part of the net when the ball is still in play, losing the point.\n* {{Anchor|Tramline|tramline}} '''Tramline''': Line defining the limit of play on the side of a singles or doubles court.{{sfnp|Hedges|1978|p=261|ps=}}{{sfnp|Shine|2003|pp=138\u2013139|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Trampolining|trampolining}} '''Trampolining''': Effect which occurs when striking a ball flat with a racket that is strung at a very loose tension.  Trampolining results in a shot that has a very high velocity.\n* {{Anchor|Tree|tree}} '''Two ball pass''': Passing an opponent that has come to the net with a first shot that causes them trouble on the volley followed up by hitting the second ball by them.\n* {{Anchor|Triple Bagel|Triple bagel|triple bagel}} '''Triple bagel''': Colloquial term for three sets won to ''[[#love|love]]''. See ''[[#bagel|bagel]]''.\n* {{Anchor|Triple Crown|Triple crown|triple crown}} '''Triple crown''': Winning the championship in all three tennis disciplines (singles, doubles and mixed doubles) at one event, especially a Grand Slam tournament.\n* {{Anchor|T|t}} '''T''' ('''the T'''):  The spot on a [[tennis court]] where the center line and the service line intersect perpendicularly to form a \"T\" shape.{{sfnp|Shine|2003|p=132|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Tube|tube}}'''Tube''': (Colloquial term) to deliberately and successfully hit the ball, at the opponent's the body; e.g. \"he tubed his opponent.\"\n* {{Anchor|Tweener racket|tweener racket}} '''[[Tweener racket]]''': a tennis racket of mid-weight, mid-head size and mid-stiffness, often used as a transitional racket for young professionals.\n* {{Anchor|Tweener|tweener|Hot Shot|Hot shot|hot shot}} '''[[Tweener (tennis)|Tweener]]''' (also called '''hot dog''', '''Gran Willy''' or '''Sabatweenie''' \u2014 the last two names after [[Guillermo Vilas]] and [[Gabriela Sabatini]] respectively, who pioneered the shot in the 1970s and 80s): A difficult trick shot in which a player hits the ball between his or her legs. It is usually performed when chasing down a [[lob (tennis)|lob]] with the player's back to the net. Forward-facing tweeners are also sometimes employed, and have been dubbed \"front tweeners\". See also [[#Gran Willy|Gran Willy]] and [[#Sabatweenie|Sabatweenie]].\n* {{Anchor|Twist Serve|Twist serve|twist serve}} '''Twist serve''' (or '''American twist serve'''): Serve hit with a combination of slice and topspin which results in a curving trajectory and high bounce in the opposite direction of the ball's flight trajectory. See also ''[[kick serve]]''.{{sfnp|Shine|2003|p=7|ps=}}\n\n==U==\n* {{Anchor|Umpire|umpire}} '''[[Official (Tennis)#Chair umpire|Umpire]]''' (or '''chair umpire'''): Person designated to enforce the rules of the game during play, usually sitting on a high chair beside the net.{{sfnp|Hedges|1978|p=261|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Underhand service|underhand service|Underhand serve|underhand serve|underhand|Underhand}} '''Underhand serve''' (or '''underarm serve'''): A serve in which the player lobs the ball from below shoulder level.{{sfnp|Shine|2003|p=142|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Underspin|underspin}} '''Underspin''' (or '''backspin''' or '''undercut'''): Spin of a ball where the top of the ball rotates away from the direction of travel; the spin is underneath the ball, causing the ball to float and to bounce at a lower angle to the court.{{sfnp|Shannon|1981|p=548|ps=}}{{sfnp|Shine|2003|pp=142\u2013143|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Unforced error|unforced error}} '''Unforced error''': Error in a service or return shot that cannot be attributed to any factor other than poor judgement and execution by the player; contrasted with a ''[[#Forced error|forced error]]''.{{sfnp|Shine|2003|p=143|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Unseeded player|unseeded player|Unseeded|unseeded}} '''Unseeded player''': Player who is not a ''[[Single-elimination tournament#Seeding|seed]]'' in a tournament.{{sfnp|Shine|2003|pp=143\u2013144|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Upset|upset}} '''Upset''': The defeat of a high-ranked player by a lower-ranked player.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.atpworldtour.com/en/news/cilic-nishikori-stakhovsky-wimbledon-2017-wednesday|title=Kei Nishikori Beats Sergiy Stakhovsky, Who Upset Roger Federer At 2013 Wimbledon {{!}} ATP World Tour {{!}} Tennis|work=ATP World Tour|access-date=2017-12-10|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==V==\n[[File:Tsvetana Pironkova 1, Wimbledon 2013 - Diliff.jpg|thumb|180px|Approaching a forehand [[#volley|volley]]]]\n\n* {{Anchor|Vantage|vantage}} '''Vantage''': Archaic term for ''[[#advantage|advantage]]''.{{sfnp|Shannon|1981|p=548|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|VASSS|vasss}} '''VASSS''': Abbreviation for '''Van Alen Streamlined Scoring System''', an alternative scoring method developed by [[Jimmy Van Alen|James Van Alen]] aimed at avoiding very long matches that can arise under the traditional advantage scoring system. The only element of the VASSS to be adopted by tennis authorities was the ''[[#tiebreak|tiebreak]]''.{{sfnp|Robertson|1974|p=340|ps=}}{{sfnp|Shine|2003|pp=145|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Volley|volley}} '''[[Volley (tennis)|Volley]]''': A shot hit, usually in the vicinity of the net, by a player before the ball bounces on their own side of the court.{{sfnp|Hedges|1978|p=261|ps=}}{{sfnp|Shine|2003|pp=146|ps=}}\n\n==W==\n* {{Anchor|Walkover|walkover|WO|w/o}} '''[[Walkover]]''' (\"'''WO'''\" or \"'''w/o'''\"): Unopposed victory. A [[walkover]] is awarded when the opponent fails to start the match for any reason, such as injury. For a mid-match withdrawal, see ''[[#retirement|retirement]]''.\n* {{Anchor|Western grip|western grip}} '''Western grip''': Type of grip used if a player wants to generate a lot of topspin on the groundstrokes, is created by placing the index knuckle on bevel 5 of the grip.{{sfnp|Shine|2003|pp=147\u2013148|ps=}}{{sfnp|Shannon|1981|p=548|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Whiff|whiff}} '''Whiff''': A stroke in which the player misses the ball completely. Whiffing a serve is considered a fault in an official match.<ref>{{cite web|title=Swings vs. \"Whiffs\"|url=https://www.usta.com/Improve-Your-Game/Rules/Rulings/Swings_vs_whiffs/|website=USTA|publisher=United States Tennis Association|accessdate=22 July 2016}}</ref>\n* {{Anchor|Wide|wide}} '''Wide''': A call to indicate that the ball has landed out of court, beyond the sideline.{{sfnp|Shannon|1981|p=548|ps=}}{{sfnp|Shine|2003|p=149|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Wild Card|Wild card|wild card|WC}} '''[[Wild card (sports)#Professional tennis|Wild card]]''' (\"'''WC'''\"): Player allowed to play in a tournament, even if his or her rank is not adequate or he or she does not register in time. Typically a few places in the draw are reserved for wild cards, which may be for local players who do not gain direct acceptance or for players who are just outside the ranking required to gain direct acceptance. Wild cards may also be given to players whose ranking has dropped due to a long-term injury.{{sfnp|Shine|2003|p=150|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Winner|winner}} '''Winner''': A shot that is not reached by the opponent and wins the point; sometimes also a serve that is reached but not returned into the court.{{sfnp|Grasso|2011|p=310|ps=}}{{sfnp|Shine|2003|p=153|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|World Championship Tennis|world championship tennis|WCT}} '''WCT''': Abbreviation for [[World Championship Tennis]], a tour for professional male tennis players established in 1968 which lasted until the emergence of the ATP Tour in 1990. \n* {{Anchor|WTA Finals|WTAF}} '''[[WTA Finals]]''': The annual season-ending tournament featuring eight of the top-ranked women in the world (plus two alternates).\n* {{Anchor|WTA|Women's Tennis Association|wta}} '''WTA''': Abbreviation for [[Women's Tennis Association]], the main organizing body of women's professional tennis; governs the WTA Tour with the largest tournaments for women.{{sfnp|Grasso|2011|pp=310\u2013311|ps=}}{{sfnp|Shine|2003|pp=157\u2013158|ps=}}\n\n==Z==\n* {{Anchor|Zero Pointer|Zero pointer|zero pointer}} '''Zero pointer''': Ranking points received by skipping selected professional tennis tour events which a top ranked player is committed to participate in (mandatory tournaments). Therefore, the player risks getting no points added to his or her ranking even when participating in an alternative tournament in place of the mandatory event.\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Tennis}}\n* [[Tennis shots]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n;Sources\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite book|last=Grasso|first=John|title=Historical Dictionary of Tennis|date=2011|publisher=Scarecrow Press|location=Lanham, Md.|isbn=978-0810872370|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Hedges|first=Martin|title=The Concise Dictionary of Tennis|date=1978|pages=[https://archive.org/details/concisedictionar00hedg/page/251 251\u2013261]|publisher=Mayflower Books|location=New York|isbn=978-0861240128|ref=harv|url=https://archive.org/details/concisedictionar00hedg/page/251}}\n* {{cite book|last=Robertson|first=Max|title=The Encyclopedia of Tennis|year=1974|publisher=Allen & Unwin|location=London|isbn=9780047960420|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|editor-last=Shannon|editor-first=Bill|title=Official Encyclopedia of Tennis|date=1981|publisher=Harper & Row|location=New York [u.a.]|isbn=9780060148966|pages=[https://archive.org/details/unitedstatestenn0000unse/page/272 272\u2013277]|edition=3rd, Revised and updated|ref=harv|url=https://archive.org/details/unitedstatestenn0000unse/page/272}}\n* {{cite book|last=Shine|first=Ossian|title=The Language of Tennis|date=2003|publisher=Carcanet|location=Manchester|isbn=978-1857546330|ref=harv}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wiktionarycat|type=Tennis|category=Tennis}}\n*[http://www.britishtennis.com/newtotennis/glossary/ Glossary of tennis terms at britishtennis.com]\n*[http://www.tennis.com.au/learn/rules-and-scoring/glossary Glossary of tennis terms at Tennis Australia]\n\n{{tennis box}}\n{{Glossaries of sports}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Glossary Of Tennis}}\n[[Category:Tennis terminology| ]]\n[[Category:Glossaries of sports|Tennis]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Wikipedia glossary}}\nThis page is a [[glossary]] of [[tennis]] terminology.\n{{compact ToC | refs=yes|extlinks=yes}}\n\n==A==\n* {{Anchor|Ace|ace}} '''[[Ace (tennis)|Ace]]''': Serve where the tennis ball lands inside the ''[[#service box|service box]]'' and is not touched by the receiver; thus, a shot that is both a serve and a winner is an ace. Aces are usually powerful and generally land on or near one of the corners at the back of the service box. Initially, the term was used to indicate the scoring of a point.{{sfnp|Grasso|2011|p=19|ps=}}{{sfnp|Shine|2003|p=3|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Action|action}} '''Action''': Synonym of ''[[#spin|spin]]''\n* {{Anchor|Ad court|ad court}} '''Ad court''': Left side of the court''' '''of each player, so called because the ''ad'' (''advantage'') point immediately following a deuce is always served to this side of the court.{{sfnp|Shine|2003|p=3|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Ad|ad}} '''Ad''': Used by the chair umpire to announce the score when a player has the ''[[#advantage|advantage]]'', meaning they won the point immediately after a ''[[#deuce|deuce]]''. See [[scoring in tennis]]\n* {{Anchor|Advantage set|advantage set|Advantage format|advantage format}} '''Advantage set''': Set won by a player or team having won at least six games with a two-game advantage over the opponent (as opposed to a [[#Tiebreakbreak|tiebreak format]]). Final sets in the singles draws of the [[French Open]] remains the only major tennis event to use all advantage sets. In the past, they were used at [[Tennis at the Summer Olympics|Olympic tennis events]] (until 2012), [[Davis Cup]] (until 2015), [[Fed Cup]] (until 2015), [[Australian Open]] (until 2018) and [[The Championships, Wimbledon|Wimbledon]] (until 2018) when they all switched to tie breaks.\n* {{Anchor|Advantage|advantage|}} '''Advantage''': When one player wins the first point from a ''[[#deuce|deuce]]'' and needs one more point to win the game; not applicable when using deciding points.{{sfnp|Grasso|2011|p=19|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|All-Comers|all-comers}} '''All-Comers''': Tournament in which all players took part except the reigning champion. The winner of the All-Comers event would play the title holder in the ''[[#Challenge Round|Challenge Round]]''.{{sfnp|Hedges|1978|p=251|ps=}}{{sfnp|Grasso|2011|p=22|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|All-court|all-court|all court}} '''All-court''' (or '''All-court game'''): Style of play that is a composite of all the different playing styles, which includes baseline, transition, and serve and volley styles.{{sfnp|Shannon|1981|p=539|ps=}}{{sfnp|Shine|2003|pp=5\u20136|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|All|all}} '''All''': Used by the chair umpire to announce scores when both players have the same number of points or the same number of games. When both players are at 40, the preferred term is ''[[#deuce|deuce]]''.{{sfnp|Grasso|2011|p=22|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Alley|Tramlines|alley|tramlines}} '''Alley''': Area of the court between the singles and the doubles sidelines, which together are known as ''[[#tramline|tramlines]]''.{{sfnp|Grasso|2011|p=23|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Alternate|alternate}} '''Alternate''': Player or team that gains acceptance into the main draw of a tournament when a main draw player or team withdraws. Such a player may be a ''[[#lucky loser|lucky loser]]''.\n* {{Anchor|Approach shot|approach shot}} '''Approach shot''': A ''[[#groundstroke|groundstroke]]'' shot used as a setup as the player approaches the net, often using underspin or topspin.{{sfnp|Shine|2003|p=8|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|ATP Champions Race|ATP champions race|atp Champions Race|atp champions race}} '''ATP Champions' Race''' (or '''ATP Rankings Race To London'''): ATP point ranking system that starts at the beginning of the year and by the end of the year mirrors the ATP entry system ranking. The top eight players at the end of the year qualify for the [[ATP Finals]].<ref name=atprankingsfaq/>\n* {{Anchor|ATP World Tour Finals|ATP WTF}} '''ATP Finals''': Formerly known as the ''Tennis Masters Cup'' (see [[#T|T]] below), it is the annual season-ending tournament featuring eight of the top-ranked men in the world (plus two alternates).<ref>{{cite web|title=Tournaments \u2013 ATP World Tour Finals|url=http://www.atpworldtour.com/Tennis/Tournaments/London-Finals.aspx|website=www.atpworldtour.com|publisher=[[Association of Tennis Professionals]] (ATP)}}</ref>\n* {{Anchor|ATP|atp|Association of Tennis Professionals|Association of tennis professionals|association of tennis professionals}} '''ATP''': Abbreviation for [[Association of Tennis Professionals]], the main organizing body of men's professional tennis; governs the ATP World Tour with the largest tournaments for men.\n* {{Anchor|Australian formation|australian formation}} '''Australian formation''': In doubles, a formation where the server and partner stand on the same side of the court before starting the point.<ref>{{cite web|author1=Kathleen Krajco|title=Australian Doubles Strategy|url=http://www.tennisserver.com/wildcards/wildcards_02_06.html|publisher=The Tennis Server}}</ref>{{sfnp|Shine|2003|p=9|ps=}}\n\n==B==\n\n[[File:Ball kid - 2010 Australian Open.jpg|thumb|180px|A ''[[#ball boy|Ball boy]]'' in action]]\n* {{Anchor|Backcourt|backcourt}} '''Backcourt''': The area of the tennis court between the ''[[#baseline|baseline]]'' and the ''[[#service line|service line]]''.{{sfnp|Shine|2003|p=10|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Backhand|backhand}} '''[[Backhand]]''': Stroke in which the ball is hit with the back of the racket hand facing the ball at the moment of contact. A backhand is often hit by a right-handed player when the ball is on the left side of the court, and vice versa.{{sfnp|Hedges|1978|p=251|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Backhand smash|backhand smash}} '''Backhand smash''': A type of ''[[#smash|smash]]'' played over the backhand side.{{sfnp|Shine|2003|p=10|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Backspin|backspin}} '''[[Backspin]]''': Shot that rotates the ball backwards after it is hit; also known as ''[[#slice|slice]]'' or ''underspin''. The trajectory of the shot is affected by an upward force that lifts the ball. See [[Magnus effect]].{{sfnp|Shine|2003|p=10|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Backswing|backswing}} '''Backswing''': Portion of a swing where the racket is swung backwards in preparation for the forward motion to hit the ball.{{sfnp|Hedges|1978|p=251|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Bagel|bagel}} '''[[Bagel (tennis)|Bagel]]''': Colloquial term for winning or losing a set 6\u20130 (the shape of the zero being reminiscent of the round shape of a [[bagel]]). See also ''[[#breadstick|breadstick]]''.<ref>{{cite web|title=BuzzWord \u2013 Bagel|url=http://www.macmillandictionary.com/buzzword/entries/bagel.html|website=www.macmillandictionary.com|publisher=Macmillan}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author1=Peter Bodo|title=Bagel, Anyone?|url=http://www.tennis.com/pro-game/2011/07/bagel-anyone/41515/#.VOs5h3zF8rs|publisher=Tennis.com|date=26 July 2011}}</ref>{{sfnp|Shine|2003|p=11|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Bagnall\u2013Wild|bagnall\u2013wildl}} '''Bagnall\u2013Wild''': A method of draw which places all byes in the first round. Introduced in the 1880s.<ref>{{cite book|title=Wright & Ditson's Lawn Tennis Guide for 1893|location=Boston|publisher=Wright & Ditson|pages=[https://archive.org/details/wrightditsonoff20unkngoog/page/n145 124], 125|url=https://archive.org/details/wrightditsonoff20unkngoog|editor=Joseph T. Whittelsey|oclc=32300203|year=1893}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Gillmeister|first=Heiner|title=Tennis : A Cultural History|url=https://archive.org/details/tennisculturalhi0000gill|url-access=registration|year=1998|publisher=Leicester University Press|location=London|isbn=978-0718501952|page=[https://archive.org/details/tennisculturalhi0000gill/page/355 355]|edition=Repr.}}</ref>\n* {{Anchor|Ball Boy|Ball boy|ball boy}} '''[[Ball boy]]''' (also '''ball girl''' or '''ballkid'''): a person, commonly a child tasked with retrieving tennis balls from the court that have gone out of play and supplying the balls to the players before their service. Ball boys in ''net'' positions normally kneel near the net and run across the court to collect the ball, while ball boys in the ''back'' positions stand in the back along the perimeter of the arena. Ball boys in the back are responsible for giving the balls to the player serving.{{sfnp|Shine|2003|p=13|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Ball toss|ball toss}} '''Ball toss''': The action of throwing up the ball prior to the ''[[#serve|serve]]''.{{sfnp|Shine|2003|p=13|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Baseline|baseline}} '''[[Wiktionary:Baseline|Baseline]]''': Line at the farthest ends of the court indicating the boundary of the area of play. If the ball goes over the baseline it will be the other player's point.{{sfnp|Hedges|1978|p=252|ps=}}{{sfnp|Shine|2003|p=14|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Baseliner|baseliner}} '''baseliner''': Player who plays around the baseline during play and relies on the quality of his or her ground strokes.{{sfnp|Shine|2003|p=14|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Big serve|big serve}} '''Big serve''': Forceful serve, usually giving an advantage in the point for the server.\n* {{Anchor|Bisque|bisque}} '''Bisque''': One stroke (point), which may be claimed by the receiver at any part of the set. Part of the handicapping odds and used during the early era of the sport. Abolished by the LTA in 1890.<ref>{{cite news|title=Lawn Tennis Association|url=http://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0000206/18900130/001/0003|work=Manchester Courier and Lancashire General Advertiser|publisher=[[British Newspaper Archive]]|date=30 January 1890|url-access=subscription }}</ref>\n* {{Anchor|Block|block}} '''Block''' (or '''blocked return'''): Defensive shot with relatively little backswing and shortened action instead of a full swing, usually while returning a serve.{{sfnp|Shine|2003|p=17|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Bounce|bounce}} '''Bounce''': The upward movement of the ball after it has hit the ground. The trajectory of the bounce can be affected by the surface and weather, the amount and type of spin and the power of the shot.{{sfnp|Hedges|1978|p=252|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Breadstick|breadstick}} '''Breadstick''': Colloquial term for winning or losing a set 6\u20131, with the straight shape of the one supposedly being reminiscent of the straight shape of a breadstick. See also ''[[#bagel|bagel]]''.<ref>{{cite web|author1=Carl Bialik|title=Radwanska's Bakery of Odd Results|url=https://blogs.wsj.com/dailyfix/2013/07/03/radwanskas-bakery-of-odd-results/|publisher=The Wall Street Journal|date=3 July 2013}}</ref>\n* {{Anchor|Break back|break back}} '''Break back''': To win a game as the receiving player or team immediately after losing the previous game as the serving player or team.\n* {{Anchor|Break point|break point}} '''Break point''': Point which, if won by the receiver, would result in a break of service; arises when the score is 30\u201340 or 40\u2013ad. A double break point or two break points arises at 15\u201340; a triple break point or three break points arises at 0\u201340.{{sfnp|Shine|2003|p=18|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Break|break}} '''[[Wiktionary:break|Break]]''': To win a game as the receiving player or team, thereby breaking serve. At high level of play the server is more likely to win a game, so breaks are often key moments of a match. Noun: ''break (service break)'' (e.g. \"to be a break down\" means \"to have, in a set, one break fewer than the opponent\", \"to be a double break up\" means \"to have, in a set, two breaks more than the opponent\").{{sfnp|Shine|2003|pp=17\u201318|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Breaker|breaker}} '''Breaker''': Colloquial term for ''[[#tiebreak|tiebreak]]''.{{sfnp|Shine|2003|p=18|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Buggy whip|buggy whip}} '''Buggy whip''': Forehand hit with a follow-through that does not go across the body and finish on the opposite side, but rather goes from low to high, crosses the opposite shoulder (optionally) and finishes on the same side (similar to the driver of a horse-drawn carriage whipping a horse). Used, for example, by [[Rafael Nadal]] (racket head crosses the opposite shoulder) and [[Maria Sharapova]] (racket head stays on the same shoulder).<ref>{{cite book|last1=Hoskins|first1=Tina|title=The Tennis Drill Book|date=2003|publisher=Human Kinetics|location=Champaign, Ill. ;Leeds|isbn=978-0736049122|page=[https://archive.org/details/tennisdrillbook0000hosk/page/23 23]|url=https://archive.org/details/tennisdrillbook0000hosk|url-access=registration}}</ref>\n* {{Anchor|Bumper guard|bumper guard}} '''Bumper guard''': A piece of plastic that protects the outside of the upper-half of the racket head.{{sfnp|Shine|2003|p=18|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Bye|bye}} '''[[Bye (sports)|Bye]]''': Automatic advancement of a player to the next round of a tournament without facing an opponent. Byes are often awarded in the first round to the top-seeded players in a tournament.{{sfnp|Hedges|1978|p=252|ps=}}\n*'''Bunt''': To use the power of the opponents shot and hit it back with a short swing.\n\n==C==\n[[File:Tennis court imperial.svg|thumb|180px|A tennis ''[[#court|court]]'' with its dimensions and components]]\n\n* {{Anchor|Call|call}} '''Call''': Verbal utterance by a line judge or chair umpire declaring that a ball landed outside the valid area of play.{{sfnp|Shine|2003|p=19|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Can Opener|Can opener|can opener}} '''Can opener''': Serve hit by a right-handed player with slice, landing on or near the intersection of the singles tramline and service line in the deuce court (or in the ad court for a left-handed server).\n* {{Anchor|Cannonball|cannonball}} '''Cannonball''': Somewhat archaic term for a very fast, flat serve.{{sfnp|Shine|2003|p=19|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Career Golden Slam}} '''Career Golden Slam''': In addition to having won all four major titles in their career, a player that has also won an Olympic gold medal is said to have achieved a career Golden Slam. Only four players have ever achieved this in singles: [[Steffi Graf]] (1988), [[Andre Agassi]] (1996), [[Rafael Nadal]] (2010) and [[Serena Williams]] (2012). The term is rarely used in doubles, although the feat has been more common in that discipline. It has been achieved individually by nine wheelchair tennis players and three able-bodied players ([[Pam Shriver]], [[Gigi Fern\u00e1ndez]], [[Daniel Nestor]]), and by three teams ([[The Woodies]], the [[Williams sisters]], and the [[Bryan brothers]]). [[Tennis at the Summer Olympics|Tennis at the Olympics]] was not played 1928\u20131984.\n* {{Anchor|Career Grand Slam|career grand slam}} '''Career Grand Slam''' (or '''career slam'''): Players who have won all four Major championships over the course of their career (but not within the same calendar year) are said to have won a career Grand Slam.<ref name=\"oup\"/>\n* {{Anchor|Carpet|carpet|carpet court}} '''Carpet''': A surface for tennis courts consisting of textile or polymer materials supplied in rolls. Previously common for indoor professional events, the surface was dropped from major pro tournaments in 2009. See [[carpet court]].\n* {{Anchor|Carve|carve}} '''Carve''': To hit a groundstroke shot with a combination of sidespin and underspin.\n* {{Anchor|Centre Mark|Centre mark|centre mark}} '''Centre mark''': Small mark located at the centre of the baseline. When serving the player must stand on the correct side of the mark corresponding with the score.{{sfnp|Shannon|1981|p=540|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Challenge Round|Challenge round|challenge round}} '''Challenge Round''': Final round of a tournament, in which the winner of a [[Single-elimination tournament|single-elimination]] phase faces the previous year's champion, who plays only that one match. The challenge round was used in the early history of [[The Championships, Wimbledon|Wimbledon]] (from 1877 through 1921) and the [[US Open (tennis)|US Open]] (from 1884 through 1911), and, until 1972, in the [[Davis Cup]].{{sfnp|Hedges|1978|p=251|ps=}}{{sfnp|Shine|2003|p=21\u201332|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Challenge|challenge}} '''Challenge''': When a player requests an official review of the spot where the ball landed, using electronic ball tracking technology. See [[Hawk-Eye]]. Challenges are only available in some large tournaments.\n* {{Anchor|Challenger|challenger}} '''Challenger''': A tour of tournaments one level below the top-tier [[ATP World Tour]]. Currently, Challenger tournaments compose the [[ATP Challenger Tour]]. Players, generally ranked around world no. 80 to world no. 300, compete on the Challenger tour in an effort to gain ranking points which allow them to gain entry to tournaments on the ATP World Tour.\n* {{Anchor|Change-over|change-over}} '''Change-over''' (or '''change of ends'''): 90 second rest time after every odd-numbered game when the players change ends.{{sfnp|Shine|2003|p=22|ps=}}<ref name=\"oup\">{{cite web |title=Tennis words amongst those to be added to the Oxford English Dictionary |url=https://global.oup.com/academic/news/June272017?cc=de&lang=en& |website=[[Oxford University Press]] |date=27 June 2017}}</ref>\n* {{Anchor|Chip and charge|chip and charge}} '''Chip and charge''': Type of approach shot which involves hitting a slice shot while rapidly moving forward and following the shot into the net. Aimed at putting the opponent under pressure.{{sfnp|Shine|2003|p=23|ps=}}<ref name=\"oup\"/>\n* {{Anchor|Chip|chip}} '''Chip''': Blocking a shot with underspin, creating a low trajectory.{{sfnp|Shine|2003|p=23|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Chop|chop}} '''Chop''': Shot hit with extreme underspin, opposite of topspin.{{sfnp|Hedges|1978|p=252|ps=}}{{sfnp|Robertson|1974|p=217|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Clay|clay}} '''Clay''': a natural surface made of crushed [[shale]], [[stone]], [[brick]] or [[clay]] on which tennis is played, most notably at the [[French Open]]. See: [[clay court]].\n* {{Anchor|Closed stance|closed stance}} '''Closed stance''': Classic technique in which the ball is hit while the hitter's body is facing at an angle between parallel to the baseline and with his back turned to the opponent.{{sfnp|Shine|2003|pp=25\u201326|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Code Violation|Code violation|code violation}} '''Code violation''': a rule violation on the men's and women's professional tour match called by the chair umpire which results in a player receiving an official warning or a penalty. The first violation results in a warning; the second, a point penalty; the third and more, a game penalty each. A code violation may also be judged severe enough to result in the player having to forfeit the match immediately (without having to go through the three or more automatic penalty stages). There often follows additional monetary fine for each code violation.\n* {{Anchor|Consolidate|consolidate}} '''Consolidate''' (a break): To hold serve in the game immediately following a break of serve.\n* {{Anchor|Continental grip|continental grip}} '''Continental grip''': way of holding the racket in which the bottom knuckle of the index finger is in contact with the top of the handle and the heel of the hand with the bevel directly clockwise from it.<ref name=\"oup\"/>\n* {{Anchor|Counterpuncher|counterpuncher}} '''Counterpuncher''': Defensive ''[[#baseliner|baseliner]]''. See [[tennis strategy]].\n* {{Anchor|Court|court}} '''[[Tennis court|Court]]''': Area designated for playing a game of tennis.<ref name=itfcourt>{{cite web|title=Court Rules|url=http://www.itftennis.com/technical/publications/rules/courts/overview.aspx|website=www.itftennis.com|publisher=[[International Tennis Federation]] (ITF)}}</ref>{{sfnp|Hedges|1978|pp=252\u2013253|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Cross-over|cross-over}} '''Cross-over''': Player crossing the net into the opponent's court. It can be done either in a friendly fashion, or maliciously, thereby invoking a code violation. The latter sometimes happens when it is uncertain whether the ball on a decisive point landed inside or outside the court when playing on clay, thus leaving a mark.\n* {{Anchor|Crosscourt shot|crosscourt shot}} '''Crosscourt shot''': Hitting the ball diagonally into the opponent's court.{{sfnp|Hedges|1978|p=254|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Cyclops|cyclops}} '''[[Cyclops (computer system)|Cyclops]]''': Device formerly used at [[Wimbledon Championships|Wimbledon]] and other tournaments to detect a serve that landed long, past the service line. The device emitted an audible noise when the serve was long. Succeeded by ''[[#Hawk-Eye|Hawk-Eye]]''.{{sfnp|Shine|2003|p=31\u201332|ps=}}\n\n==D==\n[[File:EVD-tenis-090.jpg|thumb|180px|An example of a ''[[#dead net|dead net cord]]'']]\n\n* {{Anchor|Dampener|dampener}} '''Dampener''' A small rubber device affixed to the strings of the racket to absorb some of the vibration caused by hitting the ball.{{sfnp|Shine|2003|p=32|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Davis Cup|Davis cup|davis cup}} '''[[Davis Cup]]''': International, annual men's tennis competition in which teams from participating countries compete in a single-elimination format, with matches occurring at several stages during the year.{{sfnp|Robertson|1974|pp=225\u2013231|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Dead net|Dead net cord|dead net|dead net cord}} '''Dead net''' (or '''dead net cord'''): Situation in which a player scores by inadvertently hitting the ball in such a way that it touches the upper cord of the net and rolls over to the other side; the player is said to have \"gotten (caught) a dead net (dead net cord)\" and considered to be lucky.\n* {{Anchor|Dead Rubber|Dead rubber|dead rubber}} '''[[Dead rubber]]''': Davis/Fed Cup match which is played after the victor of the tie has already been decided. Dead rubbers may or may not be played, depending on the coaches' agreement to do so, and are usually best of three, instead of five, sets. Typically, players who play the dead rubber are lower-ranked members of the team looking to gain Davis/Fed Cup match experience.<ref name=nytrubber/>\n* {{Anchor|Deciding point|deciding point}} '''Deciding point''': In doubles, the point played when the game score reaches deuce and there is no ad play; the game is decided in favor of whichever team wins the deuce point.\n* {{Anchor|Deep shot|deep shot}} '''Deep shot''': Shot that lands near the baseline, as opposed to near the net or mid-court.\n* {{Anchor|Default|default}} '''Default''': Disqualification of a player in a match by the chair umpire after the player has received four [[Tennis terminology#Code violation|code violation]] warnings, generally for his/her conduct on court. A '''double default''' occurs when both players are disqualified. Defaults also occur when a player misses a match with no valid excuse. Defaults are considered losses.\n* {{Anchor|Deuce court|deuce court}} '''deuce court''': Right side of the court of each player, so called because it is the area into which the ball is served when the score is deuce.\n* {{Anchor|Deuce|deuce}} '''Deuce''': Score of 40\u201340 in a game. A player must win two consecutive points from a deuce to win the game, unless the tournament employs ''deciding points'', as in the 2010 ATP World Tour Finals. A player who has won one point after deuce is said to have the [[#advantage|''advantage'']].\n* {{Anchor|Dink|dink}} '''Dink''': [[Onomatopoetic]] term for a shot with little ''pace'', usually hit close to the net.{{sfnp|Shine|2003|p=35|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Dirtballer|dirtballer}} '''Dirtballer''': Colloquial term for a [[clay court specialist]].{{sfnp|Shine|2003|p=35|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Disadvantage|Disadvantage}} '''Disadvantage''': Player or team which is 40-advantage down.\n* {{Anchor|Double Bagel|Double bagel|double bagel}} '''Double bagel''': Two sets won to love; see ''[[#bagel|bagel]]''.{{sfnp|Shine|2003|p=36|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Double Fault|Double fault|double fault}} '''Double fault''': Two serving faults in a row in one point, causing the player serving to lose the point.{{sfnp|Shine|2003|p=36|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Doubles|doubles|Men's Doubles|Men's doubles|women's doubles|Women's Doubles|Women's doubles|women's doubles}} '''Doubles''': Match played by four players, two per side of the court. A doubles court is 9&nbsp;ft (2.97m) wider than a singles court.{{sfnp|Robertson|1974|p=234|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Down the line|down the line}} '''Down the line''': Ball hit straight along the sideline to the opponent's side of the court.{{sfnp|Hedges|1978|p=254|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Draw|draw|Qualifying Draw|Qualifying draw|qualifying draw|Main Draw|Main draw|main draw}} '''Draw''': The schedule of matches in a tennis tournament. The starting fixtures are determined by a combined process of player ''seeding'' and random selection, and may or may not involve a public ''draw ceremony''. A ''qualifying draw'' is set up to arrange the starting lineup of the qualifying competition (''qualies''), from where ''unseeded'' players qualify for a place in the starting lineup or the ''main draw'' of the tournament.{{sfnp|Hedges|1978|p=254|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Drive Volley|Drive volley|drive volley|Swing Volley|Swing volley|swing volley}} '''[[Drive volley]]''' (or '''swing volley'''): a tennis volley executed with full swing or topspin drive, thus with pace and conventionally at shoulder height; in the manner of a forehand or backhand swing.{{sfnp|Shannon|1981|p=542|ps=}}<ref>[https://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/drive-volley Drive Volley ''Merriam Webster'']</ref>\n* {{Anchor|Drop Shot|Drop shot|drop shot}} '''[[Drop shot]]''': Play in which the player hits the ball lightly enough to just go over the net, usually with ''backspin''; designed to catch a player who is away from the net off guard.{{sfnp|Hedges|1978|p=254|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Drop Volley|Drop volley|drop volley}} '''Drop volley''': ''Drop shot'' executed from a ''volley'' position.\n\n==E==\n* {{Anchor|Elbow|elbow}} '''Elbow''': Corner of the baseline and the doubles alley.\n* {{Anchor|Entry System|Entry system|entry system}} '''Entry system''': Ranking system used by the ATP and WTA tours, so named because it determines whether a player has a sufficiently high ranking to gain direct acceptance (not as a qualifier or wild card) into the main draw of a tournament. A player's Entry System ranking is different from his or her Race ranking, which is reset to zero at the beginning of each year. A player carries points and the associated Entry ranking continuously unless those points are lost at a tournament at which the player had previously earned them.\n* {{Anchor|Error|error}} '''Error''':  A shot that does not land (correctly) in the opponent's court, resulting in the loss of a point.{{sfnp|Shannon|1981|p=542|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Exhibition|exhibition}} '''Exhibition''': Tournament in which players compete for the purpose of entertaining the crowd or raising money, but not ranking points on the ATP or WTA tours.\n\n==F==\n[[File:2014 US Open (Tennis) - Tournament - Bernard Tomic (14954485718).jpg|thumb|180px|Example of a ''[[#follow though|follow through]]'' action after the ball is hit]]\n\n* {{Anchor|Fault|fault}} '''Fault''': Serve that fails to land the ball in the opponent's service box, therefore not starting the point. See also ''double fault'' and ''foot fault''.{{sfnp|Hedges|1978|pp=254\u2013255|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Fed Cup|Fed cup|fed cup}} '''[[Fed Cup]]''' (or '''Federation Cup'''): International, annual women's tennis competition in which teams from participating countries compete in a single-elimination format tournament with matches occurring at several stages during the year.{{sfnp|Robertson|1974|pp=241\u2013243|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|First Service|First service|first service}} '''First serve''': The first of the two attempts to serve that a player is allowed at the beginning of a point. A let serve that lands inbounds does not count as a serve.\n* {{Anchor|Five|five}} '''Five''': Number of games completed (e.g. \"7\u20135\" is spoken as \"seven\u2013five\"), or a spoken abbreviation of \"15\" in points (e.g. a score of 40\u201315 is sometimes spoken as \"forty\u2013five\").\n* {{Anchor|Flat|flat}} '''[[Flat (tennis)|Flat]]''' (or '''flat shot'''): Shot with relatively little spin and usually hard-hit.{{sfnp|Shannon|1981|p=542|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Flatliner|flatliner}} '''Flatliner''': Player who hits the ball ''flat'' with a very low trajectory with exceptional depth and accuracy. Examples include [[Andre Agassi]] and [[Lindsay Davenport]].\n* {{Anchor|Follow through|follow through}} '''Follow through''': Portion of a swing after the ball is hit.{{sfnp|Robertson|1974|p=243|ps=}}{{sfnp|Shannon|1981|p=542|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Foot Fault|Foot fault|foot fault}} '''Foot fault''': Type of service fault in which a player, during the serve, steps on or over the baseline into the court before striking the ball. A foot fault may also occur if the player steps on or across the center hash mark and its imaginary perpendicular extension from the baseline to the net. The definition of a foot fault has changed several times since the introduction of (lawn) tennis.{{sfnp|Hedges|1978|p=255|ps=}} \n* {{Anchor|Forced error|forced error}} '''Forced error''': Error caused by an opponent's good play; contrasted with an ''[[#unforced error|unforced error]]''. Counting forced errors as well as unforced errors is partly subjective.{{sfnp|Shannon|1981|p=542|ps=}}<ref name=\"oup\"/>\n* {{Anchor|Forehand|forehand}} '''[[Forehand]]''': Stroke in which the player hits the ball with the front of the racket hand facing the ball; contrasted with ''backhand''.{{sfnp|Hedges|1978|p=255|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Frame shot|frame shot}} '''Frame shot''': A mishit on the frame of the racket rather than the strings. \n* {{Anchor|Fry|fry}} '''Fry''': See ''[[#breadstick|breadstick]]''.\n* {{Anchor|Futures|futures}} '''Futures''': Series of men's tour tennis tournaments which compose the [[ITF Men's Circuit]], a tour two levels below the ATP World Tour and one level below the ATP Challenger Tour. Players compete in Futures events (generally when ranked below world no. 300 or so) to garner enough ranking points to gain entry into Challenger events.\n\n==G==\n* {{Anchor|Game point|game point}} '''[[Tennis score|Game point]]''': Situation in which the server is leading and needs one more point to win the game. See also ''[[#break point|break point]]''.{{sfnp|Shannon|1981|p=543|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Game|game}} '''Game''': A game consists of a sequence of ''[[#point|points]]'' played with the same player serving and is a segment of a ''set''. Each ''set'' consists of at least six games.{{sfnp|Shannon|1981|p=543|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Get|get}} '''Get''': Reaching and returning a ball that is difficult to retrieve.\n* {{Anchor|Ghost in to the net|Ghost into the Net}} '''Ghost in to the net''': To approach the net from the baseline while the opposing player is focused on retrieving a ball and therefore unaware that the player is approaching the net.\n* {{Anchor|GOAT}} '''GOAT''': Colloquial acronym for ''Greatest Of All Time''.\n* {{Anchor|Golden Bagel Award|Golden Bagel award|golden bagel award}} '''[[Golden Bagel Award]]''': Award for male players winning the most ''bagels'' (sets won 6\u20130), from January 1 until the year-end tournament. Davis Cup matches and incomplete sets are not counted.\n* {{Anchor|Golden Set|Golden set|Golden set}} '''[[Golden set (tennis)|Golden set]]''': A set that is won without dropping a single point.\n* {{Anchor|Golden Slam|Golden slam|golden slam}} '''[[Golden Slam]]''': Winning the Grand Slam and the [[Tennis at the Summer Olympics|tennis Olympic]] gold medal in a calendar year. This has only ever been achieved once, by [[Steffi Graf]] in 1988. See also ''career Golden Slam''\n* {{Anchor|Grand Slam|Grand Slams|Grand slam|grand slam}} '''[[Grand Slam (tennis)|Grand Slam]]''': Winning all four of the prestigious major tournaments in a calendar year. \"Grand Slam\" is also commonly used to refer to any one of the four tournaments: the [[Australian Open]], the [[French Open]] (Roland Garros), [[Wimbledon Championships|Wimbledon]], and the [[U.S. Open (tennis)|U.S. Open]].  See also [[#Career Grand Slam|Career Grand Slam]].{{sfnp|Hedges|1978|p=255|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|grass}} '''Grass''': A natural [[Lawn#Uses|turf]] surface tennis is played on, most notably at [[The Championships, Wimbledon|Wimbledon]].  See: [[grass court]].\n* {{Anchor|Grinding|grinding}} '''Grinding''': Playing out points with a series of shots from the baseline. See also [[Wear|attrition]].\n* {{Anchor|Grip|grip}} '''Grip''': A way of holding the racket in order to hit shots during a match. The three most commonly used conventional grips are the Continental, the Eastern and the Western. Most players change grips during a match depending on which shot they are hitting. For further information on grips, including all the types, see [[grip (tennis)]].{{sfnp|Robertson|1974|pp=257\u2013258|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Grommet strip|grommet strip}} '''Grommet strip''': A strip of plastic containing small tubes that are placed in the frame's string holes to prevent the strings from rubbing against the abrasive frame.{{sfnp|Shine|2003|p=56|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Groundies|groundies}} '''Groundie''': Colloquial word for a ''[[#groundstroke|groundstroke]]''.\n* {{Anchor|Groundstroke|groundstroke}} '''[[Groundstroke]]''': Forehand or backhand shot that is executed after the ball bounces once on the court.{{sfnp|Shannon|1981|p=543|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Grunting|grunting}} '''[[grunting (tennis)|Grunting]]''': Noises made by players while either serving or hitting the ball.{{sfnp|Hedges|1978|p=256|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Natural Gut|Natural gut|natural gut}} '''[[Strings (tennis)#Natural Gut|Gut]]''': Type of racket string. Can be made from [[catgut]] or synthetic gut.{{sfnp|Shannon|1981|p=543|ps=}}\n\n==H==\n* {{Anchor|Hacker|hacker}} '''Hacker''': Player whose clumsy strokes seem more accidental than intentional.{{sfnp|Shannon|1981|p=543|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Hail Mary|Hail mary|hail Mary|hail mary}} '''Hail Mary''': Extremely high lob, for defensive purposes.\n* {{Anchor|Half court|half court}} '''Half court''': The area of the court in the vicinity of the service line.\n* {{Anchor|Half volley|half volley}} '''[[Half volley]]''': A groundstroke shot made immediately after a bounce or simultaneous to the bounce and played with the racket close to the ground.{{sfnp|Hedges|1978|p=256|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Handicapping|handicapping}} '''Handicapping''' A system in which competitors are given advantages or compensations to equalize the chances of winning.{{sfnp|Hedges|1978|p=256|ps=}}{{sfnp|Robertson|1974|pp=258\u2013259|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Hardcourt|hardcourt}} '''Hardcourt''' (or '''hard court'''): A type of court which is made of asphalt or concrete with a synthetic/acrylic layer on top. They can vary in color and tend to play medium-fast to fast.\n* {{Anchor|Hawk-Eye|Hawk-eye|hawk-eye|Hawkeye|hawkeye}} '''[[Hawk-Eye]]''': Computer system connected to cameras to track the path of the ball for replay purposes; used with the player challenge system to contest and review designated [[#line call|line call]]s.\n* {{Anchor|Head|head}} '''Head''' (or '''racket head'''): Portion of the racket that contains the strings.{{sfnp|Shine|2003|p=97|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Heavy|heavy}} '''Heavy''' (ball): Ball hit with so much topspin that it feels \"heavy\" when the opposing player strikes it.\n* {{Anchor|Hit and giggle|hit and giggle}} '''Hit and giggle''': non-competitive social tennis.\n* {{Anchor|Hitting Partner|Hitting partner|hitting partner}} '''Hitting partner''' (or '''sparring partner'''): specialist employed by a tennis player to practice strokes during training\n* {{Anchor|Hold|hold}} '''Hold''' (or '''hold serve'''): To win the game when serving. Compare ''break''.\n\n==I==\n* {{Anchor|I-formation|i-formation}} '''[[I-formation (tennis)|I-formation]]''': Formation used in doubles where the net player on the serving team crouches roughly at the centre service line; used mainly to counter teams that prefer a crosscourt return.{{sfnp|Grasso|2011|p=143|ps=}}<ref>{{cite web|author1=David Cox|title=The I Formation: when, why and how to use it|url=http://www.tennis.com.au/news/2014/07/30/the-i-formation-when-why-and-how-to-use-it|publisher=Tennis Australia|date=30 July 2014}}</ref>\n* {{Anchor|Inside-in|inside-in|}} '''Inside-in''': Running around the backhand side to hit a forehand ''down the line.'' Vice versa for inside in backhand.\n* {{Anchor|Inside-out|inside-out}} '''Inside-out''': Running around the backhand side and hitting a ''crosscourt'' forehand. Vice versa for inside out backhand.\n* {{Anchor|Insurance Break|Insurance break|insurance break|}} '''Insurance break''': Break that achieves an overall advantage of two breaks of serve.\n* {{Anchor|ITF|ipin}} '''IPIN''': Abbreviation for International Player Identification Number, a registration number required for all professional tennis players and administered by the governing body ITF.\n* {{Anchor|ITF|ITF entry}} '''ITF entry''': High-ranking ITF players can be awarded a spot into ATP Challenger and ITF women's tournaments main draws based on their ITF ranking.\n* {{Anchor|ITF|itf}} '''ITF''': Abbreviation for [[International Tennis Federation]], the governing body of world tennis. Founded in 1913 as the International Lawn Tennis Federation (ILTF).{{sfnp|Robertson|1974|p=265|ps=}}\n\n==J==\n* {{Anchor|Jamming|jamming}} '''Jamming''': Serving or returning straight into the opponent's body.\n* {{Anchor|Junior exempt|Junior exempt}} '''Junior exempt''' (\"'''JE'''\"): High-ranking junior players can be awarded a spot in the draw of a tournament through the ITF's junior exempt project.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.itftennis.com/juniors/players/junior-exempt.aspx|title=Junior Exempt|publisher=[[International Tennis Federation]]|accessdate=2 February 2016}}</ref>\n* {{Anchor|Junk ball|junk ball}} '''Junk ball''': A shot or return stroke in which the ball tends to be slow and possibly also without spin; often introduced unpredictably to upset the flow of the game and the rhythm of the opposition.\n\n==K==\n\n* {{Anchor|Kick serve|kick serve}} '''[[Twist serve|Kick serve]]''': Type of spin serve that bounces high. Introduced in the United States in the late 1880s and called the ''American twist''.{{sfnp|Hedges|1978|pp=251, 259\u2013260|ps=}}<ref>{{cite web|author1=Rod Croft|title=How to hit a fierce kick serve|url=http://www.tennis.com.au/news/2013/06/06/how-to-hit-a-fierce-kick-serve|website=www.tennis.com.au|publisher=Tennis Australia|date=6 June 2013}}</ref>\n* {{Anchor|Knock-up|knock-up}} '''Knock-up''': Practice or warm-up session without scoring which usually precedes the start of competitive play.{{sfnp|Shannon|1981|p=543|ps=}}<ref>{{cite web|author1=Jonathan Overend|title=Pre-match knock-ups should be scrapped|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/blogs/legacy/jonathanoverend/2011/12/tennis_knock-up.html|website=www.bbc.co.uk|publisher=BBC|date=21 December 2011}}</ref>\n\n==L==\n[[File:Line Judges Centre Court.JPG|thumb|180px|''[[#line judge|Line judges]]'' at [[The Championships, Wimbledon|Wimbledon]]]]\n* {{Anchor|Lawn tennis|Lawn tennis}} '''Lawn tennis''': \"Regular\" tennis, as opposed to [[real tennis]], the game from which tennis is derived. Reflects the fact that the game was first played on grass.{{sfnp|Shine|2003|p=70|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Let-check|let-check}} '''Let-check''': Electronic sensor on the net that assists chair umpires in calling lets by detecting vibration. Typically, it is used only on show courts in professional matches, like electronic review. Players and commentators occasionally complain that such devices are too sensitive, that is, indicate too many [[false positive]]s.\n* {{Anchor|Let|let|Do-over|do-over}} '''Let''': A call that requires the point to be replayed. The umpire indicates this type of let by announcing \"Let. First serve,\" or \"Let. Second serve.\" Lets typically occur when an otherwise-valid serve makes contact with the net before hitting the ground. Theoretically, a player could serve an infinite number of otherwise-valid let serves, but a serve that touches the net and then lands out of bounds counts as one of the two allowed serves. A let can also be called during play when there is some distraction to either player not caused by the players themselves, such as a ball boy moving behind a receiver, debris flying across the court in windy conditions, or a ball accidentally falling out of a player's pocket or entering from a neighboring court. The call is made by the chair umpire when one is assigned to the match, as in professional matches, or one of the players when there is no chair umpire. When a receiver is legitimately unprepared for a serve, a let is technically the result, even if the word goes unspoken.<ref>{{cite book|title=Rules of Tennis|year=2012|publisher=ITF|url=http://www.itftennis.com/media/117960/117960.pdf|page=9}}</ref>{{sfnp|Shine|2003|pp=70\u201371|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Line call|line call}} '''[[Line call]]''' (or '''call'''): Call made by the ''[[#line judge|line judge]]''. A call of 'out' will be made in combination with an outstretched arm pointing sideways if a ball lands outside the court and if the ball is 'in', i.e. lands on or within the outer lines, this is indicated by holding both hands flattened and the arms stretched downwards.{{sfnp|Shine|2003|p=71|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Line judge|line judge}} '''Line judge''' (or '''linesman''', '''lineswoman''' or '''line umpire'''): Person designated to observe the passage of tennis balls over the boundary lines of the court. A line judge can declare that a play was inside or outside the play area and cannot be overruled by the players. Line judges must defer to an umpire's decision, even when it contradicts their own observations.{{sfnp|Hedges|1978|p=256|ps=}}{{sfnp|Grasso|2011|p=175|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Lingering Death tiebreak|Lingering death tiebreak|lingering death tiebreak|Lingering Death|Lingering death|lingering death}} '''Lingering death tiebreak''': Version of the tiebreak played as the best of twelve points, with a two-point advantage needed to clinch the set.{{sfnp|Shine|2003|p=72|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Lob Volley|Lob volley|lob volley}} '''Lob volley''': Type of ''[[#volley|volley]]'' shot aimed at lobbing the ball over the opponent and normally played when the opponent is in the vicinity of the net.{{sfnp|Shannon|1981|p=544|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Lob|lob}} '''[[Lob (tennis)|Lob]]''': Stroke in which the ball is hit high above the net. If the opposing player or players are up at the net, the intention may be an offensive lob in order to win the point outright. In a defensive lob, the intent is to give the player time to recover and get in position, or, if the opponents are at the net, to force them to chase down the lob. See also ''[[#moonball|moonball]]''.{{sfnp|Hedges|1978|p=256|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Love game|love game}} '''Love game''': Shutout game, won without the opponent scoring a single point.{{sfnp|Shine|2003|p=75|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Love|love}} '''Love''': A [[#Scoring|score]] of zero (e.g. \"15-0\" is spoken \"fifteen-love\"; \"to hold to love\" means \"to win the game when serving with the opponent scoring zero points\"; \"to break to love\" means \"to win the game when receiving with the opponent scoring zero points\"). Thought to be derived from the French term, ''l'oeuf'', literally ''the egg'', meaning nothing; less popular alternative theory claiming it to be from the Dutch word ''lof doen'', meaning honour.<ref>Palmatier, Robert.  [https://books.google.com/books?id=kSr4fO2zYrIC&pg=PA245&dq=love+l%27oeuf+tennis&hl=en&ei=Flr8S8ukFYOB8gb_4ND6BQ&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=2&ved=0CC0Q6AEwAQ#v=onepage&q=love%20l%27oeuf%20tennis&f=false Speaking of animals: a dictionary of animal metaphors], page 245 (1995).</ref><ref>Horn, Geoffrey.  [https://books.google.com/books?id=tQoY647Kk-wC&pg=PA13&dq=love+l%27oeuf+tennis&hl=en&ei=Flr8S8ukFYOB8gb_4ND6BQ&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=3&ved=0CDIQ6AEwAg#v=onepage&q=love%20l%27oeuf%20tennis&f=false Rafael Nadal], page 13 (2006).</ref>{{sfnp|Shine|2003|pp=74\u201375|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Lucky Loser|Lucky loser|lucky loser}} '''[[Lucky loser]]''' (\"'''LL'''\"): Highest-ranked player to lose in the final round of qualifying for a tournament, but still ends up qualifying because of a sudden withdrawal by one of the players already in the main draw. In Grand Slam events, one of the four highest-ranked losers in the final qualifying round is randomly picked as the lucky loser.\n\n==M==\n* {{Anchor|Mac-Cam|Mac-cam|mac-cam|MACCam}} '''[[Mac-Cam]]''': High-speed video camera used for televised instant replays of close shots landing on/near the baseline. Name derived from [[John McEnroe]].\n* {{Anchor|Masters Cup|Masters cup|masters cup}} '''[[Masters Cup]]''': Former name of the year-end ATP championship, in which the eight highest-ranked players compete in a [[Round-robin tournament|round-robin]] format.\n* {{Anchor|Match|match}} '''Match''': A contest between two players (singles match)  or two teams of players (doubles match), normally played as the best of three or five sets.{{sfnp|Hedges|1978|p=256|ps=}}{{sfnp|Shannon|1981|p=544|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Match point|match point}} '''Match point''': Situation in which the player who is leading needs one more point to win the match. Variations of the term are possible; e.g. ''championship point'' is the match point in the final match of a championship or a ''gold medal point'' is the match point in the final match of the Olympics.{{sfnp|Shannon|1981|p=544|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Mercedes Super 9|Super 9|super 9|Super Nine|Super nine|super nine}} '''Mercedes Super 9''': Former name for the nine ATP Tour Masters 1000 tournaments.\n* {{Anchor|Mini-break|mini-break}} '''Mini-break''': Point won from the opponent's serve. The term is usually used in a tiebreak, but it can be used during normal service games as well. To be \"up a mini-break\" means that the player has one more mini-break than his/her opponent.\n* {{Anchor|Mini-hold|mini-hold}} '''Mini-hold''': Point won by the server, usually in a tiebreak.\n* {{Anchor|MIPTC|miptc}} '''MIPTC''': Abbreviation for [[Men's International Professional Tennis Council]], administrative body of the tournaments that composed the [[Grand Prix tennis circuit]]. Existed from 1974 until the creation of the [[ATP Tour]] in 1989.\n* {{Anchor|Mis-hit|mis-hit}} '''Mis-hit''': Stroke in which the racket fails to make contact with the ball in the \"sweetspot\" area of the strings.\n* {{Anchor|Mixed Doubles|Mixed doubles|mixed doubles}} '''mixed doubles''': Match played by four players, two male, two female, one of each sex per side of the court.{{sfnp|Shannon|1981|p=544|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Moonball|moonball}} '''Moonball''': A type of groundstroke that is hit with a lot of topspin, usually with the forehand, to create a high, slow, floating shot that lands close to the opponent's baseline. See also ''[[#lob|lob]]''.<ref>{{cite news|author1=Ben Rothenberg|title=Wozniacki Survives Battle of Moonballs|url=http://straightsets.blogs.nytimes.com/2013/03/16/wozniacki-survives-battle-of-moonballs/?_r=0|work=The New York Times|date=16 March 2013|access-date=7 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150207210531/http://straightsets.blogs.nytimes.com/2013/03/16/wozniacki-survives-battle-of-moonballs/?_r=0|archive-date=7 February 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author1=Ron Waite|title=A Tennis Stroke That Is \"Out Of This World\"|url=http://www.tennisserver.com/turbo/turbo_09_02.html|publisher=The Tennis Server}}</ref>\n* {{Anchor|MOP|mop}} '''MOP''': Point at 0\u201330; stands for major opportunity point.\n* '''Main draw''': See ''[[#draw|draw]]''.\n\n==N==\n* {{Anchor|Net cord|net cord|netcord}} '''Net cord''': see ''dead net cord''\n* {{Anchor|Net point|net point}} '''Net point''': Point won or lost on approaching the net, as opposed to a point won or lost by a stroke from the baseline.\n* {{Anchor|Net posts|net posts}} '''Net posts''': Posts on each side of the court which hold up the net. The net posts are placed 3 feet (0.914 m) outside the doubles court on each side, unless a singles net is used, in which case the posts are placed 3 feet (0.914 m) outside the singles court.<ref name=itfcourt/>\n* {{Anchor|Net sticks|net stick}} '''Net sticks''' (or '''[[#singles sticks|singles sticks]]'''): Pair of poles placed on the singles line to support the net during a singles match.{{sfnp|Shannon|1981|p=544|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Net|net}} '''Net''': Interlaced fabric, cord, and tape stretched across the entire width of the court; it is held up by the posts.{{sfnp|Robertson|1974|p=287|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|New balls|new balls}} '''New balls''': New set of balls replacing the old ones during the game from time to time due to the fact that strokes make the ball heat up and alter its bounce characteristics; the player first to serve one of the new balls shows it to the opponent.\n* {{Anchor|No-Man's Land|No man's land|No-man's land|no-man's land|no man's land}} '''No-man's land''': Area between the service line and the baseline, where a player is most vulnerable.{{sfnp|Shannon|1981|p=544|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Non-endemic products|non-endemic products}} '''Non-endemic products''': Products for tennis sponsorship that are not intrinsic to the sport such as watches, cars, jewelry.\n* {{Anchor|Not up|Not Up|not up|not Up}} '''Not up''': Call given by the umpire when a player plays a ball that has already bounced twice, i.e. the ball was out of play when the player played it.\n* {{Anchor|NTRP Rating|NTRP rating|NTRP}} '''NTRP rating''': National Tennis Rating Program rating; system used in the United States to rank players on a scale from 1 to 7, with 1 being an absolute beginner and 7 a touring pro.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.usta.com/USTA/Global/Active/Custom%20Pages/Leagues/1237_NTRP.aspx |title=USTA National Tennis Ranking Program (NTRP) |publisher=[[USTA]] |accessdate=2009-08-21 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090820090732/http://www.usta.com/USTA/Global/Active/Custom%20Pages/Leagues/1237_NTRP.aspx |archive-date=2009-08-20 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==O==\n* {{Anchor|Official|official}} '''[[Official (tennis)|Official]]''': Member of the officiating team: tournament referee, chair umpire, or linesman.\n* {{Anchor|On one's racket|on one's racket}} '''on one's racket''': A situation in which a player can win the match, set, or tiebreak by holding serve.  This occurs when a player breaks the opponent's serve or achieves a mini break in a tiebreak.<ref><!-- \"And Zverev had the match on his racket, with match point at 5-4. But Zverev had a sitter that he hit into the net.\" -->{{Cite news|url=http://www.bnpparibasopen.com/en/media-and-news/news/2016/03/16/nadal-reacts-to-zverev-win|title=Nadal Reacts To Zverev Win {{!}} BNP Paribas Open|work=BNP Paribas Open|access-date=2017-07-15|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.atpworldtour.com/en/news/federer-stuttgart-2016-sf-reaction|title=Federer Stuttgart 2016 SF Reaction {{!}} ATP World Tour {{!}} Tennis|work=ATP World Tour|access-date=2017-07-15|language=en}}<!-- \"After Thiem saved a match point serving at 5/6, Federer had the match on his racquet at 7/6.\" --></ref><ref><!-- \"The next eight points went on serve; Ferrer had the set on his racquet when he took the balls with two serves to come at 5-4.\" -->{{Cite news|url=http://www.tennis.com/pro-game/2012/07/inadequately-heartbreaking/38079/|title=Inadequately Heartbreaking|work=Tennis.com|access-date=2017-07-15}}</ref><ref><!-- \"Once he had broken for 4-2, he had the set on his racquet at 5-3.\" -->{{Cite news|url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-sports/fantastic-federer-shows-his-class-on-grass/article3611733.ece|title=Fantastic Federer shows his class on grass|work=The Hindu|access-date=2017-07-15|language=en}}</ref>\n* {{Anchor|On serve|on serve}} '''On serve''': Situation where both players or teams have the same number of breaks in a set. While on serve, neither player or team can win the set without a break of serve. An advantage set requires at least one break to win.\n* {{Anchor|Open Era|open era}} '''Open Era''': Period in tennis which began in 1968 when tournaments became open to both amateurs and professional players.{{sfnp|Shine|2003|p=85|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Open stance|open stance}} '''Open stance''': Modern technique in which the hitter's body facing is at an angle between parallel to the baseline and facing the opponent. See also ''[[#closed stance|closed stance]]''.\n* {{Anchor|OP|op}} '''OP''': Stands for opportunity point; 15\u201330, an opportunity to potentially break serve.\n* {{Anchor|Out|out}} '''Out''': An error in which the ball lands outside the playing area.{{sfnp|Shine|2003|p=86|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Overgrip|overgrip|Overwrap|overwrap}} '''Overgrip''' (or '''overwrap'''): padded tape spirally wrapped over the handle or grip of the racket to absorb moisture or add gripping assistance.{{sfnp|Shine|2003|p=86|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Overhead|overhead}} '''Overhead''': Stroke in which the player hits the ball over his/her head; if the shot is hit relatively strongly, it is referred to as a [[Smash (tennis)|smash]]; smashes are often referred to as simply ''overheads'', although not every overhead shot is a smash.{{sfnp|Shine|2003|p=87|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Overrule|overrule}} '''Overrule''': To reverse a call made by a ''[[#line judge|line judge]]'', done by the ''[[#umpire|umpire]]''.{{sfnp|Shine|2003|p=87|ps=}}\n\n==P==\n* {{Anchor|Paint the lines|paint the lines}} '''Paint the lines''': To hit shots that land as close to the lines of the court as possible.\n* {{Anchor|Passing shot|passing shot}} '''Pass''' (or '''passing shot'''): Type of shot, usually played in the vicinity of the baseline, that passes by (not over) the opponent at the net. See also ''[[#lob|lob]]''.{{sfnp|Shannon|1981|p=545|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Percentage tennis|percentage tennis}} '''Percentage tennis''': Style of play consisting of safe shots with large margins of error. Aimed at keeping the ball in play in anticipation of an opponent's error.<ref name=\"oup\"/>\n* {{Anchor|Poaching|poaching}} '''Poaching''' (noun: '''poach'''): In doubles, an aggressive move where the player at the net moves to volley a shot intended for his/her partner.{{sfnp|Hedges|1978|p=257|ps=}}{{sfnp|Shannon|1981|p=545|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Point|point}} '''[[Point (tennis)|Point]]''': Period of play between the first successful service of a ball and the point at which that ball goes out of play. It is the smallest unit of ''[[#scoring|scoring]]'' in tennis.{{sfnp|Shine|2003|p=90|ps=}}\n*{{Anchor|Pre-qualifying|pre-qualifying}} '''Pre-qualifying''': Tournament in which the winner earns a wild card into a tournament's qualifying draw.\n* {{Anchor|Pressureless Ball|Pressureless ball|pressureless ball}} '''Pressureless ball''': Special type of tennis ball that does not have a core of pressurized air as standard balls do, but rather has a core made of solid rubber, or a core filled tightly with micro-particles.  Quality pressureless balls are approved for top-pro play generally, but pressureless balls are typically used mostly at high altitudes, where standard balls would be greatly affected by the difference between the high pressure in the ball and the thin air.\n* {{Anchor|Protected Ranking|Protected ranking|protected ranking}} '''Protected ranking''' (\"'''PR'''\"): Players injured for a minimum of six months can ask for a protected ranking, which is based on his or her average ranking during the first three months of his or her injury. The player can use his or her protected ranking to enter tournaments' main draws or qualifying competitions when coming back from injury.<ref name=atprankingsfaq>{{cite web|title=Rankings FAQ|url=http://www.atpworldtour.com/Rankings/Rankings-FAQ.aspx|website=www.atpworldtour.com|publisher=[[Association of Tennis Professionals]] (ATP)}}</ref> It is also used in the [[Women's Tennis Association|WTA]] for players returning from [[pregnancy]] leave.<ref>https://uk.reuters.com/article/uk-tennis-women-wta/wta-increases-rankings-protection-for-returning-mothers-idUKKBN1OG28M</ref>\n* {{Anchor|Pulp|pulp}} '''Pulp''': 30\u201330, not quite ''deuce'' (punning on the [[homophone]] \"juice\").\n* {{Anchor|Pusher|pusher}} '''[[Pusher (tennis)|Pusher]]''': Player who does not try to hit winners, but only to return the ball safely; often used in a derogative manner.\n* {{Anchor|Putaway|putaway}} '''Putaway''': Offensive shot to try to end the point with no hope of a return.{{sfnp|Shannon|1981|p=546|ps=}}\n*'''Ping it''': To hit an offensive shot and place the ball deep to the corners of the court.\n\n==Q==\n* {{Anchor|Qualies|qualies}} '''Qualies''': Short for ''qualification rounds'' or similar.{{sfnp|Grasso|2011|p=229|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Qualification round|qualification round}} '''Qualification round''': Final round of play in a pre-tournament qualification competition, also known as ''qualies''.{{sfnp|Grasso|2011|p=229|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Qualifier|qualifier}} '''Qualifier''' (\"'''Q'''\"): Player who reaches the tournament's main draw by competing in a pre-tournament qualifying competition, rather than automatically by virtue of his/her world ranking, by being awarded a wild card, or other exemption.{{sfnp|Grasso|2011|p=229|ps=}}\n* '''Qualifying draw''': See ''[[#draw|draw]]''.\n\n==R==\n[[File:Babolat pure drive plus.jpg|thumb|180px|A modern ''[[#racket|tennis racket]]'']]\n\n* {{Anchor|Racquet abuse|racquet abuse|Racket abuse|racket abuse}} '''Racket abuse''' ('''racquet abuse'''): When a player slams their racket into the ground or net in frustration. Can result in a warning from the umpire or docking of points.\n* {{Anchor|Racquet|racquet|Racket|racket}} '''[[tennis racket|Racket]]''' (or '''racquet'''): Bat with a long handle and a large looped frame with a string mesh tautly stretched across it, the frame made of wood, metal, graphite, composite, or some other synthetic material, used by a tennis player to hit the tennis ball during a game of tennis.{{sfnp|Hedges|1978|pp=257\u2013258|ps=}}{{sfnp|Grasso|2011|p=231|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Rally|rally}} '''[[Rally (tennis)|Rally]]''': Following the service of a tennis ball, a series of return hits of the ball that ends when one or other player fails to return the ball within the court boundary or fails to return a ball that falls within the play area.{{sfnp|Hedges|1978|p=258|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Rankings|rankings}} '''Rankings''': A hierarchical listing of players based on their recent achievements. Used to determine qualification for entry and seeding in tournaments.{{sfnp|Hedges|1978|p=257|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Rating|rating}} '''Rating''': A system used by national tennis organizations to group players of comparable skills. The rating of players is dependent on their match record.{{sfnp|Shine|2003|p=100|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Real tennis|real tennis}} '''[[Real tennis]]''' (also '''royal tennis''' or '''court tennis'''):  An indoor racket sport which was the predecessor of the modern game of (lawn) tennis. The term ''real'' is used as a [[retronym]] to distinguish the ancient game from the modern game of lawn tennis. Known also as ''court tennis'' in the United States or ''royal tennis'' in Australia.{{sfnp|Shine|2003|pp=101\u2013102|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Receiver|receiver}} '''Receiver''': Player who is receiving the ''[[#serve|service]]'' of the opponent.{{sfnp|Hedges|1978|p=258|ps=}}<ref>{{cite web|title=The rankings riddle|url=http://www.tennis.com.au/news/2014/06/20/the-rankings-riddle|website=www.tennis.com.au|publisher=Tennis Australia|date=20 June 2014}}</ref>\n* {{Anchor|Referee|referee}} '''[[Official (Tennis)#Referee|Referee]]''': Person in charge of enforcing the rules in a tournament, as opposed to a tennis match. See also ''[[#umpire|umpire]]''.{{sfnp|Robertson|1974|p=304|ps=}}{{sfnp|Shannon|1981|p=546|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Reflex Volley|Reflex volley|reflex volley}} '''Reflex volley''': Volley in which the player has no time to plan the shot, and instead reacts instinctively to get the racket in position to return the ball. This occurs frequently in doubles and in advanced singles.\n* {{Anchor|Registered player|registered player}} '''Registered player''': A designation used during the beginning of the Open Era to identify a category of amateur tennis players who were allowed to compete for prize money but stayed under the control of their national associations. \n* {{Anchor|Retirement|retirement}} '''Retirement''' (\"'''ret.'''\"): Player's withdrawal during a match, causing the player to forfeit the tournament. Usually this happens due to injury. For a pre-match withdrawal, see ''[[#walkover|walkover]]''.\n* {{Anchor|Retriever|retriever}} '''Retriever''': Defensive baseliner who relies on returning the ball rather than scoring direct winners. See [[tennis strategy]].{{sfnp|Shannon|1981|p=546|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Return Ace|Return ace|return ace}} '''Return ace''': Shot in which the opponent serves, the receiver returns the serve, and the opponent does not hit the ball.\n* {{Anchor|Return|return}} '''Return''': Stroke made by the receiver of a service.{{sfnp|Robertson|1974|p=305|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Rising Shot|Rising shot|rising shot}} '''Rising shot''': Shot in which the ball is hit before it reaches its apex; also ''hitting on the rise''.\n* {{Anchor|Round of 16|Round of sixteen}} '''Round of 16''': Round of a tournament prior to the quarterfinals in which there are 16 players remaining, corresponds to the fourth round of 128-draw tournament, the third round of a 64-draw, and second round of a 32-draw tournament.\n* {{Anchor|Round Robin|Round robin|round robin}} '''Round robin''' (\"'''RR'''\"): Tournament format in which players are organised into groups of three or four players and compete against all other members of the group. Players are then ranked according to number of matches, sets, and games won and head-to-head records. The top one, two, or four players then qualify for the next stage of the tournament.{{sfnp|Hedges|1978|p=258|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Rubber|rubber}} '''Rubber''': Individual match, singles or doubles, within a Davis Cup or Fed Cup ''[[#tie|tie]]''.<ref name=nytrubber>{{cite news|author1=Stuart Miller|title=Quirks of the Game: Davis Cup\u2019s Strange Lingo|url=http://straightsets.blogs.nytimes.com/2012/11/15/quirks-of-the-game-davis-cups-strange-lingo/|work=The New York Times|date=15 November 2012|access-date=7 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150922041224/http://straightsets.blogs.nytimes.com/2012/11/15/quirks-of-the-game-davis-cups-strange-lingo/|archive-date=22 September 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref>{{sfnp|Hedges|1978|p=259|ps=}}\n\n==S==\n[[File:Azarenka Roland Garros 2009 2.jpg|thumb|180px|Preparing to ''[[#serve|serve]]'' to start a ''[[#point|point]]'']]\n\n[[File:Joao Souza (14706260226).jpg|thumb|180px|Player preparing to hit a backhand ''[[#slice|slice shot]]'']]\n\n<!-- 'serving wide':  See Talk page, the section entitled 'serving wide'.  --> \n* {{Anchor|SABR|SABR}} '''SABR''' (Sneak Attack By Roger): a ploy where a returner rushes forward during a serve to catch an opponent off guard with a quick return. Popularized by [[Roger Federer]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Federer defends 'SABR' attack as US Open final tension builds|url=https://sports.yahoo.com/news/ageless-federer-braced-straight-shootout-djokovic-031717637--ten.html|accessdate=13 September 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/tennis/rogerfederer/11859167/US-Open-2015-Roger-Federers-aggressive-new-SABR-shot-is-not-disrespectful-but-it-is-brilliant.html | title=The Telegraph: Roger Federer's aggressive new SABR shot | accessdate=8 December 2015| date=2015-09-11 | last1=Cary | first1=Tom }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://ftw.usatoday.com/2015/09/what-is-roger-federers-new-sabr-move | title=USA Today: What is Roger Federer's new SABR move? | accessdate=8 December 2015| date=2015-09-10 }}</ref>\n* {{Anchor|Satellite|scratch}} '''Satellite''': Intermediate junior level of play, equivalent of Level 6\n* {{Anchor|scoring|scoring}} '''Scoring''': Method of tracking progress of a match. A match consists of ''points'', ''game'' and ''sets''.{{sfnp|Grasso|2011|p=255\u2013256|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Scratch|scratch}} '''Scratch''': Withdrawal from a match due to an injury.\n* {{Anchor|Second Service|Second service|second service|Second Serve|Second serve|second serve}} '''Second serve''': Second and final of the two serve attempts a player is allowed at the beginning of a point, not counting net cord let serves that would otherwise be good.\n* {{Anchor|Second Snap|Second snap|second snap}} '''Second snap''': a tennis ball struck for top spin against lubricated or co-poly strings will get extra rotation on the ball from the mains popping back in position before the ball leaves contact with the racket.\n* {{Anchor|Seed|seed}} '''Seed''' (or '''seeding'''): Player whose position in a tournament has been arranged based on his/her ranking so as not to meet other ranking players in the early rounds of play. Named for the similarity to scattering seeds widely over the ground to plant them. For a given tournament there is a specified number of seeds, depending on the size of the draw. For ATP tournaments, typically one out of four players are seeds. For example, a 32-draw International Series tournament would have eight seeds. The seeds are chosen and ranked by the tournament organizers and are selected because they are the players with the highest ranking who also, in the estimation of the organizers, have the best chance of winning the tournament. Seed ranking is sometimes controversial, because it does not always match the players' current ATP ranking.{{sfnp|Hedges|1978|p=259|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Serve and volley|serve and volley}} '''[[Serve and volley]]''':  Method of play to serve and immediately move forward to the net to make a volley with the intent to hit a winner and end the point.{{sfnp|Grasso|2011|p=261|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Serve|serve}} '''[[Serve (tennis)|Serve]]''' (verb and noun. Also '''service''', noun): The starting stroke of each point. The ball must be hit into the opponent's ''service box'', specifically the box's half that is diagonally opposite the server.{{sfnp|Grasso|2011|pp=260\u2013261|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Service box|service box}} '''Service box''': Rectangular area of the court, marked by the sidelines and the service lines, that a serve is supposed to land in.{{sfnp|Shine|2003|p=113|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Service game|service game}} '''Service game''': With regard to a player, the game in which the player is serving (e.g. \"Player A won a love service game\" means that Player A has won a game where (s)he was serving without the opponent scoring).\n* {{Anchor|Service line|service line}} '''Service line''': A line that runs parallel to the net at a distance of 21&nbsp;ft (6.4m) and forms part of the demarcation of the ''service box''.{{sfnp|Hedges|1978|p=260|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Set point|set point}} '''Set point''': Situation in which the player who is leading needs one more point to win a set. If the player is serving in such a situation, (s)he is said to be \"serving for the set\".{{sfnp|Grasso|2011|p=261|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Set|set}} '''Set''': A unit of scoring. A set consists of games and the first player to win six games with a two-game advantage wins the set. In most tournaments a ''[[#tiebreak|tiebreak]]'' is used at six games all to decide the outcome of a set.{{sfnp|Grasso|2011|p=261|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Shamateurism|shamateurism}} '''Shamateurism''': Amalgamation of 'sham' and 'amateurism', derogatory term for a custom that widely existed before the open era where an amateur player would receive financial remuneration to participate in a tournament in violation of amateur laws.{{sfnp|Robertson|1974|p=316|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Shank|shank}} '''Shank''': Significantly misdirected shot, the result of hitting the ball in an unintentional manner, typically with the frame of the racket. Such shots typically land outside the court, however, it is possible to hit a shank that lands validly in the court.\n* {{Anchor|Shot clock|shot clock}} '''Shot clock''': A publicly displayed clock which is used in between points to ensure that a player serves within 25 seconds. First used in grand slams at the Australian Open in 2018.\n* {{Anchor|Singles Sticks|Singles sticks|singles sticks}} '''Singles sticks''' (or '''[[#net sticks|net sticks]]'''): Pair of poles which are placed underneath the net near the singles sideline for the purpose of raising it for singles play.\n* {{Anchor|Singles|singles}} '''[[Singles (tennis)|Singles]]''': Match played by two players, one on each side of the court. A singles court is narrower than a doubles court and is bounded by the inner sidelines and the baseline.{{sfnp|Hedges|1978|p=260|ps=}}{{sfnp|Grasso|2011|p=263|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Sitter|sitter}} '''Sitter''': Shot which is hit with very little pace and no spin, which bounces high after landing, thus being an easy shot to ''put away''.{{sfnp|Shine|2003|p=119|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Sledgehammer|Sledgehammer}} '''Sledgehammer''': Two-handed backhand winner down the line.\n* {{Anchor|Slice|slice}} '''Slice''': Shot with underspin (backspin), or a serve with sidespin. Groundstrokes hit with slice tend to have a flat trajectory and a low bounce.{{sfnp|Hedges|1978|p=260|ps=}}{{sfnp|Grasso|2011|p=263|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Smash|smash}} '''[[Smash (tennis)|Smash]]''': Strongly hit ''[[#overhead|overhead]]'', typically executed when the player who hits the shot is very close to the net and can therefore hit the ball nearly vertically, often so that it bounces into the stands, making it unreturnable.{{sfnp|Hedges|1978|p=260|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Spank|spank}} '''Spank''': To hit a groundstroke flat with a lot of pace.\n* {{Anchor|Sparring Partner|Sparring partner|sparring partner}} '''Sparring partner''': see ''[[#hitting partner|hitting partner]]''\n* {{Anchor|Special Exempt|Special exempt|special exempt}} '''Special exempt''' (\"'''SE'''\"): Players who are unable to appear in a tournament's qualifying draw because they are still competing in the final rounds of a previous tournament can be awarded a spot in the main draw by special exempt.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.atpworldtour.com/-/media/files/rulebook/2017/2017-atp-rulebook_chapter-vii.pdf|title=ATP Rule Book|publisher=atpworldtour.com|accessdate=3 May 2018}}</ref>\n* '''Special ranking''' (\"'''SR'''\"): See ''[[#protected ranking|protected ranking]]''.\n* {{Anchor|Spin|spin}} '''Spin''': Rotation of the ball as it moves through the air, affecting its trajectory and bounce. See ''[[#backspin|backspin]]'', ''[[#topspin|topspin]]'', and ''[[#underspin|underspin]]''.{{sfnp|Hedges|1978|p=260|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Split step|split step}} '''Split step''': a footwork technique in which a player does a small bounce on both feet, just as the opponent hits the ball. This lets the player go more quickly in either direction.{{sfnp|Shine|2003|pp=122\u2013123|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Spot Serving|Spot serving|spot serving|Spot Server|Spot server|spot server}} '''Spot serving'''/'''spot server''': Serving with precision, resulting in the ball landing either on or near the intersection of the center service line and service line or singles tramline and service line.\n* {{Anchor|Squash Shot|Squash shot|squash shot|}} '''Squash shot''': Forehand or backhand shot typically hit on the run from a defensive position, either with slice, or from behind the player's stance.\n* {{Anchor|Stance|Stance}} '''Stance''': The way a player stands when hitting the ball\n* {{Anchor|Stick the Volley|Stick the volley|stick the volley}} '''Stick volley''': Volley hit crisply, resulting in shot with a sharp downward trajectory.\n* {{Anchor|Stiffness|stiffness}} '''Stiffness''' (or '''racket stiffness'''): The resistance of the racket to bending upon impact with the ball.{{sfnp|Shine|2003|pp=123\u2013124|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Stop volley|stop volley}} '''Stop volley''': A softly-hit volley which absorbs almost all the power of the shot resulting in the ball dropping just over the net.{{sfnp|Shannon|1981|p=547|ps=}}{{sfnp|Shine|2003|p=124|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Stopper|stopper}} '''Stopper''': Player who will not win or go deep in a tournament but is good enough to stop a top seed from advancing.\n* {{Anchor|Straight sets|straight sets}} '''Straight sets''': Situation in which the winner of a match does not lose a set. A straight set may also mean a set which is won by a score of 6-something; i.e. is won at the first opportunity and does not reach five games all.{{sfnp|Shannon|1981|p=547|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|String Saver|String saver|string saver}} '''String saver''': Tiny piece of plastic that is sometimes inserted where the strings cross, to prevent the strings from abrading each other and prematurely breaking.{{sfnp|Shine|2003|p=125|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Strings|strings}} '''[[Strings (tennis)|Strings]]''': Material woven through the face of the racket. The strings are where contact with the ball is supposed to be made.{{sfnp|Shine|2003|pp=124\u2013125|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Stroke|stroke}} '''Stroke''': Striking of the ball.{{sfnp|Hedges|1978|p=260|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Sudden Death tiebreak|Sudden death tiebreak|sudden death tiebreak|Sudden Death|sudden death}} '''Sudden death tiebreak''': Version of the tiebreak played as the best of nine points, with the last being a deciding point to clinch the set. Introduced in 1965 by Jimmy Van Alen as a component of the ''[[#VASSS|VASSS]]''.<ref name=tiebreak/>{{sfnp|Shine|2003|pp=134\u2013135|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Super-Tiebreak|super tiebreak}} '''Super tiebreak''': A ''tiebreak'' variation played to ten points instead of seven; usually used in double to decide a match instead of playing a third set.{{sfnp|Shine|2003|p=127|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Supercoach}} '''Supercoach''': A tennis coach who has had a successful professional career.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.atpworldtour.com/en/news/raonic-krajicek-june-2017|title=Raonic, Krajicek Mutually Part Ways {{!}} ATP World Tour {{!}} Tennis|work=ATP World Tour|access-date=2017-12-10|language=en}}</ref>\n* {{Anchor|Sweetspot|sweetspot}} '''Sweetspot''': Central area of the racket head which is the best location, in terms of control and power, for making contact with the ball.{{sfnp|Shine|2003|p=128|ps=}}\n* '''Swing volley''': See ''[[#drive volley|drive volley]]''.\n\n==T==\n[[File:Tennis ball 01.jpg|thumb|180px|A standard optic yellow ''[[#tennis ball|tennis ball]]'']]\n\n* {{Anchor|Tanking|tanking}} '''Tanking''' (noun: '''tank'''): Colloquial term for losing a match on purpose; or to purposely lose a non-vital set, so as to focus energy and attention on a match-deciding set which could result in a temporary ban such as that encountered by [[Nick Kyrgios]].{{sfnp|Shine|2003|pp=130\u2013131|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Taping it|taping it}} '''Tape it''': To play a shot that hits the tape at the top of the net.\n* {{Anchor|Tennis Ball|Tennis ball|tennis ball|Ball|ball}} '''[[Tennis ball]]''': Soft, hollow, air-filled rubber ball coated in a synthetic fur, used in the game of tennis. The ITF specifies that a tennis ball must have a diameter of 6.54\u20136.86&nbsp;cm (2.57\u20132.70&nbsp;in) and a weight of 56.0\u201359.4g. Yellow and white are the only approved colors at tournament level.{{sfnp|Hedges|1978|p=251|ps=}}{{sfnp|Robertson|1974|p=202|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Tennis Bubble|Tennis bubble|tennis bubble}} '''Tennis bubble''': Indoor tennis facility consisting of a domed structure which is supported by air pressure generated by blowers inside the structure.\n* {{Anchor|Tennis Dad|Tennis dad|tennis dad}} '''Tennis dad''': Father of a tennis player, often used in reference to a parent actively participating in the player's tennis development and/or career.\n* {{Anchor|Tennis Elbow|Tennis elbow|tennis elbow}} '''[[Tennis elbow]]''': Common injury in beginner to intermediate tennis players, possibly due to improper technique or a racket which transmits excessive vibration to the arm.{{sfnp|Robertson|1974|p=329|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Tennis Hall of Fame|tennis Hall of Fame|Hall of Fame|HoF|HOF|hof}} '''Tennis Hall of Fame''': The [[International Tennis Hall of Fame]] located in [[Newport, Rhode Island]], United States. It was established in 1954 and hosts an annual tournament around the induction ceremony.{{sfnp|Grasso|2011|p=144\u2013145|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|The Vineyard of Tennis|The vineyard of tennis|the vineyard of tennis}} '''The vineyard of tennis''': Southern California as characterized by [[Bud Collins]].\n* {{Anchor|Tiebreak|Tie-break|Tie break|Tie-breaker|Tiebreaker}} '''[[Tennis score#Scoring a tiebreak game|Tiebreak]]''': Special game played when the score is 6\u20136 in a set to decide the winner of the set; the winner is the first to reach at least seven points with a difference of two points over the opponent.{{sfnp|Hedges|1978|p=260|ps=}}<ref name=tiebreak>{{cite web|author1=Steve Tignor|title=1970: The Tiebreaker Is Introduced|url=http://www.tennis.com/pro-game/2015/02/1970-tiebreaker-introduced/54116/#.VOoChXzF8rs|publisher=Tennis.com|date=18 February 2015}}</ref>\n* {{Anchor|Tie|tie}} '''Tie''': Synonymous with ''[[#match|match]]'', but used for team competitions such as the [[Davis Cup]] and [[Fed Cup]].\n* {{Anchor|Topspin|topspin}} '''[[Topspin]]''': Spin of a ball where the top of the ball rotates toward the direction of travel; the spin goes forward over the top of the ball, causing the ball to dip and bounce at a higher angle to the court.{{sfnp|Shine|2003|pp=135\u2013136|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Toss|Toss}} '''Toss''': At the beginning of a match, the winner of a coin toss chooses who serves first. In amateur tennis the toss is often performed by spinning the racket.{{sfnp|Hedges|1978|pp=260\u2013261|ps=}}{{sfnp|Robertson|1974|p=330|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Touch|touch}} '''Touch''': Occurs when a player touches any part of the net when the ball is still in play, losing the point.\n* {{Anchor|Tramline|tramline}} '''Tramline''': Line defining the limit of play on the side of a singles or doubles court.{{sfnp|Hedges|1978|p=261|ps=}}{{sfnp|Shine|2003|pp=138\u2013139|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Trampolining|trampolining}} '''Trampolining''': Effect which occurs when striking a ball flat with a racket that is strung at a very loose tension.  Trampolining results in a shot that has a very high velocity.\n* {{Anchor|Tree|tree}} '''Two ball pass''': Passing an opponent that has come to the net with a first shot that causes them trouble on the volley followed up by hitting the second ball by them.\n* {{Anchor|Triple Bagel|Triple bagel|triple bagel}} '''Triple bagel''': Colloquial term for three sets won to ''[[#love|love]]''. See ''[[#bagel|bagel]]''.\n* {{Anchor|Triple Crown|Triple crown|triple crown}} '''Triple crown''': Winning the championship in all three tennis disciplines (singles, doubles and mixed doubles) at one event, especially a Grand Slam tournament.\n* {{Anchor|T|t}} '''T''' ('''the T'''):  The spot on a [[tennis court]] where the center line and the service line intersect perpendicularly to form a \"T\" shape.{{sfnp|Shine|2003|p=132|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Tube|tube}}'''Tube''': (Colloquial term) to deliberately and successfully hit the ball, at the opponent's the body; e.g. \"he tubed his opponent.\"\n* {{Anchor|Tweener racket|tweener racket}} '''[[Tweener racket]]''': a tennis racket of mid-weight, mid-head size and mid-stiffness, often used as a transitional racket for young professionals.\n* {{Anchor|Tweener|tweener|Hot Shot|Hot shot|hot shot}} '''[[Tweener (tennis)|Tweener]]''' (also called '''hot dog''', '''Gran Willy''' or '''Sabatweenie''' \u2014 the last two names after [[Guillermo Vilas]] and [[Gabriela Sabatini]] respectively, who pioneered the shot in the 1970s and 80s): A difficult trick shot in which a player hits the ball between his or her legs. It is usually performed when chasing down a [[lob (tennis)|lob]] with the player's back to the net. Forward-facing tweeners are also sometimes employed, and have been dubbed \"front tweeners\". See also [[#Gran Willy|Gran Willy]] and [[#Sabatweenie|Sabatweenie]].\n* {{Anchor|Twist Serve|Twist serve|twist serve}} '''Twist serve''' (or '''American twist serve'''): Serve hit with a combination of slice and topspin which results in a curving trajectory and high bounce in the opposite direction of the ball's flight trajectory. See also ''[[kick serve]]''.{{sfnp|Shine|2003|p=7|ps=}}\n\n==U==\n* {{Anchor|Umpire|umpire}} '''[[Official (Tennis)#Chair umpire|Umpire]]''' (or '''chair umpire'''): Person designated to enforce the rules of the game during play, usually sitting on a high chair beside the net.{{sfnp|Hedges|1978|p=261|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Underhand service|underhand service|Underhand serve|underhand serve|underhand|Underhand}} '''Underhand serve''' (or '''underarm serve'''): A serve in which the player lobs the ball from below shoulder level.{{sfnp|Shine|2003|p=142|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Underspin|underspin}} '''Underspin''' (or '''backspin''' or '''undercut'''): Spin of a ball where the top of the ball rotates away from the direction of travel; the spin is underneath the ball, causing the ball to float and to bounce at a lower angle to the court.{{sfnp|Shannon|1981|p=548|ps=}}{{sfnp|Shine|2003|pp=142\u2013143|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Unforced error|unforced error}} '''Unforced error''': Error in a service or return shot that cannot be attributed to any factor other than poor judgement and execution by the player; contrasted with a ''[[#Forced error|forced error]]''.{{sfnp|Shine|2003|p=143|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Unseeded player|unseeded player|Unseeded|unseeded}} '''Unseeded player''': Player who is not a ''[[Single-elimination tournament#Seeding|seed]]'' in a tournament.{{sfnp|Shine|2003|pp=143\u2013144|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Upset|upset}} '''Upset''': The defeat of a high-ranked player by a lower-ranked player.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.atpworldtour.com/en/news/cilic-nishikori-stakhovsky-wimbledon-2017-wednesday|title=Kei Nishikori Beats Sergiy Stakhovsky, Who Upset Roger Federer At 2013 Wimbledon {{!}} ATP World Tour {{!}} Tennis|work=ATP World Tour|access-date=2017-12-10|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==V==\n[[File:Tsvetana Pironkova 1, Wimbledon 2013 - Diliff.jpg|thumb|180px|Approaching a forehand [[#volley|volley]]]]\n\n* {{Anchor|Vantage|vantage}} '''Vantage''': Archaic term for ''[[#advantage|advantage]]''.{{sfnp|Shannon|1981|p=548|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|VASSS|vasss}} '''VASSS''': Abbreviation for '''Van Alen Streamlined Scoring System''', an alternative scoring method developed by [[Jimmy Van Alen|James Van Alen]] aimed at avoiding very long matches that can arise under the traditional advantage scoring system. The only element of the VASSS to be adopted by tennis authorities was the ''[[#tiebreak|tiebreak]]''.{{sfnp|Robertson|1974|p=340|ps=}}{{sfnp|Shine|2003|pp=145|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Volley|volley}} '''[[Volley (tennis)|Volley]]''': A shot hit, usually in the vicinity of the net, by a player before the ball bounces on their own side of the court.{{sfnp|Hedges|1978|p=261|ps=}}{{sfnp|Shine|2003|pp=146|ps=}}\n\n==W==\n* {{Anchor|Walkover|walkover|WO|w/o}} '''[[Walkover]]''' (\"'''WO'''\" or \"'''w/o'''\"): Unopposed victory. A [[walkover]] is awarded when the opponent fails to start the match for any reason, such as injury. For a mid-match withdrawal, see ''[[#retirement|retirement]]''.\n* {{Anchor|Western grip|western grip}} '''Western grip''': Type of grip used if a player wants to generate a lot of topspin on the groundstrokes, is created by placing the index knuckle on bevel 5 of the grip.{{sfnp|Shine|2003|pp=147\u2013148|ps=}}{{sfnp|Shannon|1981|p=548|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Whiff|whiff}} '''Whiff''': A stroke in which the player misses the ball completely. Whiffing a serve is considered a fault in an official match.<ref>{{cite web|title=Swings vs. \"Whiffs\"|url=https://www.usta.com/Improve-Your-Game/Rules/Rulings/Swings_vs_whiffs/|website=USTA|publisher=United States Tennis Association|accessdate=22 July 2016}}</ref>\n* {{Anchor|Wide|wide}} '''Wide''': A call to indicate that the ball has landed out of court, beyond the sideline.{{sfnp|Shannon|1981|p=548|ps=}}{{sfnp|Shine|2003|p=149|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Wild Card|Wild card|wild card|WC}} '''[[Wild card (sports)#Professional tennis|Wild card]]''' (\"'''WC'''\"): Player allowed to play in a tournament, even if his or her rank is not adequate or he or she does not register in time. Typically a few places in the draw are reserved for wild cards, which may be for local players who do not gain direct acceptance or for players who are just outside the ranking required to gain direct acceptance. Wild cards may also be given to players whose ranking has dropped due to a long-term injury.{{sfnp|Shine|2003|p=150|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|Winner|winner}} '''Winner''': A shot that is not reached by the opponent and wins the point; sometimes also a serve that is reached but not returned into the court.{{sfnp|Grasso|2011|p=310|ps=}}{{sfnp|Shine|2003|p=153|ps=}}\n* {{Anchor|World Championship Tennis|world championship tennis|WCT}} '''WCT''': Abbreviation for [[World Championship Tennis]], a tour for professional male tennis players established in 1968 which lasted until the emergence of the ATP Tour in 1990. \n* {{Anchor|WTA Finals|WTAF}} '''[[WTA Finals]]''': The annual season-ending tournament featuring eight of the top-ranked women in the world (plus two alternates).\n* {{Anchor|WTA|Women's Tennis Association|wta}} '''WTA''': Abbreviation for [[Women's Tennis Association]], the main organizing body of women's professional tennis; governs the WTA Tour with the largest tournaments for women.{{sfnp|Grasso|2011|pp=310\u2013311|ps=}}{{sfnp|Shine|2003|pp=157\u2013158|ps=}}\n\n==Z==\n* {{Anchor|Zero Pointer|Zero pointer|zero pointer}} '''Zero pointer''': Ranking points received by skipping selected professional tennis tour events which a top ranked player is committed to participate in (mandatory tournaments). Therefore, the player risks getting no points added to his or her ranking even when participating in an alternative tournament in place of the mandatory event.\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Tennis}}\n* [[Tennis shots]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n;Sources\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite book|last=Grasso|first=John|title=Historical Dictionary of Tennis|date=2011|publisher=Scarecrow Press|location=Lanham, Md.|isbn=978-0810872370|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Hedges|first=Martin|title=The Concise Dictionary of Tennis|date=1978|pages=[https://archive.org/details/concisedictionar00hedg/page/251 251\u2013261]|publisher=Mayflower Books|location=New York|isbn=978-0861240128|ref=harv|url=https://archive.org/details/concisedictionar00hedg/page/251}}\n* {{cite book|last=Robertson|first=Max|title=The Encyclopedia of Tennis|year=1974|publisher=Allen & Unwin|location=London|isbn=9780047960420|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|editor-last=Shannon|editor-first=Bill|title=Official Encyclopedia of Tennis|date=1981|publisher=Harper & Row|location=New York [u.a.]|isbn=9780060148966|pages=[https://archive.org/details/unitedstatestenn0000unse/page/272 272\u2013277]|edition=3rd, Revised and updated|ref=harv|url=https://archive.org/details/unitedstatestenn0000unse/page/272}}\n* {{cite book|last=Shine|first=Ossian|title=The Language of Tennis|date=2003|publisher=Carcanet|location=Manchester|isbn=978-1857546330|ref=harv}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wiktionarycat|type=Tennis|category=Tennis}}\n*[http://www.britishtennis.com/newtotennis/glossary/ Glossary of tennis terms at britishtennis.com]\n*[http://www.tennis.com.au/learn/rules-and-scoring/glossary Glossary of tennis terms at Tennis Australia]\n\n{{tennis box}}\n{{Glossaries of sports}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Glossary Of Tennis}}\n[[Category:Tennis terminology| ]]\n[[Category:Glossaries of sports|Tennis]]\n", "name_user": "45.118.106.208", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eB)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Glossary_of_tennis_terms"}
{"title_page": "OJ 287", "text_new": "{{Quasar\n  | name = OJ 287\n  | image = \n  | caption=\n  | epoch = [[J2000]]\n  | ra = {{RA|08|54|48.9}}<ref name=\"ned\">{{cite web\n    | work=NASA/IPAC Extragalactic Database\n    | title=NED results for object OJ +287\n    | url=http://ned.ipac.caltech.edu/cgi-bin/objsearch?objname=OJ+%2B287&extend=no&hconst=73&omegam=0.27&omegav=0.73&corr_z=1&out_csys=Equatorial&out_equinox=J2000.0&obj_sort=RA+or+Longitude&of=pre_text&zv_breaker=30000.0&list_limit=5&img_stamp=YES\n    | accessdate=2008-07-10 }}</ref>\n  | dec = {{DEC|+20|06|31}}<ref name=\"ned\" />\n  | constellation name = [[Cancer (constellation)|Cancer]]\n  | z = 0.306000 <ref name=\"ned\" />\n  | type = [[BL Lac object|BL Lac]]<ref name=\"ned\" />\n  | dist_ly = {{convert|3.5|Gly|Gpc|3|lk=on|abbr=on}}\n  | appmag_v = 15.43<ref>{{cite simbad|title= QSO J0854+2006|accessdate=15 March 2018}}</ref>\n  | names = EGO 0851+202,<ref name=\"ned\" /> 3EG J0853+1941,<ref name=\"ned\" /> RGB J0854+201<ref name=\"ned\" />\n}}\n\n'''OJ 287''' is a [[BL Lac object]] located 3.5 [[1000000000 (number)|billion]] [[light-year]]s away that has produced quasi-periodic optical outbursts going back approximately 120 years, as  first apparent on photographic plates from 1891. It has been seen on photographic plates since at least 1887.<ref name=SnT-2015-01-13>{{cite news |url= http://www.skyandtelescope.com/astronomy-news/black-hole-binary-en-route-merger-0113201423/ |title= Black Hole Binary En Route to Merger? |date= 13 January 2015 |author= Camille M. Carlisle |publisher= [[Sky & Telescope]] }}</ref> It was first detected at radio wavelengths during the course of the [[Ohio Sky Survey]].\n\n==Characteristics==\nIts central [[supermassive black hole]] is [[List of most massive black holes|among the largest known]], with a mass of 18 billion [[solar masses]],<ref>{{Cite journal | last1 = Valtonen | first1 = M. J. | last2 = Lehto | first2 = H. J. | last3 = Nilsson | first3 = K. | last4 = Heidt | first4 = J. | last5 = Takalo | first5 = L. O. | last6 = Sillanp\u00e4\u00e4 | first6 = A. | last7 = Villforth | first7 = C. | last8 = Kidger | first8 = M. | last9 = Poyner | first9 = G. | last10 = Pursimo | doi = 10.1038/nature06896 | first10 = T. | last11 = Zola | first11 = S. | last12 = Wu | first12 = J. -H. | last13 = Zhou | first13 = X. | last14 = Sadakane | first14 = K. | last15 = Drozdz | first15 = M. | last16 = Koziel | first16 = D. | last17 = Marchev | first17 = D. | last18 = Ogloza | first18 = W. | last19 = Porowski | first19 = C. | last20 = Siwak | first20 = M. | last21 = Stachowski | first21 = G. | last22 = Winiarski | first22 = M. | last23 = Hentunen | first23 = V. -P. | last24 = Nissinen | first24 = M. | last25 = Liakos | first25 = A. | last26 = Dogru | first26 = S. | display-authors = 3 | title = A massive binary black-hole system in OJ 287 and a test of general relativity | journal = Nature | volume = 452 | issue = 7189 | pages = 851\u2013853 | year = 2008 | pmid =  18421348| pmc = | url = http://astrophysics.rit.edu/pastjclub/nature06896.pdf|arxiv = 0809.1280 |bibcode = 2008Natur.452..851V }}</ref> more than six times the value calculated for the previous largest object.<ref name=\"newscientist\">{{cite news| url=https://www.newscientist.com/article/dn13166-biggest-black-hole-in-the-cosmos-discovered.html|title= Biggest black hole in the cosmos discovered| date=10 January 2008| publisher= NewScientist.com news service| first= David| last= Shiga}}</ref>\n[[File:BlackHoleDiskFlareInGalaxyOJ287-animation-20200428.webm|thumb|left|Black Hole Disk Flares In Galaxy OJ 287 (animation; 28 April 2020)]]\nThe optical light curve shows that OJ 287 has a periodic variation of 11\u201312 years with a narrow double peak at maximum brightness.<ref>{{cite journal|title=A new model for the periodic outbursts of the BL Lac object OJ287| last=Shi| first=Weizhao| last2=Liu | first2=Xiang | last3=Song | first3=Huagang | journal=Astrophysics and Space Science| volume=310| issue= 1\u20132| pages= 59\u201363| date=2007| doi=10.1007/s10509-007-9413-z|bibcode = 2007Ap&SS.310...59S }}</ref> This kind of variation suggests that it is a [[binary black hole|binary supermassive black hole]] of two black holes of similar size.<ref>{{Cite journal | last1 = Valtonen | first1 = M. J. | last2 = Nilsson | first2 = K. | last3 = Sillanp\u00e4\u00e4 | first3 = A. | last4 = Takalo | first4 = L. O. | last5 = Lehto | first5 = H. J. | last6 = Keel | first6 = W. C. | last7 = Haque | first7 = S. | last8 = Cornwall | first8 = D. | last9 = Mattingly | first9 = A. | display-authors = 3 | title = The 2005 November Outburst in OJ 287 and the Binary Black Hole Model | doi = 10.1086/505039 | journal = The Astrophysical Journal | volume = 643 | issue = 1 | pages = L9\u2013L12 | year = 2006 | pmid =  | pmc = |bibcode = 2006ApJ...643L...9V  | doi-access = free }}</ref> The double-burst variability is thought to result from the smaller [[black hole]] punching through the [[accretion disc]] of the larger black hole every 12 years.<ref name=SnT-2015-01-13/> Until the 2015 discovery of the binary nature of [[PG 1302-102]], this was the best binary black hole candidate known, since 2008.<ref name=SnT-2015-01-13/>\n\nThe smaller [[supermassive black hole]] with a mass of \"only\" 100 million {{solar mass}} orbits the larger one with an observed 11- to 12-year orbital period. The maximum brightness is obtained when the minor component moves through the [[accretion disk]] of the supermassive component at [[apsis#Terminology|perinigricon]].\n\nThe mass was calculated in 2008 by a team led by [[Mauri Valtonen]] of [[Tuorla Observatory]] in Finland.<ref>{{cite news | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/science/nature/7181877.stm | title = Huge black hole tips the scales | date = 2008-01-10 | accessdate = 2008-01-10 | publisher = [[BBC]]}}</ref> The timing of these outbursts allows the [[precession]] of the companion's elliptical orbit to be measured (39\u00b0 per orbit), which allows the mass of the central black hole to be calculated using [[Albert Einstein]]'s principles of [[General relativity]] (see [[Kepler problem in general relativity]]).<ref name=newscientist/>\n\nThe accuracy of this measurement has been called into question due to the limited number and precision of observed companion orbits, but the calculated value will be further refined using future measurements. The companion's orbit is decaying via the emission of [[gravitational radiation]] and it is expected to merge with the central black hole within approximately 10,000 years.<ref name=newscientist/><ref>{{Cite journal | last1 = Valtonen | first1 = M. J. | last2 = Lehto | first2 = H. J. | last3 = Sillanpaa | first3 = A. | last4 = Nilsson | first4 = K. | last5 = Mikkola | first5 = S. | last6 = Hudec | first6 = R. | last7 = Basta | first7 = M. | last8 = Terasranta | first8 = H. | last9 = Haque | first9 = S. | last10 = Rampadarath | first10 = H. | display-authors = 3 | title = Predicting the Next Outbursts of OJ 287 in 2006\u20132010 | doi = 10.1086/504884 | journal = The Astrophysical Journal | volume = 646 | issue = 1 | pages = 36\u201348 | year = 2006 | pmid =  | pmc = |bibcode = 2006ApJ...646...36V }}.</ref>\n\nIn order to reproduce all the known outbursts, a recent study shows that the rotation of the primary black hole has to be 28% of the maximum allowed rotation for a [[Kerr black hole]].<ref>{{cite journal|doi=10.1088/0004-637X/709/2/725|title=Measuring the Spin of the Primary Black Hole in OJ287| last=Valtonen|first= M. J. |last2=Mikkola|first2= S.|author2-link=Seppo Mikkola|last3=Merritt|first3= D.|author3-link=David Merritt|last4=Gopakumar|first4= A.| last5=Lehto|first5= H. J.|last6= Hyv\u00f6nen|first6=T.|last7=Rampadarath|first7=H.|last8= Saunders|first8=R.|last9=Basta|first9=M.|last10=Hudec|first10=R. | display-authors = 3 | journal=The Astrophysical Journal| volume= 709| issue= 1| pages= 725\u2013732|date=February 2010| bibcode=2010ApJ...709..725V|arxiv = 0912.1209}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{WikiSky|z=12}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20150912112348/http://www.caha.es/18-billions-of-suns-support-einstein.html 18 Billions of Suns Support Einstein] ([[Calar Alto Observatory]])\n* [http://www.astro.utu.fi/OJ287MMVI/img/OJ287opticalhistorical.gif Historical lightcurve of OJ 287]\n* [http://astronomy.swin.edu.au/sao/SAO_Observers/OJ287.html Object: OJ 287] (SAO Observers)\n* [http://www.astro.utu.fi/OJ287MMVI/ OJ 287 2005-2008 Project] (Tuorla Observatory)\n* [http://www.centauri-dreams.org/?p=644 A Supermassive Black Hole Pairing] (Centauri Dreams)\n\n{{Sky|08|54|48.9|+|20|06|31|3500000000}}\n{{Stars of Cancer}}\n\n[[Category:BL Lacertae objects]]\n[[Category:Quasars]]\n[[Category:Supermassive black holes]]\n[[Category:Cancer (constellation)]]\n", "text_old": "{{Quasar\n  | name = OJ 287\n  | image = \n  | caption=\n  | epoch = [[J2000]]\n  | ra = {{RA|08|54|48.9}}<ref name=\"ned\">{{cite web\n    | work=NASA/IPAC Extragalactic Database\n    | title=NED results for object OJ +287\n    | url=http://ned.ipac.caltech.edu/cgi-bin/objsearch?objname=OJ+%2B287&extend=no&hconst=73&omegam=0.27&omegav=0.73&corr_z=1&out_csys=Equatorial&out_equinox=J2000.0&obj_sort=RA+or+Longitude&of=pre_text&zv_breaker=30000.0&list_limit=5&img_stamp=YES\n    | accessdate=2008-07-10 }}</ref>\n  | dec = {{DEC|+20|06|31}}<ref name=\"ned\" />\n  | constellation name = [[Cancer (constellation)|Cancer]]\n  | z = 0.306000 <ref name=\"ned\" />\n  | type = [[BL Lac object|BL Lac]]<ref name=\"ned\" />\n  | dist_ly = {{convert|3.5|Gly|Gpc|3|lk=on|abbr=on}}\n  | appmag_v = 15.43<ref>{{cite simbad|title= QSO J0854+2006|accessdate=15 March 2018}}</ref>\n  | names = EGO 0851+202,<ref name=\"ned\" /> 3EG J0853+1941,<ref name=\"ned\" /> RGB J0854+201<ref name=\"ned\" />\n}}\n\n'''OJ 287''' is a [[BL Lac object]] located 3.5 [[1000000000 (number)|billion]] [[light-year]]s away that has produced quasi-periodic optical outbursts going back approximately 120 years, as  first apparent on photographic plates from 1891. It has been seen on photographic plates since at least 1887.<ref name=SnT-2015-01-13>{{cite news |url= http://www.skyandtelescope.com/astronomy-news/black-hole-binary-en-route-merger-0113201423/ |title= Black Hole Binary En Route to Merger? |date= 13 January 2015 |author= Camille M. Carlisle |publisher= [[Sky & Telescope]] }}</ref> It was first detected at radio wavelengths during the course of the [[Ohio Sky Survey]].\n\n==Characteristics==\nIts central [[supermassive black hole]] is [[List of most massive black holes|among the largest known]], with a mass of 18 billion [[solar masses]],<ref>{{Cite journal | last1 = Valtonen | first1 = M. J. | last2 = Lehto | first2 = H. J. | last3 = Nilsson | first3 = K. | last4 = Heidt | first4 = J. | last5 = Takalo | first5 = L. O. | last6 = Sillanp\u00e4\u00e4 | first6 = A. | last7 = Villforth | first7 = C. | last8 = Kidger | first8 = M. | last9 = Poyner | first9 = G. | last10 = Pursimo | doi = 10.1038/nature06896 | first10 = T. | last11 = Zola | first11 = S. | last12 = Wu | first12 = J. -H. | last13 = Zhou | first13 = X. | last14 = Sadakane | first14 = K. | last15 = Drozdz | first15 = M. | last16 = Koziel | first16 = D. | last17 = Marchev | first17 = D. | last18 = Ogloza | first18 = W. | last19 = Porowski | first19 = C. | last20 = Siwak | first20 = M. | last21 = Stachowski | first21 = G. | last22 = Winiarski | first22 = M. | last23 = Hentunen | first23 = V. -P. | last24 = Nissinen | first24 = M. | last25 = Liakos | first25 = A. | last26 = Dogru | first26 = S. | display-authors = 3 | title = A massive binary black-hole system in OJ 287 and a test of general relativity | journal = Nature | volume = 452 | issue = 7189 | pages = 851\u2013853 | year = 2008 | pmid =  18421348| pmc = | url = http://astrophysics.rit.edu/pastjclub/nature06896.pdf|arxiv = 0809.1280 |bibcode = 2008Natur.452..851V }}</ref> more than six times the value calculated for the previous largest object.<ref name=\"newscientist\">{{cite news| url=https://www.newscientist.com/article/dn13166-biggest-black-hole-in-the-cosmos-discovered.html|title= Biggest black hole in the cosmos discovered| date=10 January 2008| publisher= NewScientist.com news service| first= David| last= Shiga}}</ref>\n[[File:BlackHoleDiskFlareInGalaxyOJ287-animation-20200428.webm|thumb|left|Black Hole Disk Flare In Galaxy OJ 287 (animation; 28 April 2020)]]\nThe optical light curve shows that OJ 287 has a periodic variation of 11\u201312 years with a narrow double peak at maximum brightness.<ref>{{cite journal|title=A new model for the periodic outbursts of the BL Lac object OJ287| last=Shi| first=Weizhao| last2=Liu | first2=Xiang | last3=Song | first3=Huagang | journal=Astrophysics and Space Science| volume=310| issue= 1\u20132| pages= 59\u201363| date=2007| doi=10.1007/s10509-007-9413-z|bibcode = 2007Ap&SS.310...59S }}</ref> This kind of variation suggests that it is a [[binary black hole|binary supermassive black hole]] of two black holes of similar size.<ref>{{Cite journal | last1 = Valtonen | first1 = M. J. | last2 = Nilsson | first2 = K. | last3 = Sillanp\u00e4\u00e4 | first3 = A. | last4 = Takalo | first4 = L. O. | last5 = Lehto | first5 = H. J. | last6 = Keel | first6 = W. C. | last7 = Haque | first7 = S. | last8 = Cornwall | first8 = D. | last9 = Mattingly | first9 = A. | display-authors = 3 | title = The 2005 November Outburst in OJ 287 and the Binary Black Hole Model | doi = 10.1086/505039 | journal = The Astrophysical Journal | volume = 643 | issue = 1 | pages = L9\u2013L12 | year = 2006 | pmid =  | pmc = |bibcode = 2006ApJ...643L...9V  | doi-access = free }}</ref> The double-burst variability is thought to result from the smaller [[black hole]] punching through the [[accretion disc]] of the larger black hole every 12 years.<ref name=SnT-2015-01-13/> Until the 2015 discovery of the binary nature of [[PG 1302-102]], this was the best binary black hole candidate known, since 2008.<ref name=SnT-2015-01-13/>\n\nThe smaller [[supermassive black hole]] with a mass of \"only\" 100 million {{solar mass}} orbits the larger one with an observed 11- to 12-year orbital period. The maximum brightness is obtained when the minor component moves through the [[accretion disk]] of the supermassive component at [[apsis#Terminology|perinigricon]].\n\nThe mass was calculated in 2008 by a team led by [[Mauri Valtonen]] of [[Tuorla Observatory]] in Finland.<ref>{{cite news | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/science/nature/7181877.stm | title = Huge black hole tips the scales | date = 2008-01-10 | accessdate = 2008-01-10 | publisher = [[BBC]]}}</ref> The timing of these outbursts allows the [[precession]] of the companion's elliptical orbit to be measured (39\u00b0 per orbit), which allows the mass of the central black hole to be calculated using [[Albert Einstein]]'s principles of [[General relativity]] (see [[Kepler problem in general relativity]]).<ref name=newscientist/>\n\nThe accuracy of this measurement has been called into question due to the limited number and precision of observed companion orbits, but the calculated value will be further refined using future measurements. The companion's orbit is decaying via the emission of [[gravitational radiation]] and it is expected to merge with the central black hole within approximately 10,000 years.<ref name=newscientist/><ref>{{Cite journal | last1 = Valtonen | first1 = M. J. | last2 = Lehto | first2 = H. J. | last3 = Sillanpaa | first3 = A. | last4 = Nilsson | first4 = K. | last5 = Mikkola | first5 = S. | last6 = Hudec | first6 = R. | last7 = Basta | first7 = M. | last8 = Terasranta | first8 = H. | last9 = Haque | first9 = S. | last10 = Rampadarath | first10 = H. | display-authors = 3 | title = Predicting the Next Outbursts of OJ 287 in 2006\u20132010 | doi = 10.1086/504884 | journal = The Astrophysical Journal | volume = 646 | issue = 1 | pages = 36\u201348 | year = 2006 | pmid =  | pmc = |bibcode = 2006ApJ...646...36V }}.</ref>\n\nIn order to reproduce all the known outbursts, a recent study shows that the rotation of the primary black hole has to be 28% of the maximum allowed rotation for a [[Kerr black hole]].<ref>{{cite journal|doi=10.1088/0004-637X/709/2/725|title=Measuring the Spin of the Primary Black Hole in OJ287| last=Valtonen|first= M. J. |last2=Mikkola|first2= S.|author2-link=Seppo Mikkola|last3=Merritt|first3= D.|author3-link=David Merritt|last4=Gopakumar|first4= A.| last5=Lehto|first5= H. J.|last6= Hyv\u00f6nen|first6=T.|last7=Rampadarath|first7=H.|last8= Saunders|first8=R.|last9=Basta|first9=M.|last10=Hudec|first10=R. | display-authors = 3 | journal=The Astrophysical Journal| volume= 709| issue= 1| pages= 725\u2013732|date=February 2010| bibcode=2010ApJ...709..725V|arxiv = 0912.1209}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{WikiSky|z=12}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20150912112348/http://www.caha.es/18-billions-of-suns-support-einstein.html 18 Billions of Suns Support Einstein] ([[Calar Alto Observatory]])\n* [http://www.astro.utu.fi/OJ287MMVI/img/OJ287opticalhistorical.gif Historical lightcurve of OJ 287]\n* [http://astronomy.swin.edu.au/sao/SAO_Observers/OJ287.html Object: OJ 287] (SAO Observers)\n* [http://www.astro.utu.fi/OJ287MMVI/ OJ 287 2005-2008 Project] (Tuorla Observatory)\n* [http://www.centauri-dreams.org/?p=644 A Supermassive Black Hole Pairing] (Centauri Dreams)\n\n{{Sky|08|54|48.9|+|20|06|31|3500000000}}\n{{Stars of Cancer}}\n\n[[Category:BL Lacertae objects]]\n[[Category:Quasars]]\n[[Category:Supermassive black holes]]\n[[Category:Cancer (constellation)]]\n", "name_user": "Drbogdan", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eCharacteristics:adj", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/OJ_287"}
